<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  IOC Worried About Olympic Booze Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A Frenchman and his wine will not be  
parted. That's the latest issue facing Salt Lake City's embattled 
Olympic organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee said Wednesday it was  
concerned about a possible clash between Mormon restrictions on 
alcohol and foreign cultures where beer and wine are part of life. 
</P>
<P>
	Its coordination commission for the 2002 Winter Games asked Salt  
Lake City organizers to request ``with great respect'' that Utah 
authorities allow unfettered alcohol sales in the main press 
center, which will be set up in the gigantic Salt Palace convention 
center downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a Frenchman, I know that a Frenchman kept from his wine  
might get cranky,'' IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelley Thomas, senior vice president for communications for the  
Salt Lake Organizing Committee, the panel would ``make every 
effort'' to gain an exemption from liquor laws for the Salt Palace 
for the two weeks of the games. Such exemptions can be granted for 
convention facilities, but are limited to one a year. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no plans to request similar exemptions for other  
Olympic sites, SLOC spokesman Frank Zang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah officials have repeatedly said that the Olympics would not  
force a relaxation of liquor laws, and the Mormon church, which 
dominates the state's population and politics, has attacked 
requests for changes in the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Mormon teaching forbids alcohol use.  
</P>
<P>
	Phone messages left at the offices of Gov. Mike Leavitt and  
House Speaker Martin Stephens were not immediately returned, and a 
call to Senate President Lane Beattie was not answered. Alcoholic 
Beverage Control Department director Kenneth Wynn was away from his 
office and unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The first visit by IOC leaders to Salt Lake City since the  
bribery scandal broke ends today, and both sides said disputes 
issues were few. 
</P>
<P>
	``Zero surprises,'' Servan-Schreiber said. He compared the  
sessions to ``making wedding plans, but magnified 10 million 
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said SLOC presented reports on sports, environmental  
impact, telecommunications, media operations, marketing and other 
areas. She said no SLOC proposals were rejected, although fine 
tuning was needed on some. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said the two sides discussed sight lines at the Delta  
Center for figure skating, but that no further action was taken. 
Officials are concerned that some seats at the city's biggest 
indoor arena won't have good views of the ice, and skaters 
complained during the world championships there in February that 
they had trouble seeing the fans, which interrupted their rhythm. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas also said SLOC hoped to have its list of Olympic events  
finished by June, with competition schedules done by December. Salt 
Lake City organizers have proposed several new events, including 
skeleton -- a luge-like race where sledders go down the track head 
first -- and women's bobsled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Servan-Schreiber said ``liquor for the bar'' was the issue  
that grabbed the IOC's attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Grocery stores here sell beer, but other alcohol sales are  
restricted to state-run outlets, establishments serving food or 
``social clubs,'' where a customer must be sponsored by a club 
member before imbibing. Often the ``sponsorship'' is no more than a 
nod from the guy on the next barstool, but it's a barrier not seen 
in most of the rest of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC bans alcohol from its own sponsorship program, although  
national and local Olympic committees can sign with brewers and 
vintners. Otherwise, Olympic leaders accept alcohol's presence. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Olympic venues in the past have served beer and wine, and  
the press center -- probably the highest concentration of foreign 
visitors to the games aside from the athletes' village, where wine 
is usually available with meals -- always has a least one place 
where thirsty reporters can belly up, no questions asked. 
</P>
<P>
	In their bids, Salt Lake City organizers took pains to show how  
easy it was to buy a drink here. Tom Welch, the motivator behind 
the bid and now disgraced for his role in the bribery scandal, used 
to tell Olympic leaders, ``If you can't get a drink in Salt Lake 
City, you can't be very thirsty.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
