<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Eyes Limits on N.Korea Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers led by the chairman of the House  
International Relations Committee proposed new restrictions 
Wednesday on a 5-year-old aid program designed to persuade North 
Korea to scale back its nuclear energy program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should be getting more for our money,'' said Chairman  
Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y. The legislation, which goes before 
Gilman's panel, would limit President Clinton's discretion in 
providing money under the program and impose new requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1994 agreement, North Korea agreed to curtail its  
nuclear energy program in exchange for fuel oil for its 
conventional power plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton requested $55 million in his budget for fiscal year 2000  
for the oil program, up from $35 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the State Department, spokesman James P. Rubin criticized  
congressional moves to scuttle or alter the agreement. He said U.S. 
inspection teams were in Pyongyang Wednesday and expect to gain 
access Thursday to an underground site that U.S. officials have 
asked to inspect for weapons development activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the fact that we're getting access ... that should  
take the steam out of some of those ill-advised ideas to throw away 
an agreement that has helped us prevent North Korea from becoming a 
major nuclear power threatening our vital national interests,'' 
Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that some members of Congress have never liked the  
agreement. The administration, he said, would work with Congress to 
iron out concerns but believes the agreement is in the best 
interests of the United States, Japan and South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman and other congressional critics of the program contend  
North Korea has not lived up to its end, citing reports that the 
communist nation may be continuing to develop a nuclear weapons 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	They have also criticized North Korea's 1998 launch of a  
multistage rocket over Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would require North Korea to meet all terms of  
the 1994 agreement, including allowing international inspections of 
suspected nuclear sites. It would also prod Japan and South Korea 
to contribute more to the program. 
</P>
<P>
	And it would permit humanitarian food shipments to North Korea  
only if it could be demonstrated the food ``is not diverted to the 
North Korean military and that North Korea is taking steps to 
regain self-sufficiency in food production.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is also sponsored by Reps. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.;  
John Kasich, R-Ohio; Dan Burton, R-Ind.; Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio.; 
and Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	The House last year voted to block the oil payments, but they  
were restored in later negotiations with the Senate and the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, U.S. aid to North Korea amounts to $235 million a year,  
Gilman said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
