</P>
<P>
	Gates Meets With More Than 100 CEOs  
</P>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Corporate success will hinge increasingly  
on how well information is organized electronically and made 
accessible to workers who need it, Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill 
Gates said today. To merely have a Web site, computers and e-mail 
is no longer enough, Gates said at the third annual Microsoft CEO 
Summit. He said what's important is how the tools are used within a 
company. Gates' keynote address opened a two-day conference of more 
than 100 chief executives from the world's 1,000 biggest 
corporations. He made no mention of the federal antitrust trial 
against Microsoft that is being heard in Washington, D.C. 

</P>
<P>
	New-Look AT&AMP;T Hosts Shareholders  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., having already committed $100 billion  
to acquisitions for its new cable-telephone strategy, is still 
shopping around for investments, the company said today at its 
annual shareholders meeting. Chief executive C. Michael Armstrong 
stressed that AT&AMP;T needs a smooth transition at Tele-Communications 
Inc. and MediaOne Group, the two cable TV companies already being 
acquired. AT&AMP;T president John Zeglis added that the company will 
likely make more investments in foreign companies, as it has in 
Canada and Japan, to expand its global network. The company also 
said it has begun testing a new wireless service in Dallas using a 
pizza box-sized receiver for local and long-distance calls. AT&AMP;T 
stock was down 9/16 at 58 9/16 today. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Chip Maker To Give Bonuses  
</P>
<P>
	FOUNTAIN VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Another $20 million bonus will be  
handed out to the 1,000 employees at a computer memory-chip firm 
that boasts a family-style ``we're in it together'' philosophy. 
John Tu and David Sun, co-founders of Kingston Technology Co., told 
employees in memos that the big payoff will come in July, company 
spokeswoman Heather Jardin said today. Tenure and performance 
determine how much each employee gets out of the $20 million bonus. 
She declined to provide other specifics, only saying that ``it's a 
huge range.'' 

</P>
<P>
	US Airways Shareholders OK Bonuses  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- US Airways Group Inc. shareholders  
overwhelmingly approved today an offer to 30 top executives of up 
to 500 percent of their base salary in potential bonus pay. The 
approval came despite complaints from union members, who say their 
salaries have remained stagnant while management's compensation has 
skyrocketed. The 9,000 flight attendants have not had a 
cost-of-living raise since 1996, and they are working under a 
contract that came up for renewal that year. The 10,000 ticket and 
gate agents, who have not had a cost-of-living raise since 1991, 
joined the Communications Workers of America in 1997. US Airways 
shares were at 52 1/8, down 2 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	'Star Wars' Fans Praise New Film  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Force is back: a new Star Wars film for the  
first time in 16 years. Maybe some critics panned the prequel, 
``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' But what one heard 
outside movie houses from Charleston, W. Va., to New York City to 
Los Angeles after midnight and early morning showings was that it 
was worth every hour of waiting to get into a showing and worth the 
years of waiting to witness new Star Wars. Some companies were 
bracing for ``Phantom'' sickouts today as people played hooky to go 
to the movies. 

</P>
<P>
	Italian Regulators Warn Olivetti  
</P>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Italy's stock market regulator warned  
Olivetti SpA to stick to the facts in statements about its hostile 
bid for Telecom Italia SpA. Consob's warning followed a complaint 
to the agency by Telecom Italia, which said statements attributed 
to an adviser to Olivetti could improperly influence the outcome of 
the takeover bid. Olivetti has offered $65 billion for Telecom 
Italia in a tender offer that ends Friday. If successful, it would 
be the largest hostile corporate takeover in Europe. 

</P>
<P>
	Healtheon Talks Merger With WebMD  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Healtheon Corp. said today it is in negotiations  
to merge with WebMD Inc. in a deal that would create a powerful 
Internet health-care site linking doctors, patients and other 
medical services. Healtheon, which went public three months ago, 
has seen its value increase seven-fold and now has a market value 
of about $5.5 billion. The Santa Clara, Calif.-based company 
provides consumers and health-care providers with an easy way to 
monitor insurance claims and get referrals. Doctors also can use 
Healtheon to order supplies and check lab results. Privately held 
WebMD has an Internet site that offers extensive medical 
information, drug prescriptions and other services to both doctors 
and consumers. Healtheon shares were at 80 1/4, up 24 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Tyco Buying Raychem for $2.87 Billion  
</P>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Tyco International Ltd. plans to buy  
Raychem Corp., a designer, manufacturer and distributor of 
electronic components, for about $2.87 billion in cash and stock. 
Tyco International is a diversified manufacturing and service 
company and said Raychem would complement its electronic components 
business under the deal announced today. The boards of both 
companies have unanimously approved the transaction. 

</P>
<P>
	Disaster Losses Higher Than Ever  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shortsighted development policies have  
increased the nation's vulnerability to major natural disasters 
rather than lessening it, a new report warned today. Dennis S. 
Mileti, a University of Colorado sociologist, sees a fundamental 
flaw in the U.S. attitude toward disasters: a fantasy that 
technology can make us safe. Mileti headed a panel of experts who 
spent five years studying U.S. handline of disasters. Disasters 
over the past 20 years have cost the United States more than $500 
billion and the toll is rising, due to an increasingly complex 
society and more people moving to disaster-prone areas, according 
to the report ``Disasters by Design.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-EU Beef Confrontation Lingers  
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The European Union's refusal to accept  
North American beef is jeopardizing the integrity of world trade 
law and will lead to retaliatory sanctions, U.S. Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman warned today. But European Union Agriculture 
Commissioner Franz Fischler, speaking after Glickman to 600 
delegates at the World Meat Congress, insisted that hormonally 
treated U.S. beef ``does threaten human health,'' so the EU ban 
could not be lifted. The 15-nation union has ignored a World Trade 
Organization ruling requiring it immediately to lift its 
10-year-old ban on the hormone-treated beef from America and 
Canada. U.S. officials warn they will retaliate with $202 million 
in extra tariffs on EU imports when the arbitration deadline 
expires June 3. 

</P>
