<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:41:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America, Europe in Beef Trade War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Senior negotiators from the United States  
and European Union say they aren't optimistic of avoiding a 
deepening trade war over the EU's refusal to import hormone-treated 
U.S. beef. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and his European Union  
counterpart, Franz Fischler of Austria, both played hardball in 
public appearances alongside each other at the conclusion Wednesday 
of the World Meat Congress here. 
</P>
<P>
	And the two were locking horns in a Dublin hotel Thursday in  
hopes of narrowing the fundamental divide between them. 
</P>
<P>
	But Glickman conceded beforehand that an EU retreat on the issue  
``doesn't look terribly likely'' soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is threatening to impose $202 million in  
tariffs on EU exports June 3 in retaliation for the EU's rejection 
of a World Trade Organization verdict requiring the 15-nation union 
to begin accepting the U.S. product. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO has three times accepted U.S.-led studies finding  
hormone-treated beef safe, but Fischler insisted that EU-instigated 
research indicated it was unsafe and more thorough studies needed 
to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked whether he thought Americans who ate their domestic  
beef were running a health risk, Fischler replied, ``Yes, 
absolutely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a separate press conference, Glickman said he didn't think  
U.S. consumers would be rattled by the Europeans' fears. ``By and 
large the American public have full confidence that the system is 
safe,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Glickman's chief science adviser, Dr. Ifi Siddiqui, said the  
latest EU scientific claims looked like ``nothing new,'' compared 
to previous material already rejected by WTO panels. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Fischler and Glickman shook hands on the same stage,  
then sparred politely while taking questions from some of the 600 
delegates at the meat conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman said the EU's rejection of the WTO ruling ``risks  
perhaps destroying the entire world trading system.'' He said it 
would be crucial for the EU to accede to the Geneva-based 
organization's ruling, otherwise ``the WTO will cease to have any 
effect whatsoever'' and ``chaos will reign in the global 
marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He emphasized his willingness to see U.S. beef labeled as  
hormone-treated to allow would-be European consumers to weigh 
whether to buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan Glickman mentioned the idea that the consumer should have  
the choice,'' Fischler responded, as his U.S. counterpart notably 
avoided eye contact by pressing his hand to his forehead. ``But we 
can't accept a choice between, let's say, risky or dangerous meat 
and safe meat.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
