<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Appoint Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOMA, Congo (AP) -- Congolese rebels fighting to overthrow  
President Laurent Kabila on Wednesday named a new leader in hopes 
of resolving differences that have paralyzed the rebel movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Emile Ilunga was named the new leader of the Congolese  
Democratic Coalition, replacing Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, a former 
history lecturer who was fired Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ilunga, who is from the southern Katanga Province, had been in  
charge of the movement's health department. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was not expected to have an impact on the  
battlefield, where the rebels rely heavily on Rwandan troops in 
eastern and southern Congo, and Ugandan soldiers in the north. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel leaders have been meeting behind closed doors since Monday  
and were not immediately available for comment. It wasn't clear how 
Ilunga and several other leaders were elected. The rest of the 
government will be named on Thursday, said rebel spokesman John 
Nsana. 
</P>
<P>
	Wamba and his supporters boycotted the meeting, and he accused  
his political rivals, many of whom are former associates of the 
late Zairian dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, of staging a coup. It 
wasn't immediately clear if Wamba will join the new rebel leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Wamba has repeatedly accused fellow rebels of setting the stage  
for the return of politicians who served under Mobutu, whom Kabila 
toppled in May 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels have been divided over their failure to successfully  
organize an administration in the eastern half of Congo that is 
under their control, and to rally popular support behind the 
9-month-old war. 
</P>
<P>
	The new 45-member government will try to balance regional  
representation with representatives from each of the nine provinces 
as well as political and military officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Ilunga, the rebel military chief, Jean-Pierre  
Ondekane, was named the first vice president of the movement, and 
Moise Nyarugabo, an ethnic Tutsi, the second vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ilunga spent 30 years in exile in Brussels, Belgium, from where  
he organized an opposition to former dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, 
until joining Kabila in 1996-97 war that toppled Mobutu. After 
Kabila failed to award him with a promised vice presidency, he 
joined the rebels who took up arms in August 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wamba, who flew in to Goma under the protection of a Ugandan  
company and a battered T-55 tank, remained defiant and appeared in 
a military uniform, dismissing Ilunga's election as illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rwandan and Ugandan political and military officials, who were  
present in Goma, were lobbying for their candidates, although they 
did not take part in the rebel meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations between the two allies have been strained over the  
different approaches of how to defeat Kabila. Uganda appears to 
favor a slower pace of war, which would give more time for 
organizing the rebel administration, while Rwanda seem to want a 
quicker end to an economically exhausting war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
