<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 11:41:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Meets With More Than 100 CEOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Corporate success will hinge increasingly  
on how well information is organized electronically and made 
accessible to workers who need it, Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill 
Gates said today. 
</P>
<P>
	To merely have a Web site, computers and e-mail is no longer  
enough, Gates said at the third annual Microsoft CEO Summit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's how you take those technologies and use them inside the  
company ... that's going to differentiate'' the most effective 
businesses, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates' keynote address, ``Knowledge Workers Without Walls,''  
opened a two-day conference of more than 100 chief executives from 
the world's 1,000 biggest corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	He made no mention of the fededral antitrust trial against  
Microsoft that is being heard in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters watched via a video link from another part of the  
company's sprawling campus in this Seattle suburb. All other 
sessions were closed. A news conference with Gates and some of the 
other CEOs was scheduled in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Building on themes he has emphasized in the past, Gates said  
that making e-mail part of a corporate culture and replacing paper 
forms with electronic outlines are only first steps toward making 
full use of today's technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even what's available right now is vastly underutilized  
throughout the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cutting-edge corporations are converting their offices for  
wireless communications combining voice, pictures and data; 
reducing the number of face-to-face meetings through ad hoc as well 
as prearranged teleconferencing via computer and outfitting 
employees with ``digital dashboards,'' customized on-screen layouts 
a worker can access from any computer, Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	The digital dashboard -- ``your office on any screen,'' as he  
described it -- can be modified both by the employee and by 
executives who might decide everyone should have a given feature, 
be it last month's sales figures or a corporate phone list. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates demonstrated his own digital dashboard, including a  
toolbar featuring buttons for commands he created himself, a panel 
of moving stock quotes, a listing of top news stories on selected 
issues, access to weather maps and real-time photos of his frequent 
travel routes and e-mail ranked by priority, subject and author. 
</P>
<P>
	He also displayed some of the latest devices, including improved  
hand-held devices that instantly convert handwriting on an 
electronic pad into print on a computer screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's going to be a mainstream scenario very soon,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
