<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warner-Lambert's Profit Growth Slows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Warner-Lambert needed help to sell its  
promising new cholesterol lowering drug Lipitor, it turned to rival 
pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer agreed to take some of Lipitor's profits, and eventually  
allow Warner-Lambert to co-promote one of its new drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 deal has worked almost too well. Lipitor sales have  
soared beyond anyone's expectations. This year, the drug is 
expected to record $3.3 billion in sales. By 2002, the drug is 
expected to become the world's best-selling medication. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, its time for Pfizer fulfill its quid pro quo.  
</P>
<P>
	But that's proving tricky because it is doubtful that Pfizer has  
a drug under development with the potential to do as well as 
Lipitor, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner Lambert officials said they are in negotiations with  
Pfizer, and expect to complete them in the next two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``A quid for a drug like Lipitor is not easily found,'' Lodewijk  
J.R. de Vink, Warner-Lambert's chairman and chief executive 
officer, said at a meeting with analysts on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer has several promising drugs in its pipeline, including  
the first type of inhaled insulin. But figuring out which drug will 
become a mega-blockbuster like Lipitor is fraught with risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting a piece of a future Pfizer drug is a critical move for  
Warner-Lambert, particularly as pressure mounts on the company to 
sustain strong earnings growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert said Tuesday that its profit growth would slow  
from 30 percent this year to 20 percent in 2000. That figure is on 
the low end of Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert's top officials said the profit growth would  
decelerate because the company is dramatically bigger than before, 
and it plans to puts more money into research and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the slowdown, Warner-Lambert's 20 percent growth should  
still be among drug industry leaders, de Vink said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts are expecting an earnings per share increase of 30  
percent, or $1.92 per share, in 1999, which de Vink said the 
company would meet. The growth will decrease to 20 percent in 2000, 
said de Vink, who did not provide a specific earnings-per-share 
figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts were expecting the company's profit growth to be in the  
20 percent to 25 percent range. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pure statistics,'' de Vink said. ``Anyone who thinks we  
can continue accelerating growth when you put billions on top of 
billions in sales, is not taking a realistic view of the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert wants co-marketing rights from Pfizer for a drug  
expected to have at least $1 billion in sales, de Vink said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Lamberton, an analyst with HSBC Securities, said the  
problem may be that Warner-Lambert may be pushing for marketing 
rights to more than one Pfizer drug to get a return on par with 
Lipitor's sales. But, he said, Pfizer may want to limit 
Warner-Lambert to just one. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner Lambert's sales have risen from $8.2 billion in 1997 to  
$10.2 billion last year. Net income jumped from $870 million in 
1997 to $1.25 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the profit growth slowing could hurt the stock  
price, which some said is among the cheapest in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market does not like decelerating earnings per share  
growth even for a company like Warner-Lambert,'' said Hemant Shah, 
an analyst with HKS &AMP; Co in Warren, N.J. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
