<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reports Serb Troop Desertions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vigorously defending his Kosovo policy,  
President Clinton said Wednesday NATO airstrikes were ``the best 
available way'' to retaliate against Serb massacres of ethnic 
Albanians. The State Department produced vidotape and surveillance 
photographs it said verified the massacres. 
</P>
<P>
	The alternative to the NATO campaign, Clinton said, would have  
been ``sitting on my hands, letting those people be butchered and 
thrown out of their homes and plundered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several hours after Clinton spoke at a Democratic Party  
fund-raiser in New York, the State Department exhibited videotape 
taken with a home camera by an Albanian villager purporting to show 
that Serbs had intercepted a group of elderly men at Izbica in 
mid-April and massacred them. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the film  
confirmed U.S. surveillance photographs that the Yugoslav 
government had dismissed as forgeries. The film is evidence of war 
crimes and will be submitted to an international tribunal at The 
Hague, Netherlands, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed to three rows of graves and said they had been dug by  
the villagers. Rubin also said there were eyewitnesses to the 
atrocities. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department also reported at least 500 Serb soldiers  
had deserted in the Serbian province of Kosovo, and said it was a 
sign that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was ``feeling the 
heat'' of the 8-week-old air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, in reporting Serb desertions, said some of the soldiers  
went home to join families demonstrating against the Belgrade 
government. He cited ``credible reports'' without identifying them. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman said the desertions Tuesday were more significant  
than earlier ones because ``it involved entire units.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic himself may now see the writing on the wall and may  
be looking for a way out of the catastrophe that he has created,'' 
Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, ``I think you're  
seeing, almost anyplace you look now, signs of problems for 
Milosevic. You have now demonstrations in three different towns 
where he's having to divert troops to go and try to quell these 
internal demonstrations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Armed Service Committee, meanwhile, voted to impose  
new spending restrictions on Clinton's conduct of the military 
operation. Democrats denounced the GOP-led move as sending 
conflicting messages to U.S. troops. 
</P>
<P>
	On the diplomatic front, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe  
Talbott said there was ``really no fundamental difference'' between 
the United States and Russia on how to settle the conflict in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is that there is somebody else who is not  
participating in the meetings, of course, and that's Mr. Milosevic 
and the leadership in Belgrade,'' Talbott said. ``They understand, 
I think, clearly what is necessary to bring about a suspension of 
hostilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott spoke in Helsinki, Finland, after two days of talks with  
the Russian mediator Viktor Chernoymyrdin, who was in Belgrade on 
Wednesday. Talbott and Chernomyrdin are due to resume talks in 
Moscow on Thursday along with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, 
who had joined negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia opposes the NATO bombing and has urged a suspension while  
Milosevic considers demands by the U.S. and its allies that he 
withdraw virtually all of his troops from Kosovo and permit 
refugees to return home under NATO protection. Milosevic has shown 
no sign of accepting the U.S. and NATO demands. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in a passionate defense of his actions in Kosovo, said  
he knew ``a lot of people have questioned what I have done and how 
I have done it in Kosovo. All I can tell you, is I'm convinced I've 
done the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he has worked hard during the past six years  
``to be a force for peace,'' from Northern Ireland to the Middle 
East to the Balkans. And he said he found it ironic that ``in this 
great modern world we live in, we still can't figure out what to do 
about genocide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would far rather be here today answering the questions that  
I have to answer to the American people and to the press about what 
we have done and why we have done it and how we've done it, than 
... if I were sitting on my hands letting those people be butchered 
and thrown out of their homes and plundered and their records 
erased,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
