<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Reports Serb Desertions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As many as 500 Serb soldiers have deserted in  
Kosovo, a sign that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is 
``feeling the heat'' of NATO airstrikes, the State Department said 
today. Some of the soldiers went home to join families 
demonstrating against the Belgrade government, spokesman James P. 
Rubin said, citing ``credible reports'' without identifying them. 
He said the desertions ``involved entire units, all of one 
battalion, perhaps much of additional battalions.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Envoy Calls for Bombing Halt  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin  
urged both NATO and the Yugoslav army today to ``stop the bombings 
and make a pause.'' Chernomyrdin flew to Belgrade today to meet 
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and was likely to 
discuss details of the latest peace proposal meant to end the 
Kosovo conflict. Meanwhile, Yugoslavia's news agency claimed that 
NATO missiles caused ``great'' damage and the deaths of four people 
in Serbia. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Approves New Prime Minister  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's parliament handed Boris Yeltsin another  
victory today, approving loyalist Sergei Stepashin as new prime 
minister just days after the Russian president fired Premier 
Yevgeny Primakov and faced down an impeachment attempt. Stepashin 
said urgent measures were needed to kick-start the country's 
stalled economy. He promised to reinvigorate Russian industry, 
especially the military-industrial complex, and to 
``decriminalize'' the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs NY Transportation Hub  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton urged Congress today to  
approve $60 million for converting a New York post office into a 
massive transportation hub reminiscent of the city's grand but 
demolished Penn Station. The president took part in a ceremony 
launching the redevelopment of the 1.4 million-square-foot James A. 
Farley Post Office into a new Pennsylvania Station terminal with 
access to Amtrak's high-speed train, commuter and subway rails, as 
well as airports, buses and taxis. 

</P>
<P>
	Reporter's AIDS Test Is Negative  
</P>
<P>
	OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) -- A blood test has found that a former  
reporter who was fired for writing fictitious columns about her 
health does not have AIDS as she once claimed, the 
Messenger-Inquirer reported today. Kim Stacy was fired by the 
Owensboro newspaper May 10 after she admitted that five columns she 
wrote detailing her battle against terminal brain cancer were 
fabrications. At the time of her dismissal, she said she lied in 
the columns to avoid revealing she had AIDS. 

</P>
<P>
	Conservatives Eye Third Party  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Bob Smith  
says conservative members of the GOP may move to start a third 
party because they believe too many Republicans are abandoning the 
conservative planks of the party's platform. Smith, a conservative 
senator from New Hampshire, said conservatives are frustrated about 
stands on gun rights, national defense, school prayer, low taxes 
and opposition to abortion. 

</P>
<P>
	Accused Nazi May Lose Citizenship  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department today renewed its court  
battle to strip U.S. citizenship from John Demjanjuk, an alleged 
Nazi death camp guard who escaped a death penalty in Israel when 
evidence arose that he was a victim of mistaken identity. The 
department's Nazi-hunting Office of Special Investigations, which 
was criticized by a U.S. appellate court for ``reckless'' 
withholding of evidence that might have cleared Demjanjuk in the 
earlier case, filed a new complaint in U.S. District Court in 
Cleveland, where the 79-year-old retired auto worker lives. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: Microsoft Browser Used More  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a turnaround, almost 60 percent of  
companies in a survey released today say they now use Microsoft's 
Internet browser. Microsoft aggressive push to persuade consumers 
to use its Internet software rather than one made by rival Netscape 
is at the core of the government's antitrust trial, scheduled to 
resume June 1. A survey in October from the same research company -- 
cited as evidence in the trial -- indicated that 60 percent of 
companies used Netscape's software. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 50.44  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher in erratic trading today as  
investors pondered the market's next move following the Federal 
Reserve's warning on inflation. The Dow Jones industrial average 
closed up 50.44 points at 10,887.39. On the NYSE, gainers led 
losers 1,761-1,275. The Nasdaq composite index rose 19.05 to 
2,577.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Beat Pirates  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Brian Jordan hit a sixth-inning grand slam off s  
top onlineFrancisco Cordova to give the Atlanta Braves a 7-3 win 
today over the Pittsburgh Pirates. Tom Glavine (3-4) allowed three 
runs and five hits in seven innings for the Braves, who won their 
fourth in a row and swept the three-game series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

</P>
</TEXT>
