<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:32:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catholic Univs. To Tighten Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America's Roman Catholic colleges and  
universities are trying to get the U.S. bishops to soften a plan to 
assert tighter control over the nation's 240 church-related 
campuses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities said the  
church should recognize that the schools are governed by academic 
expectations and secular law and that their survival depends on 
continued public funding. 
</P>
<P>
	In a draft issued last year, the bishops proposed to require  
that every university president take an oath of church fidelity, 
that Catholics constitute a majority of faculty members if 
possible, and that local bishops have the power to approve 
appointments of theology professors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a counterproposal posted on the Internet over the weekend,  
the Catholic colleges and universities suggested that all three 
measures be removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee that drafted the bishops' proposal has received  
more than 100 proposed amendments from bishops and educators. It 
will consider these at a June 28-9 meeting in Washington. The 
committee plans to bring a revised version for debate and decision 
by the full U.S. hierarchy in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the bishops' committee, Bishop John Leibrecht of  
Springfield, Mo., said that all the proposed changes ``will be 
taken seriously by the committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``We're looking for a way, agreed upon by bishops and  
universities and the Vatican, that will better ensure the Catholic 
nature of our institutions of higher education, even as they 
continue to participate in the broader context of American higher 
education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Joseph O'Hare, president of Jesuit-related Fordham  
University in New York City, said he is optimistic that the bishops 
will issue a final text that educators can live with. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, the Vatican issued a decree asserting its ultimate  
right to intervene in any campus dispute and declaring that 
colleges have academic freedom only ``within the confines of the 
truth and the common good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vatican officials and some U.S. Catholics have been bothered by  
criticisms of church policy from teachers at church colleges. This 
month, Catholic conservatives protested the abortion-rights views 
of 15 commencement speakers at Catholic colleges, among them 
presidential hopeful Bill Bradley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
