<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Character Development Panel Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to last month's high school  
shootings in Colorado, the Senate approved creation of a national 
Commission on Character Development on Wednesday to study the 
impact of cultural influences on good citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel -- to include one student and one parent among 36  
members -- would have two years to present Congress with 
recommendations for legislation. The provision was approved by 
voice vote -- and attached to legislation that has become the focus 
of a fierce struggle over gun control since last week. 
</P>
<P>
	That struggle continued during the day as Democrats sought a  
vote on re-designed legislation they said would close a loophole 
that now allows some sales at gun shows to take place without a 
background check. Republicans said that even as redrafted, the 
measure was unacceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	``It eliminates all unnecessary bureaucratic paperwork and red  
tape that was purportedly conained in original amendment,'' argued 
Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said records of background checks would be expunged  
after 90 days, a gesture to law-abiding gun owners who fear 
creation of a national gun registry. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., said the proposal would allow  
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to impose a new fee on 
gun purchasers. He also said it would give the government three 
days to complete the background check -- by which time the gun show 
would have ended. 
</P>
<P>
	A vote on the proposal was postponed as the two sides engaged in  
a series of back-room negotiations on the legislation, which has 
been pending on the Senate floor since last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The national commission was part of an amendment introduced by  
Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. The proposal underscored an effort by 
Republicans to turn attention toward cultural influences on young 
people, particularly in the wake of the shootings in Littleton, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission would be charged with studying ``the impact of  
current cultural influences ... on the process of developing and 
instilling the key aspects of character, which include 
trust-worthiness, honesty. integrity, an ability to keep promises, 
loyalty, respect, responsibility, fairness, a caring nature and 
good citizenship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel would include members of the clergy as well as  
representatives of law enforcement, the information industry and 
the entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to Republicans, Democrats have chosen to place more  
emphasis on gun control issues as the Senate grapples with a 
response to last month's high school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the GOP-controlled Senate rejected a Democratic call  
for mandatory background checks for all gun show purchasers, and 
approved a Republican alternative calling for optional checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Within 24 hours, Republicans backpedaled under pressure, and  
approved a substitute that they said would make background checks 
mandatory at shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said that measure contained a loophole, and would  
continue to permit unlicensed dealers to sell weapons without 
conducting a background check on the purchaser. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, they said it had opened a new loophole by  
permitting individuals to sell their guns at pawnshops and reclaim 
them without a check. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need this amendment to close the gun show loophole once and  
for all,'' Lautenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders were hoping to line up the votes to defeat  
that proposal, and efforts were underway to draft a GOP proposal 
that reversed the pawnshop provision but left the gun show 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate struggle, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, argued at  
length against a proposal by Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., to give 
school officials greater leeway in disciplining students with 
disabilities who bring guns to schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Harkin refused to agree to limit debate, at one point telling  
inquiring Republicans he needed to continue speaking ``Because I am 
so poor at getting across my point, it seems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
