<DOCNO> APW19990519.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:31:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alan Greenspan Contributes / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Alan Greenspan contributes to American society  
in many ways, one of which involves the public's economic health, 
while another limits itself to a vigorous segment of the private 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The first and by far the more important role is in his capacity  
as chairman of the Federal Reserve, a position that grants him and 
his board of governors the power to raise or lower interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	By most measures, especially the success of the U.S. economy  
during the 1990s, the chairman is awarded gold stars for deftly 
finding a safe lane between recession and inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	But because of the style in which he performs this role he also  
provides a service to that vast industry based on trying to dope 
out what the Fed will do and what the consequences might be. 
</P>
<P>
	This the chairman accomplishes by speaking and acting in a way  
that keeps everyone on edge, never certain of what the Fed will do 
and leaving much of the message open to interpretation. A 
predecessor came up with a term for such tactics -- ``constructive 
ambiguity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Interpreting Fed messages, such as the one it delivered this  
week, helps provide employment for thousands of economists and 
market analysts who will expend millions of words dissecting their 
significance. 
</P>
<P>
	They will issue interoffice flashes to brokers, update their  
Internet sites to reflect the latest nuances, mail lengthy 
advisories to clients, issue special editions of their newsletters. 
</P>
<P>
	They will explain how the Fed's comments could mean ``good news  
on the one hand but bad news on the other,'' and that while ``we 
remain optimistic (or pessimistic), one never really can be sure,'' 
and that ``our advice is to maintain positions until the air 
clears.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From one 134-word Fed statement, they will find enough yeast for  
millions of words to hundreds of thousands of subscribers and 
clients who pay the highest per-word price in the writers' market. 
</P>
<P>
	The gist of the Fed statement issued Tuesday was that demand in  
the U.S. economy is growing faster than the supply of goods and 
services, notwithstanding the growth of productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Increases in productivity, or output per hour, have for months  
enabled workers to make real gains in take-home pay while allowing 
producers to supply goods without price increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk of that balance getting out of whack is such, said the  
Fed, that it presents the potential for a buildup of inflationary 
pressures, a suggestion that is hardly new. 
</P>
<P>
	It is well known that the Fed's antidote for such pressures is  
to nudge interest rates higher, hopefully allowing supply to catch 
up with demand. It is equally well known that Wall Street abhors 
such action, since it can also deflate stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On the surface, the Fed's message might seem pointedly clear,  
but -- a big ``but'' -- it didn't say for certain that it would 
indeed raise rates. And that gap is where analysts and forecasters 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether or not they have much worthwhile to say isn't the point.  
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street wants to know what's next, and in the absence of any  
factual information about that great unknown, various opinions are 
eagerly sampled and maybe acted upon. 
</P>
<P>
	Hey, it's a living.  

</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv PMs Thursday, May 20    	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:52:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 30 in Early Trading / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened higher. The Dow Jones  
industrial average is up 30 points in today's early going. 
Advancers on the New York Stock Exchange hold a nearly 2-1 lead 
over decliners. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq Composite Index is up 11 points and the S-and-P 500  
Index is up five points. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say stocks lack direction right now, but that the  
market may be showing some relief following the Fed's meeting 
yesterday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the central bank signaled a rate hike may be on the  
way, it chose not to bump up short-term rates yesterday. 
</P>
<P>
	And since the bond market had already priced in a move by the  
Fed, some market-watchers say there may now be a little room to 
move higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street also gets the chance today to react to earnings  
reports from Dell Computer, Applied Materials and Lycos. 

</P>
</TEXT>
