<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inventors Scammed of $60 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Thousands of inventors who dreamed of  
bringing their ideas to consumers were cheated out of $60 million 
by a group that promised to patent and market their designs, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people at a network of companies swindled about 34,000  
inventors, prosecutors said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The patenting and marketing services they provided were  
worthless,'' said U.S. Attorney Donald Stern. ``The big dreams of 
small inventors were exploited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In federal indictments unsealed Tuesday, prosecutors named  
Ronald Boulerice, 60, as leader of the network. He was president 
and owner of American Inventors Corp., which closed in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Boulerice also controlled American Institute for  
Research and Development, Massachusetts Patent Services, Washington 
Financial Group, and United Patent and Trademark Services. The 
other individuals charged occupied a range of positions for the 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Boulerice pleaded innocent to charges that include mail fraud,  
conspiracy, money laundering and tax evasion. He faces up to 135 
years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies at the center of the investigation sent mass  
mailings, promising to help inventors patent and market their 
inventions. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the inventors came up with such ideas as a  
man's suit that could be ``air conditioned'' with cool water, a 
tritium night-vision scope for rifles, and a ``binge buster fork'' 
with a tiny timer that signals when to stop eating. 
</P>
<P>
	``My guess is in these 34,000, there were probably some very  
good ideas,'' Stern said. ``I'm not sure about the air-conditioned 
suit.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
