<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Shane Wants De La Hoya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	He calls himself Sugar, and he wears his hair like another  
fighter who was called Sugar -- one who in the minds of many boxing 
people always will be the sweetest Sugar of them all. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar Shane Mosley, is one of the best fighters in the world,  
but his head still fits his sparring helmet. And he doesn't claim 
to be Sugar Ray Robinson, generally considered the best 
pound-for-pound fighter in history ... or even Sugar Ray Leonard, 
who was no slouch. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosley, however, wants to be worthy of being called Sugar, and  
so far he has been sweet -- 32-0. He has 30 knockouts, and has made 
eight defenses of the IBF lightweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the 27-year-old Mosley wants to move up from the 135-pound  
division in hopes of following the two Sugar Rays as champion of 
the colorful and competitive 147-pound welterweight division. He'd 
like to do it by beating Oscar De La Hoya later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight would be one between boxer-punchers, who shun  
hot-dogging in a boxing age when there isn't enough mustard to go 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not going to happen this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Bob Arum, who promotes De La Hoya, thinks it wouldn't be in his  
fighter's best interest at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The press would jump all over Oscar for fighting somebody  
little,'' Arum said, but didn't close the door entirely on Mosley. 
``If he fights some top welterweights and beats them, then it 
becomes a legitimate fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Mosley, who listens to father Jack, his manager, said if he  
doesn't fight De La Hoya, he will campaign for a time as a junior 
welterweight. He said he is supposed to fight in the 140-pound 
class against an unidentified opponent June 19 in New York, and 
another in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever happens, Mosley said, ``I will never fight again as a  
lightweight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of all, he wants De La Hoya.  
</P>
<P>
	The reason -- besides the prospect of a big payday and having  
trouble making 135 -- is that Mosley is very familiar with De La 
Hoya. He estimates they sparred about 100 rounds as amateurs from 
1989 to 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in the ring with Oscar as an amateur and I know who  
he is,'' Mosley explained, saying he has a thorough understanding 
of De La Hoya's style. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite what Arum says, Mosley could give De La Hoya a real  
fight. He's 5-foot-9, only two inches shorter than De La Hoya, and 
big enough to easily handle 147 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, in this era of weigh-ins a day before the fight, he's  
big enough to be in the 150s by fight time. When he was an amateur, 
Mosley fought at 139 pounds. De La Hoya won his 1992 Olympic gold 
medal at 132. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Duran was 5-7. Back in 1978, he relinquished the  
lightweight title after a seven-year reign. Two years later, he 
outpointed the 5-10 Leonard for the WBC welterweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1938, Henry Armstrong, the featherweight champion, moved up  
from 126 pounds to challenge welterweight champ Barney Ross. 
Armstrong, who weighed 133 1/2 pounds, 13 1/2 under the class limit, won 
a unanimous decision. 
</P>
<P>
	In 19 successful defenses, Armstrong weighed less than 140  
pounds 19 times. 
</P>
<P>
	It might be better for De La Hoya to fight ``little'' Shane  
Mosley now, before he settles in as a bona fide welterweight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
