<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged in Grave Robbing Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Tiffany glass expert teamed up with a grave  
robber to sell a 9-foot stained glass window stolen from a 
mausoleum, according to a federal indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Alastair Duncan, 57, had worked as an adviser to the FBI,  
various police departments and Christie's auction house, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan was charged Tuesday with conspiracy, transporting stolen  
property, witness tampering and structuring the sale of the art to 
evade paying taxes. If convicted, he could face a maximum of 10 
years in prison on the most serious charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The grave robber was not identified or charged.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is the government's day,'' said Duncan's lawyer, Peter  
Vigeland. ``We look forward to the opportunity to contest these 
charges in court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Duncan first crossed paths with the grave robber  
last year, when the thief wanted to sell the window he had stolen 
about seven years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The grave robber took the glass from the Salem Fields cemetery,  
on the border of Brooklyn and Queens, and offered to sell it to a 
middleman, who contacted Duncan, according to the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan, aware that the window had been stolen, bought it through  
a middleman for $60,000 and sold it to a buyer in Japan for 
$219,000, prosecutors alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Mausoleums and cemeteries are inviting targets for the theft of  
glass created by the late Louis Comfort Tiffany because they often 
have little or no security. The potential payout for the glass is 
great because so much of the artist's work was left in churches and 
mausoleums, leaving little to circulate in the art world. 
</P>
<P>
	The grave robber had worked in a cemetery and kept master keys  
for a number of cemeteries when he left, the indictment said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan also asked the grave robber to shop for special orders,  
prosecutors alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the thief found a large Tiffany stained-glass window in  
a mausoleum in Westchester County, Duncan allegedly turned it down. 
</P>
<P>
	He said ``his guy'' needed a window that was bigger and had more  
trees, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan was released on $100,000 bond, with arraignment set for  
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
