<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen in early  
trading Thursday following its advance Wednesday on Wall Street. 
Japanese stocks rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 124.40 yen in early trading, up 0.70 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
124.21 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 76.79 points,  
or 0.48 percent, to 16,204.97 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Wednesday, the index shed 250.44 points, or 1.53 percent. The 
Nikkei has lost 819.19 points over the past five full trading days. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar strengthened following the  
release of the Bank of Japan's monthly report, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the report, the central bank reaffirmed that although the  
economy appears to have stopped deteriorating, no signs of recovery 
can be seen. The report also noted that the yen has weakened 
recently on interest rate moves in the United States and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 132.66 yen, up from  
131.60 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices advanced as investors picked up  
shares in technology companies and a number of other exporters 
following the dollar's steep gains against the yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong dollar is good for shares in exporters because it makes  
their products cheaper overseas and increases the value of their 
repatriated earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the rise in New York stocks also boosted sentiment  
in Tokyo. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 50.44 points to 
close at 10,887.39 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among early gainers in Tokyo were blue-chips Sony Corp, Fujitsu  
Ltd., Toyota Motor Corp. and Honda Motor Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 4.10 points, or 0.32 percent, to 1,304.71. The 
TOPIX fell 23.54 points, or 1.78 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.370 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.325 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.15 yen from 101.55 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
