<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Indicted in Spying Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former Australian intelligence official,  
arrested in an FBI sting operation, was indicted Tuesday on charges 
of attempted espionage against the United States, the Justice 
Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury in suburban Alexandria, Va., returned the  
one-count indictment against Jean-Philippe Wispelaere, 28, an 
Australian citizen whose last known address was in Australia. He 
faces a maximum penalty of life in prison, or even death if certain 
conditions, like disclosure of nuclear secrets, are met. 
</P>
<P>
	Wispelaere, an Australian military intelligence official from  
July 1998 until his abrupt resignation Jan. 13, was charged with 
selling secret and top secret U.S. defense documents to undercover 
FBI agents during the last two months. The documents had been 
shared with Australia under U.S.-Australian defense treaties. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment also contained a criminal forfeiture count that  
would require Wispelaere, if convicted, to turn over to the U.S. 
government $120,000 he was paid by undercover FBI agents for nearly 
1,000 classified U.S. defense documents and satellite photographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Wispelaere was arrested Saturday at Dulles International Airport  
outside Washington as he flew in from London for what he believed 
was another meeting with spies from a foreign country. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wispelaere's request, the court appointed attorneys Nina  
Ginsberg and Greg Beckwith to defend him. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a detention hearing Thursday before U.S. Magistrate Judge  
Theresa Buchanan and an arraignment June 1 before U.S. District 
Judge Claude Hilton, both in Alexandria. 
</P>
<P>
	At a secretly videotaped rendezvous in a Bangkok hotel in April,  
Wispelaere told FBI agents, who he thought were spies for a foreign 
country, that he was in ``very dire, dire financial need'' for a 
knee operation and for some problems involving women, according to 
an FBI affidavit filed in court. 
</P>
<P>
	His father said Tuesday that if his son sold U.S. government  
secrets he acted purely out of greed. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with an Australian television station, Claude  
Wispelaere said that if his son sold secrets, ``It's not because 
he's in need of money; it's because of greed. The more money you 
have, the more you want. He was well-paid in his job,'' the father 
told Channel 7 TV in Melbourne. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
