<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Hurt Top Japan Automakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's five leading automakers saw their domestic  
auto production fall in April compared to a year earlier, sapped by 
sluggish demand because of the country's persistent recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the hardest hit was Mitsubishi Motors Corp., which said  
today its production had tumbled 20 percent to 60,527 vehicles. 
Nissan Motor Co.'s output also plummeted, falling 19.1 percent to 
86,580. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's No. 1 automaker, Toyota Motor Corp., fared better,  
seeing its production fall 5.8 percent to 234,612 vehicles. Honda 
Motor Co.'s output fell 7.5 percent to 88,478. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor Corp.'s output tumbled 14.4 percent to 53,635. It  
was the first drop in Mitsubishi's output in four months and the 
first drop in Mazda's in two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the automakers also suffered from nose-diving exports.  
</P>
<P>
	Nissan's exports, for example, tumbled 14.8 percent to 42,737,  
while overseas production also fell 12.4 percent to 75,949. 
Mitsubishi's performance was even worse, with exports dropping 49.3 
percent to 19,447. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the few bright spots in the month's results came from  
Toyota, where exports gained 2.9 percent to 135,692 vehicles and 
overseas production soared 15.6 percent to 142,260. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas production for Mitsubishi also skyrocketed 44.2 percent  
to 62,943 vehicles. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
