<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Dead in Conn. Store Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DANBURY, Conn. (AP) -- A liquor store exploded Wednesday night,  
killing one person, injuring 11 others and knocking out power to 
the neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people were trapped in the rubble of the collapsed two-story  
building. One was brought out alive four hours later. The second 
person was found dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven people were injured, including a 5-year-old boy, said  
Kristine Mascoli, a hospital spokeswoman. Victims included people 
who were inside the downtown area store and others standing 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	One person underwent surgery for multiple injuries. The  
conditions of the other victims were not available. 
</P>
<P>
	The blast blew out the front of the building, which houses  
Venancio's Wine &AMP; Liquor store on the first floor and apartments 
above it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went outside to look at it and the flames were 45 feet  
high,'' said Mark Regner, who owns a nearby used car dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast Utilities said the explosion knocked out power to 1175  
customers in the area. The blast interrupted commuter train service 
between Danbury and New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	It delayed about 500 people and six trains, said Dan Brucker, a  
Metro-North spokesman. Service was restored just before 9 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were investigating reports that a gas leak sparked  
the explosion, but could not yet confirm a cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Danbury is about 60 miles northeast of New York.  




</P>
</TEXT>
