<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic OKs 'Principles' of Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic today accepted the ``principles'' of a Kosovo peace plan. 
But Milosevic insisted in talks with a Russian envoy that the 
details must be negotiated directly with the United Nations. That 
would appear to fall short of Western conditions for halting the 
bombing campaign -- unequivocal acceptance of the international 
plan. Soon after the envoy flew out of the Yugoslav capital 
tonight, NATO warplanes launched their strongest attack in two 
weeks against the Belgrade area. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Defends Kosovo Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today that NATO  
airstrikes were ``the best available way'' to retaliate against 
Serb massacres of ethnic Albanians. The State Department produced 
videotape and surveillance photographs it said verified the 
massacres. The State Department also reported at least 500 Serb 
soldiers had deserted in Kosovo, and said it was a sign that 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was ``feeling the heat'' of 
the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Offers Gun Control Concessions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans offered fresh concessions  
on gun control tonight. A draft amendment circulated by the GOP 
calls for background checks on all purchasers at gun shows, 
including transactions exempted in a proposal that Republicans 
muscled through the Senate last week. The proposal would also 
establish a requirement for a mandatory background check for anyone 
seeking to reclaim their own weapon at a pawnshop. Clinton 
administration and Democrats said the proposal didn't go far enough 
to plug gaps that allow some criminals to obtain weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Quayle Speech Draws Fresh Criticism  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Seven years after his ``Murphy Brown''  
speech, GOP presidential hopeful Dan Quayle touched off a fresh 
round of criticism today with an anniversary address scolding legal 
and media ``elites.'' ``Unfortunately, this aristocracy has bit by 
bit undermined parental authority, weakened school discipline, and 
obstructed moral education,'' he said. The American Bar Association 
accused Quayle of ``scapegoating.'' Quayle also said the news and 
entertainment media were also to blame for a decline in moral 
values by conveying ``counterculture values.'' 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady May Form Sen. Committee  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's close friends and  
advisers expect her to form an exploratory campaign committee next 
month, taking a dramatic step closer to running for the Senate in 
New York. Two longtime associates, both speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said this week the first lady has suggested to them she 
will form the committee, which would allow her to raise and spend 
money while determining whether to seek the seat of retiring 
Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 

</P>
<P>
	Starved Baby's Mom Convicted  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A young mother who blamed breast-feeding  
problems for the death of her emaciated baby son was convicted 
today of criminally negligent homicide. Tabitha Walrond, 21, faces 
up to four years in prison. She was acquitted of the more serious 
charge of manslaughter. Prosecutors said Walrond starved 
2-month-old Tyler in 1997 to spite his father, who left her shortly 
after she got pregnant. The defense said she was a doting mother 
who didn't realize that her surgically reduced breasts were failing 
to nourish her child. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Antibiotic Resistance Growing  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jet-setting Americans who eat chicken and meat  
overseas are bringing back resistance to certain antibiotics used 
to treat stomach upset and other bacterial illnesses, according to 
a study. The study is the first to link Americans' growing 
resistance to antibiotics primarily to foreign travel. Until now, 
scientists believed resistance was growing largely because doctors 
were overprescribing antibiotics. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Thursday. The benchmark  
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 76.79 points to 16,204.97 in 
early trading. In New York Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial 
average closed up 50.44 points at 10,887.39. 

</P>
<P>
	Pacers Take Second Game From 76ers  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The 76ers staged another strong final-minute  
rally tonight, but all they finished with was another close loss, 
85-82 to the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern Conference semifinals. 
The 76ers now trail 2-0 headed to Philadelphia for Games 3 and 4. 
Allen Iverson suffered through a 7-for-28 shooting night for 
Philadelphia and finished with 25 points. Indiana's Rik Smits 
finally found his offense for the Pacers, scoring 25 points. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
