<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russian Envoy Makes No Breakthrough  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the latest effort to end the  
Kosovo crisis, Russia's special envoy made no apparent breakthrough 
in nearly eight hours of talks today with Yugoslavia's president. 
Even as the two men met in Belgrade, air raid sirens sounded over 
the capital. Diplomacy was in high gear elsewhere, with U.S., 
Finnish and Russian negotiators flying in and out of several 
European capitals and a G-8 meeting being held in Germany to try to 
resolve the nearly 2-month-old Kosovo conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Defends Kosovo Policy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vigorously defending his Kosovo policy,  
President Clinton said today NATO airstrikes were ``the best 
available way'' to retaliate against Serb massacres of ethnic 
Albanians. The State Department produced videotape and surveillance 
photographs it said verified the massacres. The alternative to the 
NATO campaign, Clinton said, would have been ``sitting on my hands, 
letting those people be butchered.'' The State Department exhibited 
videotape taken with a home camera by an Albanian villager 
purporting to show that Serbs had intercepted a group of elderly 
men at Izbica in mid-April and massacred them. 

</P>
<P>
	California's Health Care Costs Rise  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Signaling an acceleration of health  
care costs, one of the nation's biggest buyers of employee benefits 
has agreed to an average premium increase of 9.7 percent next year 
with 10 HMOs. The agreements announced by the California Public 
Employees' Retirement System represent the steepest increase since 
1992. CalPERS contracts have a national impact. The pension fund is 
the nation's second-largest buyer of health care behind the federal 
government, and is one of the earliest big buyers to negotiate 
rates for 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Florida Woman Taken Off Life Support  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A Florida woman allegedly shot by her own  
mother is dead after doctors honored her request that she be 
removed from life support. Prosecutors have said that if Georgette 
Smith went through with her plans to die they would pursue murder 
charges against her mother, Shirley Egan. Egan allegedly shot her 
daughter in the neck in March after overhearing talk about putting 
her in a nursing home. Smith was paralyzed from the neck down after 
the shooting. 

</P>
<P>
	TV Blamed in Fiji Teens Eating Woes  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Symptoms of eating disorders have increased  
fivefold among teen-age girls on Fiji since television came to the 
Pacific island nation, a study found. The year TV was widely 
introduced in Fiji in 1995, only 3 percent of girls reported they 
vomited to control their weight, according to the study by Harvard 
researcher Anne Becker. Three years later, 15 percent reported the 
behavior. Fiji has only one TV channel, which shows mostly 
American, Australian and British programs. Favorites include 
``Melrose Place,'' ``ER'' and ``Xena: Warrior Princess.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Project Nixed in NASA Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans today prevailed during debate on a  
$42 billion NASA funding bill in stripping an Internet 
earth-viewing project initiated by Vice President Al Gore. 
Democrats said the elimination of $32 million to continue Gore's 
Triana satellite project was an attempt to embarrass the party's 
2000 presidential front-runner. Gore last year initiated the idea 
of putting a satellite in orbit that would provide 24-hour views of 
the earth for TV viewers and Internet users. 

</P>
<P>
	The Force Is Back  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fans stood in theater lines across the  
country today as the latest installment of the ``Star Wars'' saga 
opened. Theaters scheduled round-the-clock showings and some 
companies decided not to fight the Force -- they sent their 
employees to ``The Phantom Menace,'' which was on schedule to 
shatter Hollywood records. No official box office figures were 
available for the early showings, but movie analysts expected the 
movie to easily top $100 million by the end of the five-day opening 
frame on Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 50.44  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher in erratic trading today.  
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 50.44 points at 
10,887.39. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,761-1,275. The Nasdaq 
composite index rose 19.05 to 2,577.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez Sees Hit Streak End  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The streak is over for Arizona's Luis  
Gonzalez. Gonzalez went 0-for-4 with three strikeouts, ending his 
hitting streak at 30 games, and the San Francisco Giants won 8-3 
today to move back into a tie atop the NL West with the 
Diamondbacks. Gonzalez, who had the longest hitting streak in the 
NL since Jerome Walton of the Chicago Cubs also hit in 30 games in 
1989, became the 12th player to have a hitting streak end at 30 
games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
