<HEADLINE> Florida Manager Returns Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Marlins manager John Boles, who underwent emergency  
back surgery Monday, shocked everyone when he walked into the 
ballpark 90 minutes before Florida's game against the Chicago Cubs 
on Wednesday night and announced he was fit to manage. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles' doctors, who repaired a herniated disc and removed a bone  
that had broken off in a two-hour operation, told him he should 
refrain from any physical activity for two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	General Manager Dave Dombrowski had hoped Boles would be back by  
Thursday at the very earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	Evidently, that didn't deter Boles from checking himself out of  
the Wednesday afternoon -- a day earlier than expected -- to take 
back the reins from interim manager Fredi Gonzalez, who was 0-2 in 
his place. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles received a warm ovation as he brought out the lineup card.  
His next appearance came after starting pitcher Jesus Sanchez 
allowed his second homer and fourth run in the first inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles joined pitching coach Rich Dubee on the mound because  
Sanchez had injured his right hamstring. 
</P>
