<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:32:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at the Nation's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *PHILADELPHIA MAYOR   	
</P>
<P>
	John Street, a black former City Council president trying to  
live down his hot-tempered past, wins Democratic primary over white 
political insider Marty Weinberg. He faces GOP businessman Sam Katz 
for the right to succeed popular Democrat Edward G. Rendell. 

</P>
<P>
 *CHARLESTON MAYOR   	
</P>
<P>
	In West Virginia's capital city, Democrat Jay Goldman, a former  
judge, beat Republican ex-mayor Kent Hall 63 percent to 37 percent. 
Goldman, who had narrowly upset incumbent Mayor Kemp Melton in the 
primary, said he wanted to ``get the city cleaned up.'' 

</P>
<P>
 *SLEEPY STUDENTS   	
</P>
<P>
	Voters in the Katonah-Lewisboro school district in Westchester  
County, in the New York suburbs, rejected a proposal to spend $1.33 
million for more buses so high school could start at 7:55 a.m. 
instead of 7:15. Some parents and teachers have said that getting 
up too early dims students' performance in school. The measure 
failed 2,142 to 1,898. 

</P>
<P>
 *ARIZONA FOOTBALL   	
</P>
<P>
	Voters rejected a new quarter-cent sales tax and refused to  
extend a quarter-cent tax to help fund a $1.8 billion development 
that would include a new stadium for football's Arizona Cardinals. 
The Cardinals use the stadium at Arizona State University, making 
them the only major pro sports team that plays on a college campus. 
The measure failed 60 percent to 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
