<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:32:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Cuts Sneezing, Wheezing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- There may be a cure for the common cold,  
researchers reported today in the Journal of the American Medical 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	An experimental cold remedy called tremacamra cut sneezing,  
runny noses and congestion nearly in half. But whether the drug 
will work on the many viruses known to cause colds has yet to be 
determined. 
</P>
<P>
	All 177 volunteers who participated in the study were given the  
same cold bug -- type 39 rhinovirus, said researchers led by Dr. 
Ronald Turner of the Medical University of South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhinoviruses commonly cause colds, but at least 100 subtypes of  
rhinoviruses exist; many colds are caused by other viruses such as 
cornaviruses and flu. 
</P>
<P>
	Tremacamra works by blocking rhinoviruses from attaching to one  
particular molecule on the outside of cells that the virus needs 
for a biological anchor. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug was inhaled daily as a nasal spray or nasal powder for  
several days at about the time the people were infected. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert not associated with the study, which was funded by  
tremacamra manufacturer Boehringer Ingelheim Pharmaceuticals, said 
it should encourage further research. 
</P>
<P>
	But real-world effectiveness and long-term safety need to be  
established, said the expert, Dr. Kenneth McIntosh of Children's 
Hospital and Harvard Medical School in Boston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 07:14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swissair Buys Airline Catering Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- The parent company of Swissair,  
SAirGroup, announced Wednesday it is purchasing the airline 
catering unit of U.S.-based Viad Corp. for $780 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SAirGroup said that Viad Corp.'s Dobbs group, headquartered in  
Memphis, would be combined with its own catering unit, Gate 
Gourmet, creating the world's largest airline caterer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gate Gourmet currently is second largest in the world, and Dobbs  
is third, SAirGroup said in a statement. Dobbs also is the largest 
train caterer in the United States, it said. It had sales of $891 
million last year and employs 11,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition marked a ``one-time chance'' for SAirGroup to  
expand its airport-related businesses, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined catering companies are expected to have annual  
sales of more than 3 billion Swiss francs ($2 billion), the Swiss 
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The synergies offered by combining the two groups ... should  
generate significant cost savings over the next five years,'' said 
SAirGroup chief executive Philippe Bruggisser. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:56:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Astronomers Spot Storm on Mars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A cyclone four times the size of Texas raged  
across the northern polar region of the planet Mars last month, 
according to space telescope views of the red planet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Space Telescope Science Institute announced today that the  
Hubble Space Telescope on April 27 spotted an immense Martian storm 
cloud, made up of water ice, that was 1,100 miles long and 900 
wide. 
</P>
<P>
	Bands of clouds spiraled in a counterclockwise motion around a  
200-mile wide eye in the center of the storm, taking on a shape 
that resembled hurricanes on Earth, astronomers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm occurred during the summer in Mars' northern  
hemisphere. It came after seasonal warming evaporated the carbon 
dioxide ice sheet that caps the Martian north pole during part of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the storm was three times larger than a storm  
spotted 20 years ago by the Viking Orbiter spacecraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomers used a wide field planetary camera on Hubble to  
photograph Mars during the planet's closest approach to Earth in 
nearly eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Two pictures, taken six hours apart on April 27, showed that the  
storm moved slightly eastward. In the second picture, the storm 
appeared to be in the process of breaking up. 
</P>
<P>
	Later pictures by the Hubble camera failed to find the storm,  
and astronomers said it could have been a short-lived phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:41:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold at 10-Year Low on Sales Fears  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold futures touched 20-year lows Wednesday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange amid fears countries around the world will 
continue to sell their holdings in search of better-returning 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, coffee futures jumped a third session in a  
row, while grain and soybeans continued lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold remains a victim of Britain's recent decision to sell,  
beginning in July, more than half its reserves, a move that has 
lead to fears other central banks will hurriedly sell their gold as 
prices collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Government treasuries have become more reluctant to hold gold as  
a monetary reserve because of its storage expense and because bonds 
now have a far better return on investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors ignored statements by the Bank of France's Governor  
Jean-Claude Trichet, who said his country, Italy, Germany and the 
U.S. Federal Reserve had no plans to sell reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund is considering selling some of  
its reserves to help fund debt relief for poor countries. Outgoing 
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, after trading had ended, 
asked the Senate Appropriations Committee to approve the Clinton 
administration's request to allow the IMF to make the sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures also became victim to a rising U.S. dollar. Most  
commodities are priced in dollars, so a strong U.S. currency makes 
it more expensive for foreign jewelers and other physical users of 
gold to buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for June delivery finished down 70 cents to $273.50 an  
ounce after falling earlier in the session to a 20-year low of 
$272.40 an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures continued to gain on the Board of Trade of the  
City of New York as Brazil, the world's largest grower, braces for 
cold weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters say temperatures will fall much below normal in  
major growing regions, although they are unlikely to produce a 
freeze. Sustained freezing temperatures could damage coffee trees, 
particularly younger ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Some speculators are betting Brazil cannot have a third  
consecutive year of mild temperatures that have led to bumper 
harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	July arabica coffee rose 6.10 cents to $1.23 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board of  
Trade on favorable harvesting and planting weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures were pressured by mild, dry weather in  
Midwest growing regions, which should speed farmer fieldwork for 
what is expected to be bumper acreage. With the effects still being 
felt of recessions in Asia, Latin America and other countries, the 
prospect for another large harvest has sent prices reeling. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also fell after China purchased 40,000 metric tons of  
soybeans from South American competitors to U.S. farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by reports farmers were seeing  
above-average yields during harvesting of the winter wheat crop, 
which accounts for much of total wheat production. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat fell 4 1/4 cents to $2.59 3/4 a bushel; July corn fell 1 1/2  
cents to $2.19 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 4 cents to $4.71 1/2 a 
bushel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
