<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF To Study Ben Johnson Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- World track's governing body set up a  
three-man panel Wednesday to study Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson's 
petition for his lifetime drug ban to be lifted. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Amateur Athletic Federation appointed a  
sub-commission to consider Johnson's application for reinstatement. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF general secretary Istvan Gyulai, honorary treasurer Robert  
Stinson of Britain and Council member Helmut Digel of Germany were 
appointed to the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	A Canadian adjudicator ruled last month that the 37-year-old  
Johnson's application should be allowed to go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was stripped of his Olympic gold medal and 100-meter  
world record after testing positive for steroids at the 1988 Seoul 
Games. After serving a two-year suspension, he was banned for life 
by the IAAF after a second positive test in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling of the adjudicator, Graeme Mew, was based on alleged  
procedural errors in the handling of Johnson's lifetime suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said the panel will submit its  
recommendations on Johnson's case at the next council meeting, Aug. 
16-17 in Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	On another issue, the IAAF removed council member Charles Mukora  
of Kenya from its three-man panel of technical delegates for the 
2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Mukora has remained on the IAAF despite resigning as a member of  
the International Olympic Committee after being implicated in the 
Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mukora was replaced on the technical panel by IAAF vice  
president Lamine Diack of Senegal. The other two delegates remained 
unchanged: China's Dapeng Lou and New Zealand's Arthur Eustace. 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said Mukora was removed not because of his role in the  
Salt Lake scandal, but because of his links with alleged 
improprieties involving Sydney's Olympic bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Mukora and the head of Uganda's national Olympic committee met  
with Australian Olympic chief John Coates the night before the 1993 
IOC vote on the 2000 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Coates pledged $35,000 in sports funding to each of the two  
countries, contingent on Sydney winning the bid. The next day, 
Sydney defeated Beijing by two votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the funds earmarked for the Kenyan Olympic committee  
allegedly ended up in Mukora's personal trust. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was accused in his position as an IOC member of doing  
something wrong in relation to the Sydney bid for reasons of 
opportunity,'' Reineri said. ``For that reason, the IAAF felt it 
was not good to send him to Sydney as a technical delegate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said Mukora did not attend the Seville meeting, but has  
not resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us he is still a council member,'' Reineri said. ``He did  
nothing wrong in the IAAF.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF announced a $66 million deal with Dentsu marketing  
company to sell television rights to IAAF events in Japan from 2000 
to 2009. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF also confirmed Palermo, Sicily, as the venue for the  
World Half Marathon Championships next October and awarded the 2001 
World Race Walking Cup to Turin, Italy, and the 2003 event to 
Naumburg, Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 00:21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine High Loses Soccer Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- For a moment, the scene appeared sadly  
familiar: Columbine High School students huddled together, crying 
and hugging fiercely. 
</P>
<P>
	But tears gave way to laughter at this occasion -- the Colorado  
girl's state soccer championship, a joyful contrast to the horror 
that tore the soul of Littleton. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the Green Mountain Rams on Tuesday spoiled  
Columbine's bid to win its first girl's soccer crown, beating the 
Rebels 2-0. But the loss seemed almost incidental as thousands of 
fans found cause to cheer in the twilight of a lovely spring 
evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt so good to hear them sing `We are Columbine,''' said  
senior midfielder Meredith Russo. 
</P>
<P>
	Several thousand people filled the stands at the Englewood High  
School stadium to root for a team that dedicated its season to the 
12 classmates and teacher who were slain during the shooting attack 
a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the fans was Patrick Ireland, a student who was shot in  
the attack April 20. Ireland gained nationwide attention after 
television cameras caught him escaping from the gunmen through a 
second-floor window. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of people hugged Ireland during the half-time break, and  
he smiled and cheered along with his classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Students and their families had rallied behind the team as they  
marched into the championship game. ``We are Columbine'' and ``Good 
Luck Rebels'' banners dotted the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	After the loss, the Rebels got a standing ovation from their  
fans -- and from the Green Mountain supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``That made me a little more sad because it is my last year  
here. I'm going to miss all these people and Columbine,'' said 
senior co-captain Angie Portincaso. Her advice to those she is 
leaving behind: ``Don't take anything for granted. You never know 
what can happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Principal Frank DeAngelis, just returning to a normal high  
school event was a victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still proud of the girls,'' he said. ``I'm hurting for  
them because they worked so hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Columbine coach Peter Horvath said he tried to keep the girls  
focused on the challenge of taking the state title, despite obvious 
distractions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't have been more proud of them if we had won,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
