<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Want To Police Agents Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The list of NCAA rules and regulations  
fills more than 400 pages. The essence of one of the key bylaws is 
so simple, however, it could be written on the back of a football 
player's hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't take money from agents.  
</P>
<P>
	Along with warnings about gambling, drugs and alcohol, the  
relatively straightforward agent rule is among those drilled into 
the minds of players from the day they arrive on campus until the 
day they leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there's no prohibition against players talking to agents.  
And there seem to be dozens of ways to skirt the rules once the 
parties come in contact. 
</P>
<P>
	It means that anywhere there's a program with a few good  
athletes, almost surely there's a director for compliance trying to 
keep track of which agent, or which agent's runner, is contacting 
which player at any given time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an issue that's always been there, and it does not seem  
to go away,'' said Jamie McCloskey, associate athletic director for 
compliance at Florida. ``Each year, it seems to be growing. 
Unfortunately, it's not just an issue at Florida.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida is, however, the latest school to encounter problems,  
with a sworn complaint filed against one agent for allegedly paying 
players. Investigations are ongoing into activities of at least two 
other agents, including Tank Black, who is also targeted by the NFL 
Players Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida is hardly alone. Alabama is just shaking off the effects  
of a probation stemming from an agent problem that cropped up six 
years ago. Since then, Florida State's football program has 
encountered problems. So has Connecticut's basketball team. 
Accusations are being investigated at LSU. The list goes on and on. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Frank Bauer, a former coach with a good reputation, says  
most agents are trustworthy, but the ones trying to break into the 
business are at a severe disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got people going out, starting firms representing  
athletes, who have no credentials and no clients,'' Bauer said. 
``So the question is, `How do you get that client?' When that 
starts up, sometimes they feel like they have to induce a client to 
go to their side. That's when you get a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only agent formally accused of wrongdoing at Florida was  
allegedly involved in something that no school could adequately 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sworn complaint filed by university police, agent Sean  
Alfortish was accused of funneling money to two football players 
through the players' roommate. Neither player was considered a 
major NFL prospect. The roommate likely never made it onto the 
school's radar until the alleged violation occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Enticements can range from beer money, to a couple hundred bucks  
to a thousands of dollars in advance on future earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Like several other states, Florida has a relatively new law  
against unlicensed and illegal agent activity. In March, the NFLPA 
approved a bylaw that forced an agent to forfeit any fee he would 
receive if he is proven to have offered an illegal inducement to 
earn a player's business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an example of more attention being paid to the problem  
by people who want to clean this thing up,'' said Tom DePaso, staff 
counsel for the NFLPA. ``I don't know if the problem has grown 
worse in the last four or five years, but there's a lot more 
attention being paid to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Often, the agent never even has to show up on campus to make an  
impact. The inducement can be funneled through a runner, sometimes 
a student or friend of a player. 
</P>
<P>
	That simply increases the list of people schools try to monitor.  
Because it is such a vast group, some believe it will take more 
than a new law or two to solve the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``The basic issue is you have kids who are being exploited by  
the schools,'' said Black's attorney, Leonard Mungo. ``These 
players know what they're worth and they know the schools are 
taking advantage. Then you have 900 agents out there looking to 
sign 240 players who get drafted. Not every agent can afford to 
play by the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just hours after Mungo was interviewed, the NFLPA filed a  
disciplinary complaint against Black. 
</P>
<P>
	The union alleged that Black provided improper cash payments in  
1997 and 1998 to college players before their eligibility was 
completed. The complaint also claimed Black acquired new autos in 
1998 for players before their college eligibility expired. 
</P>
<P>
	Black, in turn, plans to petition the U.S. Attorneys office to  
investigate the union's action. 
</P>
<P>
	McCloskey stands by as much more than an impartial observer. And  
he knows he's not the only one who is squirming as the list of 
accusations continues to grow. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were an issue at Florida and nowhere else, it would  
probably be a good thing for athletics as a whole,'' he said. ``But 
it's an issue that has potential to be a problem on many different 
campuses. And it's getting harder to control every day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
