<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:05:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TWENTY YEARS LATER: Entrepreneur magazine, celebrating its 20th  
anniversary, notes through some interesting factoids just how much 
technology has affected business people's lives and made some of 
them very wealthy. The magazine reports that David Filo and Jerry 
Yang, founders of the Internet company Yahoo!, have a net worth of 
$3 billion each today. If both men had not dropped out of Stanford 
University's Ph.D. program, they might have gone on to earn a 
starting salary of $57,000 to $110,000 a year, Entrepreneur says. 
Another example: A two-bedroom house in Silicon Valley that sold 
for $75,000 in 1975 is going for $900,000 today. But high-tech 
isn't the only way to get rich -- in 1998, 12 years after she 
founded the American Girls catalog, Pleasant Rowland sold it to 
Mattel for $700 million. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	FINANCIAL OPTIMISM: Although Americans are generally optimistic  
about their financial future, more doubts seem to be creeping into 
their outlook, according to a survey of 1,000 people commissioned 
by Phoenix Home Life Mutual Insurance Co. The survey found that 92 
percent of respondents were upbeat about the future, up from 89 
percent in a survey a year ago. But 35 percent of the respondents 
said they're concerned that their household's primary wage earner 
could lose his or her job in the next three years, compared to 31 
percent with that concern last year. And fewer people said they're 
considering an extravagant purchase such as a car or boat in the 
next five years, perhaps because of uncertainty about the future. 
In the latest survey, 20 percent said they're planning a big 
splurge; that's down from 23 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AIR FARES: The gap between the air fare that most tourists pay  
and the fare that a typical business traveler pays continues to 
widen. American Express says that when it studied fares on 215 U.S. 
routes in March, it found that the average lowest discount fare, 
the kind usually paid by tourists was $133, while refundable 
tickets with three-day advance purchase requirements, those usually 
chosen by business travelers, averaged $476. The difference between 
the two fares came to $343, up from a $317 gap in March 1998. At 
that time discount fares averaged $130 and typical business fares 
averaged $447. American Express said the average cost of an airline 
ticket, which also reflects full-price, unrestricted fares, rose $8 
to $298 in March from $290 a year earlier. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
