<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Suit Filed in Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police officers shouted racial epithets and  
celebrated with high-fives after fatally shooting a black woman who 
was unconscious in a car, her family's lawyers said in a federal 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil rights suit filed Tuesday by a legal team headed by  
celebrity attorney Johnnie Cochran named five officers and the city 
of Riverside as defendants and alleged ``racial animus'' as the 
motive for killing Tyisha Miller, 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Miller was shot 12 times on Dec. 28 after she was found  
lying in her locked car with a gun in her lap. Police, who 
responded to a 911 call, say she suddenly reached for the weapon 
when an officer smashed the car's window and tried to grab the gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Toxicology tests later showed Ms. Miller had a blood-alcohol  
level of .13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The shooting of Tyisha Miller was unjustified,'' the lawsuit  
said. ``At no time did she present an imminent threat of harm to 
the defendant officers or to anyone else and she made no aggressive 
or provocative movement such that a reasonable officer under the 
circumstances would have believed that she was a threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city's lawyer had only a brief response.  
</P>
<P>
	``The city intends to defend the case vigorously and the outcome  
will be determined in the courts,'' said Skip Miller, an outside 
attorney representing Riverside and the officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the police have denied the charges. An investigation  
by the Riverside district attorney concluded that police were 
justified in using deadly force. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit said at least 24 rounds were fired at Ms. Miller, and  
at least one officer emptied a magazine, reloaded and fired again. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was over, Cochran claimed, the officers were rejoicing,  
``high-fiving each other in joy and glee.'' He said he based his 
allegations on information from a witness whom he declined to 
identify. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and state attorney general are conducting separate  
investigations into possible civil rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages for, among other claims,  
wrongful death, assault and battery, intentional infliction of 
emotional distress and violation of civil rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 20:11:25 </DATE_TIME>
