<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic OKs Parts of Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic accepted elements of a Kosovo peace plan today, but 
insisted in talks with a Russian envoy that the details must be 
negotiated directly with the United Nations. That would appear to 
fall short of Western conditions for halting the eight-week bombing 
campaign -- unequivocal acceptance of the international plan. Soon 
after the envoy flew out of the Yugoslav capital late tonight, NATO 
warplanes launched their strongest attack in two weeks against the 
Belgrade area. Local media and witnesses said a hospital near a 
Belgrade military barracks was hit, killing at least three people. 

</P>
<P>
	House Panel Seeks To Limit Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Armed Services Committee voted today  
to impose new spending restrictions on President Clinton's conduct 
of the military operation in Yugoslavia. Democrats denounced the 
action. The panel, working on a $288.8 billion defense spending 
bill, endorsed a provision stating that none of the funds ``may be 
used for the conduct of combat or peacekeeping operations'' in 
Yugoslavia. ``That's a heck of a message to send to that 
23-year-old climbing into the cockpit of an F-16 tonight,'' said 
Rep. Gene Taylor, D-Miss. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Offers Gun Control Concessions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans offered fresh concessions  
on gun control tonight, but Democrats swiftly said they didn't go 
far enough to plug gaps that allow some criminals to obtain 
weapons. A draft amendment circulated by the GOP calls for 
background checks on all purchasers at gun shows, including 
transactions exempted in a proposal that Republicans muscled 
through the Senate last week. The concessions marked the latest in 
a series of retreats by the GOP in the wake of last month's 
shooting spree at a Colorado high school and a renewed push by 
Democrats for more restrictions on firearms. 

</P>
<P>
	Quayle Takes On Media, Legal 'Elites'  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Seven years after his ``Murphy Brown''  
speech, GOP presidential hopeful Dan Quayle touched off a fresh 
round of criticism today with an address scolding legal and media 
``elites.'' ``Unfortunately, this aristocracy has bit by bit 
undermined parental authority, weakened school discipline, and 
obstructed moral education,'' he said. Quayle and his wife, 
Marilyn, are lawyers. He criticized ``aristocrats'' who live in 
gated communities; he has a home in such a community, in the 
Phoenix suburb of Paradise Valley. 

</P>
<P>
	Starved Baby's Mom Convicted  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A young mother who blamed breast-feeding  
problems for the death of her emaciated baby son was convicted 
today of criminally negligent homicide. Tabitha Walrond, 21, faces 
up to four years in prison. She was acquitted of the more serious 
charge of manslaughter. Prosecutors said Walrond starved 
2-month-old Tyler in 1997 to spite his father, who left her shortly 
after she got pregnant. The defense said she was a doting mother 
who didn't realize that her surgically reduced breasts were failing 
to nourish her child. 

</P>
<P>
	Arbitrator Rules Against Disney  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. breached its contract  
with former film boss Jeffrey Katzenberg in 1994 and owes him a 
potentially huge interest payment on top of his sizable bonus, an 
arbitrator ruled today. The case now moves to another phase in 
which a retired judge determines exactly how much money Disney 
should pay Katzenberg, who has contended he's due at least $250 
million in an incentive bonus. If Katzenberg's final bonus ends up 
being close to what he wants, the compounded interest could be 
worth tens of millions of dollars. 

</P>
<P>
	Doctors Slow Huntington's in Mice  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scientists have found a way to delay the onset  
of Huntington's disease and slow its progress in mice by targeting 
an enzyme that is believed to trigger cell death. The finding is a 
promising lead for drug researchers working to extend the lives of 
Huntington's sufferers. In the new study, scientists blocked a 
particular enzyme in mice that had been genetically engineered to 
contract the disease. These mice developed Huntington's symptoms 
about 10 percent later in life and lived about 20 percent longer. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Thursday. The Nikkei Stock  
Average rose 76.79 points to 16,204.97 in early trading. In New 
York Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed up 50.44 
points at 10,887.39. 

</P>
<P>
	Pacers Take 2-0 Lead in Series  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers beat the Philadelphia  
76ers 85-82 in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference semifinals tonight. 
The Sixers now trail 2-0 headed to Philadelphia for Games 3 and 4. 
Allen Iverson suffered through a 7-for-28 shooting night for 
Philadelphia and finished with 25 points. Rik Smits lead Indiana 
with 25 points. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
