<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Luyendyk, Schmidt Ready to Qualify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Having top-line equipment, an experienced  
team and enough time to prepare are new luxuries for Sam Schmidt, 
Arie Luyendyk's heir with Treadway Racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt, whose background was in sports cars, joined Treadway  
this season as a replacement for Luyendyk, a two-time Indianapolis 
500 winner who is retiring after the May 30 race, his only start 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt, meanwhile, is enjoying every minute as second fiddle  
during Luyendyk's last ride. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're there, we know what the car is capable of and I think we  
have a pretty good idea of what we need to do to get the car ready 
to qualify,'' Schmidt said Tuesday. ``Now we're running with a full 
load, trying different fuel settings, stuff that most teams don't 
have time to get to, and I never had time to get to in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt and Luyendyk, driving G Force-Auroras, have been among  
the most consistent and fastest drivers since practice began last 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifications to determine the 33-car lineup are set for  
Saturday and Sunday. The Treadway team is ready now. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nice to qualify tomorrow, actually,'' Luyendyk  
said. ``Sam has been running really strong. ... At this moment, 
we're looking pretty good with time. If we don't have any 
mechanical problems, we're really OK on schedule. The team is well 
prepared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, the only driver to win at least one race in each of  
the first three seasons the Indy Racing League has been in 
operation, is preparing for his 15th start at Indianapolis. He 
already holds track records for speed in practice, qualifications 
and the race -- all set before the IRL adopted a new engine-chassis 
package that produced slower speeds -- and he's Indy's career money 
leader with more than $5.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt was the third-fastest rookie qualifier at Indianapolis  
with Blueprint Racing in 1997. He finished 34th in an expanded 
field of 35 starters after an engine problem on the pace lap. Last 
year, he started sixth, but wound up 26th after a multi-car crash 
on the 48th lap. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even before this year, Arie was one of the guys that was  
approachable. Arie was very helpful,'' Schmidt said. ``You ask him 
a question, you get a straight answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in a lot of team situations, and this one is as good  
or better than any other one, because it's like an open book. There 
are no secrets,'' he said. ``All the information we have is totally 
accessible (to Luyendyk's crew), as what they're doing with their 
car is open to us. So that really helps. You can accomplish a lot 
of things every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fastest drivers in practice, all with top laps under ideal  
weather conditions on Saturday, are Greg Ray at 225.887 mph, 
Luyendyk at 225.163, Scott Goodyear at 224.405 and Schmidt at 
224.394. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, when practice was delayed by rain, Goodyear was the  
quickest at 223.842, followed by Stephan Gregoire at 223.647, Kenny 
Brack at 223.447 and Ray at 223.214. 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk did not practice on Tuesday. Schmidt, already preparing  
his race setup, drove 44 laps, with a top speed of 217.538. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both of us would be happy to qualify tomorrow,'' Schmidt said.  
``There was a lot of speculation that after the speeds on Saturday, 
gee, are we going to see 230? I think that's out of the question 
with this car package.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pole position speed last year was a four-lap 223.503 mph  
average by Billy Boat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going 224, 225, that's kind of all there is,'' Schmidt said of  
the likely pole speed this year. ``Really, the more days of 
practice is allowing people that are maybe 20th or 30th to come up 
in speed a little bit.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
