<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Progress in WTO Leader Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Efforts to appoint a new leader for the World  
Trade Organization are going nowhere fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after Italy's Renato Ruggiero stepped down as  
director-general of the trade body, the nations are no closer to 
selecting a successor. 
</P>
<P>
	And some fear that the 134 member nations are so deadlocked over  
two candidates that they will have to start anew to find someone, 
possibly delaying a decision for months, even into the fall when 
key trade talks are scheduled to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be the worst possible solution,'' said Turkish trade  
ambassador Omer Ersun. ``It will make a mockery of our work of the 
last six months if a latecomer pops out at the last moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the director-general is in part a figurehead, the WTO  
chief also plays an important behind-the-scenes role in setting the 
trade agenda and seeking to solve some tough disputes. Ruggiero 
intervened in a nasty fight between the United States and European 
Union over trade in bananas. 
</P>
<P>
	The two candidates for the top job are former New Zealand  
Premier Mike Moore and Thai Deputy Premier Supachai Panitchpakdi, 
both of whom are considered highly qualified. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, there are no formal proposals for a third candidate to  
break the deadlock, although names floating around the WTO's 
lakeside headquarters include former Uruguayan trade minister 
Enrique Iglesias, who heads the Inter-American Development Bank in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the stalemate, a planned meeting Wednesday of the  
WTO's decision-making council was scrapped. Council chairman Ali 
Mchumo of Tanzania set no new date. 
</P>
<P>
	After intense negotiations, Mchumo last month proposed that  
Moore get the job because he had the edge over Supachai. The 
suggestion was welcomed by the United States and most Latin 
American and some European countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian nations, though, protested, saying Supachai had for months  
been the front-runner. They blocked Moore's appointment and 
demanded that Mchumo try to rally the nations around Supachai. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Mchumo has failed to narrow the gap. The WTO  
operates on the principle of consensus, and any move to decide the 
issue by a vote would meet heavy opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Suggestions by New Zealand for a power-sharing deal, with Moore  
as the chief and Supachai in the No. 2 spot have been rejected by 
Bangkok. Moore has let it be known he's not interested in being 
anyone's deputy. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side in the dispute has spelled out publicly its  
objections to the other candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai has fallen afoul of the United States -- at least  
according to Thai newspapers -- for making perceived anti-American 
comments at the height of Thailand's economic crisis last year. 
</P>
<P>
	And some Asian and African countries seem suspicious of Moore,  
fearing that the former trade unionist might give labor and 
environmental protection a higher priority in trade negotiations 
due to be launched at a November summit in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Moore has stressed his support for poor nations,  
there is a general perception that Supachai is the candidate of 
developing countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the leadership vacuum, WTO business continues as usual.  
Meetings are being held to prepare for the next round of 
negotiations to liberalize trade, and trade disputes, such as the 
one between Washington and the European Union over sales of 
hormone-treated beef, continue. 
</P>
<P>
	But some diplomats say they are distracted.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are meeting as usual but it doesn't mean the mind is  
there,'' said Carlos Perez del Castillo, Uruguay's ambassador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
