<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pimlico Runner Doesn't Remember </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The lawyer for the man who ran onto the track  
at Pimlico on Preakness day said his client doesn't remember doing 
so. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Chang Ferrell also doesn't remember confronting thundering  
thoroughbreds or taking a swing at a jockey, according to attorney 
Frederic Heyman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thing he remembers is being in the holding cell at  
Pimlico,'' Heyman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyman refused to say if his 22-year-old client was drunk before  
he jumped onto the track near the final turn, as police said. He 
did say Ferrell has been diagnosed with psychological problems, 
including manic depression. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident occurred three races before the Preakness on  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrell, who works at an aquarium store, was staying with his  
parents his father posted $2,500 bail to get him out of the Central 
Booking and Intake Center on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces assault and other charges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
