<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative GOPs Eye Third Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Conservative Republicans may move to start  
a third party because they believe too many Republicans are 
abandoning the conservative planks of the party's platform, GOP 
presidential candidate Bob Smith says. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a conservative senator from New Hampshire, says he does  
not advocate a split. But in interviews with The Washington Times 
and New Hampshire newspapers this week he said frustrated 
conservatives are seriously considering forming a third party 
centered on gun rights, national defense, school prayer, low taxes 
and opposition to abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe you may well have seen the beginnings of a  
third-party movement in this country, which will spell the end of 
the Republican Party,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it happens, I'm not leaving my party -- my party is leaving  
me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he had not ruled out a presidential run on the new  
party's ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	He would not say whether he would actively try to organize  
another party if a conservative fails to win the GOP presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican National Committee spokesman Michael Collins said  
Smith had legitimate concerns, but the party is unified on core 
principles. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us believe in smaller government, the enormous  
potential for the individual, and that the individual should be 
empowered to the maximum extent possible consistent with an orderly 
and lawful society,'' Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said conservatives were the foundation of the party and its  
most loyal supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Duprey, chairman of the state party, said he was adamantly  
opposed to a third party formed by Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am confident that Republicans will rally and unite behind  
whomever is our nominee,'' Duprey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
