<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Firm Buys Out British Pub Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Texas Pacific Group, a privately owned U.S. buyout  
firm, has invested more than $800 million in one of Britain's 
biggest pub operators, a company official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The investment in Punch Taverns Group Ltd. gives the firm a  
majority stake in a network of 1,470 tenant-run pubs. The deal is 
Texas Pacific's first venture in the European food and drinks 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Punch Taverns earned an operating profit for the year ending  
Sept. 30 of 71 million British pounds ($115 million), on sales of 
146 million pounds ($235 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Additional details of the investment were not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	Texas Pacific, whose founders managed money for the Bass family  
of Texas, opened its London office a year ago. The company has $2.5 
billion to invest, managing director Stephen Peel said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is one of several American buyout firms that have opened shop  
in London to take advantage of the mounting number of corporate 
consolidations in Europe. Other U.S. players include Kohlberg 
Kravis Roberts and Co.; Clayton, Dubilier and Rice Ltd., and Soros 
Private Equity Partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Pacific's previous deals in Europe include investments of  
$106 million in Guinness Peat Aviation PLC, an Ireland-based 
airline leasing company, and $30 million stake in Landis and Gyr 
Communications, a Swiss pay telephone manufacturer. It also did two 
deals with Britain's Virgin Group, investing in a train company and 
the MGM cinema chain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
