<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:52:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McPherson Play Tells Three Stories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's hard enough clearly telling one story on  
stage but Irish playwright Conor McPherson sets himself up for 
triple duty with ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' now at tiny Primary 
Stages off-Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	Three tales snake through the latest McPherson work to reach New  
York, following ``St. Nicholas,'' seen last season at the same 
theater, and ``The Weir,'' currently playing on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	But McPherson is a consummate storyteller, able to pack a lot in  
this short -- less than 90 minutes -- look at the lives of three men 
in a bleak resort town on the Irish coast. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, McPherson starts with a good central yarn, in  
this case, the robbery of the local bookie joint -- but there is 
more. His riffs on brotherhood, betrayal and good fortune are not 
immediately apparent as the playwright introduces his three 
characters, who sit around on stage when they are not talking 
directly to the audience. Initially, their monologues don't seem 
interrelated. 
</P>
<P>
	First up is Joe, a naive, earnest 17-year-old who idolizes  
Damien, a more worldly student who takes Joe on a memorable and 
eye-opening adventure. Then there is Ray, a university philosophy 
teacher who has been dating Joe's sister, among other women. 
Finally, there is Frank, Joe's older brother who works in their 
father's fish-and-chip shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank broods about his father's mounting debts, an amount that  
is strangling the family. He decides to help. The robbery and its 
aftermath is described from various perspectives, a fascinating 
three-way look at the same event. 
</P>
<P>
	McPherson weaves these versions together skillfully, even  
surprisingly, with an ending that would do O. Henry proud. 
</P>
<P>
	The production, straightforwardly directed by Harris Yulin, is  
not yet up to the quality of the writing. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the boyish T.R. Knight as the youthful Joe seems  
comfortable in his role. Dressed in a short-sleeve shirt, a sweater 
and tie, the lad conveys a disarming seriousness that immediately 
gains him audience support. 
</P>
<P>
	Drew McVety's swaggering Ray has the most comic monologue, a  
confrontation with a well-known philosopher that literally clears a 
lecture hall. Yet he and Thomas Lyons, whose Frank sets the plot in 
motion, don't quite inhabit the characters as forcefully as they 
should. A few more performances could rectify their tentativeness. 
</P>
<P>
	But that shouldn't stop you from listening in on these  
beautifully written monologues. ``This Lime Tree Bower'' -- the 
title comes from a poem by Samuel Taylor Coleridge -- gives a boost 
to the fine art of storytelling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
