<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Sets Social Security Hearings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A key House committee will discuss proposals  
to shore up Social Security despite a recent assessment by 
Republican leaders that congressional action is unlikely this year, 
its chairman said Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are areas where there can be an ultimate  
reconciliation,'' said House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill 
Archer, R-Texas, after a meeting with President Clinton. Archer's 
panel oversees the nation's retirement program. 
</P>
<P>
	At their White House meeting, Archer and Clinton discussed  
similarities between a Social Security rescue plan the president 
proposed in his State of the Union speech and a competing plan 
Archer unveiled in April. But neither offered to give any ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not attempt to try to negotiate any sort of  
compromise,'' Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Archer and Clinton talked about how they could help  
other lawmakers overcome reluctance to negotiate changes in the 
popular program, which has been a lightning rod for political 
attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that we have developed a working relationship that if  
we both worked our sides we would have an opportunity'' for 
compromise, Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, Democrats and Republicans have done little  
other than to try to pin the blame on each other for a lack of 
progress on Social Security, and several weeks ago, Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, said he did not think anything can be 
accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's top economic adviser, Gene Sperling, said that at the  
meeting with Archer the president brought up ``the need to have 
processes like hearings and consultations that allowed Democrats 
and Republicans to participate, express views and suggestions and 
give an opportunity for bipartisan consensus to form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear, however, if Archer's offer to hold hearings in  
June, after Congress returns from its traditional Memorial Day 
break, will provide such a forum. The Ways and Means chairman said 
he will limit discussion to proposals that meet a test of providing 
75 years of financial health for Social Security. Clinton's plan, 
by the administration's own estimate, would assure only about 60 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it is in some way added to so that it will meet that  
standard, it will be subject to the hearing and I think the 
president understands that,'' Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Clinton's and Archer's plans would invest some of Social  
Security's cash reserves in the stock market in an effort to 
increase their worth enough to help close a financing shortfall 
expected after baby boomers retire and begin to collect benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Clinton would have the government handle the  
investments while Archer would set up a new system of accounts that 
individual Americans would control. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has also proposed a new system of personal retirement  
accounts for low- and middle-income Americans. But his accounts 
would be in addition to Social Security, while Archer's would be 
counted as part of people's Social Security benefits in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Worries about a possible rise in U.S. interest  
rates sent Japanese stock prices sharply lower Wednesday for the 
fifth consecutive trading day. The U.S. dollar climbed to a 
seven-month high against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 250.44 points,  
or 1.53 percent, closing at 16,128.18. The average now has fallen a 
total of 819.18 points in five days, including Tuesday's 
42.40-point drop, or 0.26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 123.70 yen at late afternoon, up 0.84 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
123.20 yen overnight. In Wednesday's trading, the dollar ranged 
between 123.25 yen and 124.03 yen, its highest intraday level in 
Tokyo since Nov. 30, 1998, when it traded at 124.07 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, stocks remained in negative territory  
throughout Wednesday's trading after the U.S. Federal Reserve's 
Open Market Committee decided Tuesday to leave interest rates 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee did, however, put financial markets on notice that  
it is poised to raise interest rates if inflation concerns in the 
U.S. economy continue to build. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates tend to make a nation's currency more  
attractive to investors, but lighten returns on equities and 
Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo market has been in a correction phase in recent  
sessions since the Nikkei index surged to its highest closing level 
since October 1997 on May 6, some traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Market levels have been running ahead of economic  
fundamentals, and if the fundamentals aren't keeping up, share 
values are going to fall to get in line with them,'' said Yasuo 
Ueki, chief executive officer of POCO Financial Business 
Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also remained under pressure as many investors stayed  
cautious ahead of more Japanese corporate earnings announcements in 
coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 601  
million shares, up from Tuesday's turnover of 541 million shares. 
Declining issues outnumbered advancers 937 to 278, with 98 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 23.54 points, or 1.78 percent, to 1,300.61. 
The TOPIX gained 1.72 points, or 0.13 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar advanced on buying from  
overseas players following the Fed committee's decision to assume a 
tightening bias. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese trust banks were among other dollar-buying players.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also god support from a widening of the interest-rate  
differential between Japan and the United States, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, bond prices dropped Tuesday amid fear of a future  
rise in interest rates, driving the yield on the benchmark 30-year 
U.S. Treasury bond up to 5.91 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, the yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese  
government bond rose to 1.325 percent from Tuesday's finish of 
1.280 percent, driving its price down to 101.55 yen from 101.96 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 131.60 yen, up from  
131.30 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
