<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Says NATO Strategy Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder  
repeated his opposition Wednesday to the use of NATO ground forces, 
saying the alliance's current strategy was beginning to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder, who is spearheading European efforts to find a  
diplomatic solution to the Kosovo crisis, said he supported the 
19-nation alliance's strategy of waiting until the air war is over 
before sending a force into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am against any change in NATO strategy because I believe it  
is beginning to take effect,'' the chancellor told reporters at 
NATO headquarters after meeting with the alliance's top civilian 
and military leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always understood NATO's strategy to be a dual  
strategy,'' he said. ``One element is the military campaign ... to 
save people in Kosovo from being killed, from being expelled. The 
second element of our strategy has always been the search for a 
political settlement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook insisted  
Wednesday that NATO is united in its opposition to committing 
ground troops to Kosovo as an invasion force. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav army, however, appears to be expecting a NATO  
ground attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports in recent weeks have described Yugoslav army troops  
digging in areas along the borders with Albania and Macedonia in 
apparent preparation for a land invasion by NATO troops. The Serbs 
are still fighting the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in these areas, 
too, be they seem to be getting ready to defend major approaches 
from an onslaught by the allies, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have good evidence that in the area, especially towards  
Albania, that positions have been made to revettments, tanks are 
being dug in to be prepared for an attack from the side of 
Albania,'' said Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, a NATO military spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO insists, however, it will use ground troops only after Serb  
forces withdraw. Nonetheless, it does have plans for such an 
invasion on the shelf. 
</P>
<P>
	As the chancellor arrived at NATO headquarters, the alliance  
announced a lull in the air campaign caused by poor weather 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO planes flew 425 sorties on the 56th day of the operation,  
but only 58 of them involved airstrikes. Those operations were 
successful in destroying six Galeb aircraft on the ground north of 
Prizren, NATO said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon responded Wednesday to reports  
that NATO was avoiding bombing central Belgrade after the mistaken 
attack on the Chinese Embassy on May 7, saying the alliance had not 
adopted a policy of withholding attacks on the center of the 
Yugoslav capital. He did say there have been no attacks there since 
the embassy bombing, but attributed this to weather and other 
factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder came to NATO at a moment when diplomatic efforts are  
picking up steam. Envoys from seven top industrialized powers and 
Russia, known as the G-8, met in Germany on Wednesday to work on 
the draft of a U.N. resolution that would set out terms for ending 
the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign ministers from the G-8 -- made up of the United States,  
Britain, France, Canada, Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia -- 
outlined those terms two weeks ago, including a well-armed 
international force to secure the return of refugees to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution will have to satisfy Russia and China on the U.N.  
Security Council. To appease Russia, the foreign ministers did not 
specify that NATO would control the force, saying only that it had 
to be an ``effective security presence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has demanded an end to the fighting in Kosovo, a withdrawal  
of all Serb troops and police, safe return of the refugees, an 
international military force with NATO as its core, and a beginning 
to serious political talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
