<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Placebo Helps Some Depressed People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To their surprise, scientists have detected a  
change in brain activity that apparently helped some people gain 
remission from depression after taking inactive ``placebo'' pills. 
</P>
<P>
	Oddly, the detected change was exactly the opposite of what  
researchers found in people helped by Prozac. 
</P>
<P>
	If scientists can figure out how the placebo treatment works, it  
might give clues for developing new therapies, said Dr. Andrew F. 
Leuchter of the University of California, Los Angeles, 
Neuropsychiatric Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke in an interview before presenting the study Wednesday  
at the annual meeting of the American Psychiatric Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers have long known that many depressed people can get  
relief, at least for a while, by taking inert pills that they 
believe might be real medication. In fact, new medications are 
tested head-to-head against placebos to make sure the real drugs 
actually work better. As in Leuchter's study, participants agree 
beforehand that they might get a placebo and that they won't find 
out until the study is over. 
</P>
<P>
	Leuchter's study was intended to monitor the brains of people  
taking Prozac to see if changes in activity would predict who would 
get better on the drug. He and colleagues included people taking 
placebos just for comparison. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 26 people studied, half were given Prozac and the other  
half a placebo. After eight weeks, remission appeared in just under 
half the placebo group and just over half the Prozac group. 
</P>
<P>
	By placing electrodes on the scalp, Leuchter and colleagues  
found that people who improved on Prozac showed a decrease in 
activity in the front of the brain. That appeared within 48 hours 
of the start of therapy, well before any lifting of depression was 
apparent. Other antidepressants have the same effect on brain 
activity, Leuchter said. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, people who responded to the placebo treatment  
showed an increase in activity in the front of the brain. That 
showed up more gradually, after a week or more of treatment. But it 
disappeared at the eight-week point in the study, when patients 
were about to be told whether they had been taking Prozac or a 
bogus drug, Leuchter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it can only last that long, or maybe the effect ended when  
a patient knew he or she was about to discover the truth, Leuchter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the patients who responded to the placebo found out they'd  
been taking an inactive drug, many continued their remission from 
depression for several weeks, Leuchter said. Then, most said they 
were feeling depressed again and asked to get Prozac. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not clear why opposite brain responses would each lead to a  
lifting of depression, Leuchter said. ``There's probably more than 
one pathway to clinical improvement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Robert M. Post, chief of the biological psychiatry branch of  
the National Institute of Mental Health, said brain activity 
measurements are general results that don't reveal the details of 
what's happening in the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Post also said that depressed people can show either  
overactivity or underactivity in the frontal lobes of the brain. 
Each group might respond better to a different treatment, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
