<DOCNO> APW19990519.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 17:16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  IOC Worried About Utah Drink Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Forget the corruption scandal. The big  
Olympic issue in Salt Lake City now is where to get a drink. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerned that the Utah capital's Mormon restrictions on alcohol  
might run smack into foreign cultures where beer and wine are 
normal table items, the International Olympic Committee asked Salt 
Lake organizers Wednesday to try to pull the cork and let the booze 
flow at the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's coordination commission, holding four days of meetings  
with the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, asked SLOC to request 
``with great respect'' that Utah authorities allow unfettered 
alcohol sales in the main press center, slated to take over the 
mammoth Salt Palace convention center downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a Frenchman, I know that a Frenchman kept from his wine  
might get cranky,'' IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelley Thomas, SLOC's senior vice president for communications,  
said the committee would ``make every effort'' to win an exemption 
from liquor laws for the Salt Palace for the two weeks of the 
games. Such exemptions can be granted for convention facilities but 
are limited to one a year. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no plans to request similar exemptions for other  
Olympic sites, SLOC spokesman Frank Zang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah officials have said repeatedly they would not relax the  
laws for the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Phone messages left at the offices of Gov. Mike Leavitt and  
House Speaker Martin Stephens were not immediately returned, and a 
call to Senate President Lane Beattie was not answered. Alcoholic 
Beverage Control Department director Kenneth Wynn was away from his 
office and unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	With the first visit by IOC leaders to Salt Lake since the  
bribery scandal nearing its end, both sides said contentious issues 
were few and that no SLOC plans had been rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Zero surprises,'' Servan-Schreiber said. He compared the  
sessions to ``making wedding plans but magnified 10 million 
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said SLOC presented reports on sports, environmental  
impact, telecommunications, media operations, marketing and other 
areas. The meetings wrap up Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the two sides discussed sight lines at the Delta Center  
for figure skating but that no further action was taken. Officials 
are concerned that some seats at the city's biggest indoor arena 
won't have good views of the ice, and skaters complained during the 
world championships there in February that they had trouble seeing 
the fans, which interrupted their rhythm. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas also said SLOC hoped to have its list of Olympic events  
finished by June, with competition schedules done by December. Salt 
Lake organizers have proposed several new events, including 
skeleton -- a luge-like race where sledders go down the track 
headfirst -- and women's bobsled. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it came to issues, Servan-Schreiber said, ``liquor for  
the bar'' grabbed the IOC's attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Mormon teaching forbids the use of alcohol. Beer is sold in  
grocery stores, but the law in Utah, where Mormons dominate the 
population and politics, restricts other alcohol sales to state-run 
outlets, establishments serving food or ``social clubs,'' where a 
customer must be sponsored by a club member before imbibing. Often 
the ``sponsorship'' is no more than a nod from the guy on the next 
barstool, but it's a barrier not seen in most of the rest of the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC bans alcohol from its own sponsorship program, although  
national and local Olympic committees can sign with brewers and 
vintners. Otherwise, Olympic leaders accept alcohol's presence. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Olympic venues in the past have served beer and wine, and  
the press center -- probably the highest concentration of foreign 
visitors to the games aside from the athletes' village, where wine 
is usually available with meals -- always has a least one place 
where thirsty reporters can belly up, no questions asked. 
</P>
<P>
	In their bids, Salt Lake organizers took pains to show how easy  
it was to buy a drink here. Tom Welch, the motivator behind the bid 
and now disgraced for his role in the bribery scandal, used to tell 
Olympic leaders, ``If you can't get a drink in Salt Lake City, you 
can't be very thirsty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But state officials have promised that they would not change  
laws just because the Olympic circus was coming to town. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Mormon church late last year spoke out against  
pleas from the tourism and hospitality industries to change the 
laws, and local anti-alcohol groups have protested Anheuser Busch's 
sponsorship as the first step toward ``beer-soaked Winter Games in 
Salt Lake City.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 17:16:05 </DATE_TIME>
