<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:44:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Grants Local Phone Cos. Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission agreed  
Tuesday to give medium-sized local phone companies, such as 
Cincinnati Bell, ALLTEL Corp. and CenturyTel Inc., regulatory 
relief that their industry had sought. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency decided to eliminate rules that required the  
companies to file applications to the commission before building, 
acquiring or extending phone lines; directed companies to obtain 
prior FCC permission before offering new services; and forced 
companies that resell another company's long-distance service under 
their brand name do so through a separate company. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also streamlined accounting and reporting requirements  
for the companies and reduced the amount of information they would 
have to file in the event two medium-sized companies plan to merge. 
</P>
<P>
	Medium-sized companies are defined as those serving less than 2  
percent of the nation's phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Independent Telephone and Telecommunications Alliance, which  
represents the midsize companies, had asked the FCC for regulatory 
relief. It was not completely satisfied with the result. 
</P>
<P>
	ITTA's executive director, David Zesiger, said his companies  
``welcome the relief granted, but ... it appears the commission 
missed the opportunity for more substantial relief.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 17:51:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agent:Trie Repaid Clinton Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- An office manager for Democratic  
fund-raiser Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie told investigators that Trie 
reimbursed six people for donations they made to President 
Clinton's legal defense fund, an FBI agent testified Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Roberta Parker said the manager, Maria ``Dia'' Mapili,  
told investigators that six Arkansans were involved. Their names 
were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie, 49, a central figure in the controversy over  
foreign-linked campaign donations to Democrats, is accused of 
impeding a Senate investigation into political fund raising. He 
could face up to five years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	He is charged separately in Washington with making and arranging  
illegal contributions from foreigners to Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC has returned $640,000 that Trie raised. Clinton's legal  
defense fund has returned another $460,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys accused prosecutors of trying to ``infect''  
the jury with Ms. Parker's testimony, which they said regarded the 
separate charges against Trie in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
