<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A storm system plodded across the East early today, bringing  
scattered rain, fog and thunderstorms from New England to Florida. 
Strong storms also moved across the northern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusty winds, hail and heavy rain were expected by tonight across  
the Southeast coast, with scattered showers lingering in the Great 
Lakes. Fair and partly cloudy conditions were forecast for the rest 
of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	Another storm system was expected to bring showers and  
thunderstorms to the Dakotas and Minnesota, as well as rain-weary 
Iowa. Scattered storms were also forecast for the Rockies and 
Northwest coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly dry and fair conditions were expected across the West and  
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, slow-moving thunderstorms packing high winds knocked  
out power to 20,000 people in the Pittsburgh area and caused 
flooding that forced people out of several homes. Four inches of 
rain fell in some places. 
</P>
<P>
	``Manhole covers were popping off because of the rushing  
water,'' Duquesne Mayor George Matta said. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Tuesday was 100 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz. The low was 25 at 
Gunnison, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 50s and 60s across the  
Northeast, Midwest, Great Lakes and Northwest; the 70s in the 
Plains and Southeast; and the 80s in the Southwest and south 
Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
