<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:41:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Defends Telecom Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- A billion dollars here, $5 billion there.  
</P>
<P>
	Why is Microsoft Corp., the world's biggest computer software  
maker, throwing so much money into telecommunications? 
</P>
<P>
	The answer, says chairman Bill Gates, is simple. With growing  
demand by businesses and individual consumers for high-speed 
computer links, ``it's important for us to have those companies 
make the investment, build that new equipment,'' Gates said 
Wednesday in a news conference during Microsoft's third annual CEO 
summit. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Jeff Raikes, Microsoft vice president for sales and  
support, denied any grander schemes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question comes up, `Are you in some way interested in  
becoming a telecommunications company?' and the answer is no,'' 
Raikes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our core competence is building software and so we're not  
controlling any communications companies,'' Gates said. ``We are 
just a software company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under a deal announced earlier this month, Microsoft is  
investing $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp., which in turn is relying on 
Microsoft products to offer interactive television with phone 
service and other Internet features over cable TV. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 Microsoft invested $1 billion in Comcast of  
Philadelphia, which now has 4.4 million cable subscribers and 
revenues exceeding $5.5 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been able to take things like the investment we made  
in Comcast and in a passive way encourage them to make some of 
these investments and get that infrastructure in place -- and then 
we'll build software that takes advantage of it,'' Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, in a speech to open the two-day conference of more than  
100 chief executives from the world's 1,000 biggest corporations, 
Gates said corporate success would hinge increasingly on how well 
information is organized electronically and made available to 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The speech echoed themes from Gates' book, ``Business @ the  
Speed of Thought: Using a Digital Nervous System.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond merely having a corporate Web site, computers and e-mail,  
``it's how you take those technologies and use them inside the 
company ... that's going to differentiate'' the most effective 
businesses,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who joined Gates at the news conference agreed that  
businesses must keep pace with technology to thrive and perhaps 
even survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the speed with which hardware and software become  
obsolescent, ``I think that the cost of waiting is worse,'' said 
Larry Bossidy, chairman of AlliedSignal Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Even for small businesses, ``I don't think the transition ... is  
going to slow down,'' said Michael Dell, chairman of Dell Computer 
Corp. ``It's only going to accelerate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love this to be simplified and easier for the homemaker  
and not just for the corporate world,'' added Martha Stewart, 
chairwoman of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia LLC. 
</P>
<P>
	Making e-mail part of a corporate culture and replacing paper  
forms with electronic outlines are only the first steps toward 
making full use of today's technology, Gates said in his speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even what's available right now is vastly underutilized  
throughout the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cutting-edge corporations are moving to wireless communications,  
combining voice, pictures and data and outfitting employees with 
``digital dashboards,'' customized on-screen layouts a worker can 
access from any computer, Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the executives said they were especially impressed by  
a messaging system that lists phone messages as well as e-mail, 
each retrievable by voice or text. 
</P>
<P>
	The digital dashboard -- ``your office on any screen,'' Gates  
called it -- can be modified both by the employee and by executives 
who might decide everyone should have a given feature, be it last 
month's sales figures or a corporate phone list. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates demonstrated his own digital dashboard which includes a  
toolbar featuring buttons for commands he created himself, a panel 
of moving stock quotes, a listing of top news stories on selected 
issues, access to weather maps and real-time photos of his frequent 
travel routes and e-mail ranked by priority, subject and author. 
</P>
<P>
	He also displayed some of the latest gear, including improved  
handheld devices that convert handwriting on an electronic pad into 
print on a computer screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's going to be a mainstream scenario very soon,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
