<HEADLINE> Yanks' Prospect To Stay in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Michigan quarterback and New York Yankees  
prospect Drew Henson will be spending his summer in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees decided to keep Henson with the team's Class A Tampa  
affiliate in the Florida State League instead of sending him to 
Class A Greensboro in the Carolina League. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can give him a little more attention here and he will  
certainly be challenged by the league,'' New York vice president of 
player development and scouting Mark Newman said. ``He's a guy that 
responds well to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida State League is among the circuits considered as the  
highest level of Class A baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Henson joined Tampa last Thursday after spending two weeks with  
New York's extended spring training program. He will return to 
Michigan when the Wolverines begin summer practice for the upcoming 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Henson, a third baseman, had a .316 batting average with two  
RBIs over six games at the Class A level the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 third-round draft pick made his professional debut last  
year, hitting .316 with one homer and two RBIs in ten games with 
Tampa of the rookie Gulf Coast League. 
</P>
</TEXT>
