<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An army officer arrested for protests against  
what he calls Mexico's antiquated and undemocratic military justice 
system has made a second suicide attempt in a military prison, 
local media reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Hildegardo Bacilio Gomez, arrested on charges of  
sedition after leading soldiers in a protest march through Mexico 
City in December, tried to cut his wrists at an army prison in the 
Pacific coast city of Mazatlan, his lawyers told local media. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Bacilio Gomez -- an army doctor who originally ran  
afoul of the military court system on charges of insubordination -- 
took an overdose of tranquilizers and was rushed to a military 
hospital, where he recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissident officers in this and other cases have frequently  
complained of harassment and abuse at military prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacilio Gomez heads a group he calls The Patriotic Command to  
Make People Aware, which protests injustices and corruption 
allegedly committed within the Mexican military, along with abuses 
of power and mistreatment of servicemen on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Torrential rains in a northeastern  
state claimed three lives Wednesday, bringing the number of deaths 
over the last three days due to heavy rain to 14, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four houses collapsed when the earth below them gave way killing  
three people in Candeias, in Bahia state 750 miles (1200 kms) 
northeast of Rio de Janeiro, the city's secretary of administration 
Ivan Palma said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a muddy hillside collapsed on a lumber yard, burying  
buildings and cars, killing six people and injuring another 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Palma said the rains appeared to be abating.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- After years of trials and appeals, a former  
federal police commander on Wednesday was sentenced to 49 1/2 years 
in prison for a 1990 murder that helped prompt creation of Mexico's 
federal human rights commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal attorney general's office said a judge in Mexico  
City imposed the sentence for murder, torture and abuse of 
authority on Mario Alberto Gonzalez Trevino, who once headed the 
federal judicial police detachment in the drug-plagued Pacific 
coast state of Sinaloa. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Norma Corona was kidnapped and shot to death in the  
Sinaloa state capital of Culiacan in May 1990. As head of the 
Sinaloa human rights commission, she had successfuly lobbying for a 
law mandating 10 years in prison for police who used torture. 
</P>
<P>
	But investigators said her slaying apparently was due to her  
allegations that federal judicial police were involved in slaying a 
Sinaloa lawyer and three Venezuelan men whom she had represented. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal over her killing -- and handling of the case -- were  
among the factors that led Mexico to create a National Human Rights 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexican prosecutors didn't want him  
released, nor did their U.S. counterparts. But Adan Amezcua walked 
out of a prison Wednesday almost one year after his arrest in a 
case that has embarrassed Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a judge ordered the release of Adan Amezcua -- the  
brother of alleged metamphetamine traffickers Jose de Jesus and 
Luis Amezcua -- after finding that prosecutors had failed to present 
sufficient evidence to back up money-laundering charges against 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican prosecutors say the brothers belonged to a drug ring  
that sent amphetamines to the United States. None of them have ever 
been charged with drug-trafficking, but prosecutors have tried to 
pin other charges on them. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose de Jesus and Luis Amezcua have had all Mexican charges  
against them dismissed and are now being held on extradition orders 
to the United States, where they face grand jury charges that 
include manufacturing metamphetamine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
