<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mostly lower  
Wednesday, dragged down by jitters over a possible rise in U.S. 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the largest market in Asia, concerns over the rate  
rise pulled the key index down 1.5 percent, setting a trend for 
most markets in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 250.44 points,  
closing at 16,128.18. The average now has fallen a total of 819.18 
points in five days, including Tuesday's 42.40-point drop, or 0.26 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Federal Open Market Committee met Tuesday and decided  
to leave interest rates unchanged, but said it was inclined to 
adopt a tighter monetary policy to curb inflationary pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates tend to make a nation's currency more  
attractive to investors, but lighten returns on equities and 
Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar bought 123.70 yen at late  
afternoon, up 0.84 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also above 
its late New York level of 123.20 yen overnight. In Wednesday's 
trading, the dollar ranged between 123.25 yen and 124.03 yen, its 
highest intraday level in Tokyo since Nov. 30, 1998, when it traded 
at 124.07 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, concerns over local and U.S. interest rates pulled  
Hong Kong blue chip share prices down 1.8 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 223.96 points to close at  
12,403.14, its lowest close since April 15. On Tuesday, the index 
gained 38.50 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong interest rates have generally moved in line with U.S.  
rates because the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore shares also closed lower on rate hike fears, dealers  
said. The Straits Times Index closed down 6.32 points, or 0.3 
percent, at 1,911.50 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed slightly higher. The Stock  
Exchange of Thailand, or SET, Index edged up 1.95 points, or 0.4 
percent, to 483.50. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed sharply higher, propelled by  
buying in basic industry and telecommunications blue chips. The JSX 
Composite Index closed up 2.7 percent, or 15.718 points, at 593.604 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower as investors  
cashed in on recent gains. The Composite Index fell 0.6 percent, or 
4.56 points, to 775.73. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks ended sharply lower as investors  
cashed in on recent gains, spurred by concerns over a possible rise 
in U.S. interest rates. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange 
Index closed 77.48 points, or 3.1 percent, lower at 2,390.82. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher for the second consecutive day  
as a rebound continued after last week's sharp declines and 
investors shrugged off the U.S. interest rate news. The Korea 
Composite Stock Price Index rose 5.69 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
734.98. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices ended lower, with nearly all  
industry groupings sagging on the U.S. interest rate news. The All 
Ordinaries Index closed at 2,981.2, down 18.4 points, or 0.6 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices ended slightly higher as investors moved  
out of commodity-related stocks and into technology issues. The key 
Weighted Price Index closed up 29.09 points, or 0.4 percent, at 
7,614.60. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower, with brokers  
attributing the fall to weakness in the share price of market 
leaders Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. and Fletcher Challenge 
Ltd.'s Energy division. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 
19.91 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,170.69. 

</P>
</TEXT>
