<HEADLINE> Secretary To Be Tried for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALFRED, Maine (AP) -- A former church secretary who bilked more  
than $10,000 from three elderly women by concocting a story about 
her husband being a spy is competent to stand trial, a judge has 
ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Petersen, 70, received contributions from people who were  
sympathetic after hearing her story that her money was tied up 
because her husband was a secret agent who disappeared in the Gulf 
War but was officially declared dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen, who is being held on $30,000 bail, is charged with  
three counts of theft by deception. She was working as a secretary 
at St. David's Episcopal Church in Kennebunk when the crimes were 
allegedly committed. 
</P>
<P>
	Her attorney claimed -- but did not convince the judge -- that  
Petersen was delusional and could not participate in her own 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
 *After a century, S.C. heads for stock market with pension money    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- After more than a century of caution,  
South Carolina's pension funds are headed to the stock market with 
a plan to invest more than $900 million in an index fund before 
June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Next fiscal year, starting July 1, that will double to $1.8  
billion under the plan approved by the state Budget and Control 
Board on May 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1895, after the state was swindled by investments in canal  
and rail project stocks, South Carolina had a constitutional 
provision prohibiting equity investments. Voters changed that three 
years ago to allow stock market investments by the plan that covers 
more than 200,000 teachers, state employees and local government 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The almost $918 million first investment represents about 5  
percent of the South Carolina Retirement System's $18 billion. It 
will be put in a portfolio that tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 
Index, according to the plan drawn up by the Retirement System's 
investment advisory panel. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina eventually wants to invest about 40 percent of  
its retirement fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
