<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Want To Police Agents Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Don't take money from agents.  
</P>
<P>
	It's one of the most basic rules for an athlete on a college  
campus, one drilled into the minds of players as frequently as the 
nonstop warnings about gambling, drugs and alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there's nothing stopping players from talking to agents.  
And there seem to be dozens of ways to skirt the rules once the 
parties come in contact. 
</P>
<P>
	It means that anywhere there's an athletic program with a few  
good athletes, almost surely there's a director for compliance 
trying to keep track of which agent, or which agent's runner, is 
contacting which player at any given time. 
</P>
<P>
	``As salaries escalate in pro sports, it seems there are more  
sports agents today than there were five or 10 years ago,'' said 
Jamie McCloskey, associate athletic director for compliance at 
Florida. ``That means there are more individuals we need to police. 
Unfortunately, some are more ethical than others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida is the latest school to encounter problems, with a sworn  
complaint filed against one agent for allegedly paying players. 
Investigations are ongoing into activities of at least two other 
agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida is hardly alone. Alabama is just shaking off the effects  
of a probation stemming from an agent problem that cropped up six 
years ago. Since then, Florida State's football program has 
encountered problems. So has Connecticut's basketball team. 
Accusations are being investigated at LSU. The list goes on and on. 
</P>
<P>
	Longtime agent Frank Bauer has a reputation for doing things the  
right way. He says most agents are trustworthy, but the ones trying 
to break into the business are at a severe disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got people going out, starting firms representing  
athletes, who have no credentials and no clients,'' Bauer said. 
``So the question is, How do you get that client? When that starts 
up, sometimes they feel like they have to induce a client to go to 
their side. That's when you get a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only agent formally accused of wrongdoing at Florida was  
allegedly involved in something that no school could adequately 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sworn complaint filed by university police, agent Sean  
Alfortish is accused of funneling money to two football players 
through the players' roommate. Neither player was considered a 
major NFL prospect. The roommate likely never made it onto the 
school's radar until the alleged violation occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Enticements can range from beer money, to a couple hundred bucks  
to a several-thousand-dollar advance on future earnings. Some 
agents also dispense advice that directly attacks the integrity of 
the game: don't risk an injury that would jeopardize your pro 
career; get your coach to ``showcase'' you; ask to switch to the 
position NFL scouts want you to play in the pros. 
</P>
<P>
	Like several other states, Florida has a law against unlicensed  
and illegal agent activity. In March, the NFL Players Association 
approved a bylaw that forced an agent to forfeit any fee he would 
receive if he is proven to have offered an illegal inducement to 
earn a player's business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an example of more attention being paid to the problem  
by people who want to clean this thing up,'' said Tom DePaso, staff 
counsel for the NFLPA. ``I don't know if the problem has grown 
worse in the last four or five years, but there's a lot more 
attention being paid to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Often, the agent never even has to show up on campus to make an  
impact. The inducement can be funneled through a runner, sometimes 
a student or friend of a player. 
</P>
<P>
	That simply increases the list of people schools try to monitor.  
Because it is such a vast group, some believe it will take more 
than a new law or two to solve the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``The basic issue is you have kids who are being exploited by  
the schools,'' said Leonard Mungo, an attorney for agent Tank 
Black, who is being investigated, but has not been charged, by 
Florida and the NFLPA. 
</P>
<P>
	``These players know what they're worth and they know the  
schools are taking advantage,'' Mungo said. ``Then, you have 900 
agents out there looking to sign 240 players who get drafted. Not 
every agent can afford to play by the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCloskey knows that. And he knows he's not the only one who is  
squirming as the list of new agents, and new accusations, continues 
to grow. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were an issue at Florida and nowhere else, it would  
probably be a good thing for athletics as a whole,'' he said. ``But 
it's an issue that has potential to be a problem on many different 
campuses. And it's getting harder to control every day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
