<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young Bruins Setting Foundation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Getting eliminated in the second round left the  
Boston Bruins short of their playoff goal. Getting that far, 
though, was a sign of how far they've come in just two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Burns took over as coach of a team that had the NHL's worst  
record in 1996-97 and led it to the first round, where it lost to 
Washington last season. 
</P>
<P>
	And this season, he brought the Bruins into the second round,  
where they were knocked out Tuesday night with a 3-2 loss in 
Buffalo that gave the Sabres the series, four games to two. 
</P>
<P>
	Next season?  
</P>
<P>
	``We're on the right course,'' Burns said Wednesday. ``The ship  
was going the wrong way. Now it's going the right way. Now we need 
to make sure the right sailors are on board and we're tying the 
right knots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense, still led by Ray Bourque, is solid. Goalie Byron  
Dafoe had an outstanding season. Joe Thornton, who struggled as a 
rookie after being taken with the first pick of the 1997 draft, 
blossomed this season, although 1998 NHL rookie of the year Sergei 
Samsonov faltered in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins could use an extra scorer or two and some more  
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can grow together as a team,'' said 24-year-old wing Anson  
Carter, who had a career-high 24 goals. ``It will be that much more 
rewarding when we reach the pinnacle because everyone comes from 
the same beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bourque may not be around to get there.  
</P>
<P>
	At 38, he just completed his 20th season and is a candidate for  
his sixth Norris Trophy as the NHL's best defenseman. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he still hasn't won a Stanley Cup. He said Wednesday he  
will play out the final year of his contract next season before 
deciding whether to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know my best years are behind me. I know that I didn't have  
my best series against Buffalo,'' he said. ``I'll be around next 
year and you never know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston struggled into the second half of the season and was  
22-24-9 on Feb. 18. But it was 17-6-4 in its remaining 27 games and 
beat Carolina, four games to two, in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the final six weeks, we did everything to get us into the  
first round and we fought to get through the first round,'' Burns 
said, ``but then we couldn't get through the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins won the opener of the Buffalo series. But the Sabres  
won three straight before Boston stayed alive with a 5-3 win Sunday 
in which Dominik Hasek allowed four goals in two periods. The NHL's 
best goalie was in form in the Sabres' clinching win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if they're better. They played with more  
desire,'' said Dafoe, who led the league with 10 shutouts and was 
third in goals against average. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Harry Sinden questioned the team's effort and  
criticized Jason Allison, his top regular-season scorer, and Dmitri 
Khristich, who led the team in goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Khristich was a total, total disappointment,'' Sinden said  
after the final game. ``I don't think Allison was the player he was 
last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But with Allison, Carter, Samsonov and Thornton, the Bruins have  
the potential to become more of an offensive threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us have to get better each year,'' said the 19-year-old  
Thornton, who did that this season when he was Boston's fifth 
leading scorer and added three goals in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 27th straight season, the Bruins failed to win the  
Stanley Cup. But they're much closer than they were two years ago 
when they were the league's worst team. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys don't have experience going through rounds and  
winning rounds,'' Bourque said, but ``it was a successful season 
because a lot of guys battled and took on bigger roles and we'll 
need that in years to come.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
