<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:41:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFLPA Files Complaint Against Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The NFL Players Association filed a  
disciplinary complaint Wednesday against agent William ``Tank'' 
Black, who, in turn, plans to petition the U.S. Attorney's office 
to investigate the union's action. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFLPA, through its agent disciplinary committee, alleged  
that Black provided improper cash payments in 1997 and 1998 to 
college players before their eligibility was completed. The 
complaint also claimed Black acquired new autos in 1998 for players 
before their college eligibility expired. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of my biggest priorities as NFLPA president,'' said Miami  
Dolphins defensive end Trace Armstrong, ``has been to crack down on 
agents who violate the rules and damage the players' best 
interests. We are anxious to see what Mr. Black has to say about 
these charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Black must answer the complaint within 30 days, under NFLPA  
regulations. He took a step toward doing so by threatening a 
lawsuit, along with his planned petition to the U.S. Attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``We absolutely and categorically deny the allegations raised by  
the NFLPA,'' said Leonard Mungo, Black's lawyer, ``and look forward 
to responding to each and every one. It remains our intention to 
file a lawsuit in federal district court'' asking the court to take 
jurisdiction over the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a classic case of the fox watching the hen house,''  
Mungo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mungo questioned the involvement of the University of Florida,  
which along with the players association and the Southeastern 
Conference are investigating allegations that Black illegally 
recruited college players. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will also petition the U.S. Attorney's office to  
investigate the impropriety of a private agency such as the NFLPA 
using the police powers of the state (of Florida) to violate a 
citizen's constitutional and civil rights. In our opinion, the 
NFLPA has acted unlawfully by exploiting and abusing the police 
powers of a state agency -- the University of Florida -- and the 
state attorney's office to violate Mr. Black's due process and 
other civil rights under the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based agent Ray Anderson accused Black in January of  
offering LSU assistant coach Mike Haywood $10,000 to secure 
defensive lineman Anthony McFarland as a client. Black has denied 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida campus police are investigating possible violations of  
state recruiting laws involving Jevon Kearse, Reggie McGrew, Johnny 
Rutledge and Mike Peterson. Kearse and McGrew were first-round 
picks, while Peterson and Rutledge were second-round selections. 
</P>
<P>
	All recently left Black, which Mungo said cost Black at least  
$650,000 -- money the lawyer said he would try to recover once the 
investigations are complete. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our board passed a resolution in March which states that any  
agent who has offered improper inducements to a player is not 
entitled to collect a fee for negotiating that player's NFL 
contract,'' union general counsel Richard Berthelsen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roy, Forsberg Help Avs Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- For two years, Colorado languished in the shadow  
of the Detroit Red Wings, watching enviously as they supplanted the 
Avalanche as Stanley Cup champions and then won back-to-back 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no three-peat for the Red Wings, however, as the  
Avalanche finally vanquished their bitter rivals in six games in 
the Western Conference semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	After spotting Detroit a 2-0 series lead, the Avalanche won four  
in a row. Now, they face the team with the best regular-season 
record in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado will meet the Dallas Stars in Game 1 of the conference  
finals on Saturday night in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long couple of years for us,'' Avalanche  
defenseman Adam Foote said, ``but that's over for us against that 
team now. It's just very, very sweet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Forsberg scored two goals as the Avalanche beat Detroit  
5-2 Tuesday night to advance. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Forsberg clearly justified his new $30 million  
contract with his all-around play in the last four games, it was 
goalie Patrick Roy who was the catalyst for Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy, whose 12th career playoff shutout led Colorado to a 3-0  
victory in Game 5 in Denver on Sunday, made 35 saves Tuesday night, 
many of them brilliant when the game was close. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an awesome feeling, coming back from 0-2,'' Forsberg  
said. ``Everybody's been stepping up, from the last guy to the 
first guy. And Patrick's been great in net.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avs coach Bob Hartley agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick is Patrick,'' Hartley said. ``He was outstanding. I'm  
not surprised with the way he played. I grew up around Montreal and 
I saw him win with the Canadiens (Stanley Cup titles in 1986 and 
1993). I saw him win a Stanley Cup with the Avalanche (1996). He's 
rock solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Colorado lost the first two games of the series at home  
and appeared on the verge of being swept, Roy stopped 146 of 153 
shots as Colorado won four in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win four straight against Detroit -- I didn't think it was  
possible, to be honest,'' Roy said. ``But we had no choice. We put 
ourselves in a really bad position, losing those two games in 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great comeback for us, being down 2-0. We took it one  
game at a time and played some great hockey. We won three games in 
Detroit, and it's not every team that can do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blessed with talented skaters and puck-handlers, the Avalanche  
faltered early in the series with Detroit when they tried to get 
fancy, making too many passes or attempting the highlight-video 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played simple hockey,'' Roy said. ``That's how we won this  
series. It was a good series, and great for us to beat that team. 
They were the Stanley Cup champions, and we beat them. It feels 
good, but now we've got another series against another very tough 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartley called the Stars ``a great hockey club. They are the  
regular-season champions and they're going to be a great challenge 
for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the bad blood that has defined Colorado-Detroit meetings  
since 1996, the Red Wings were gracious in defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you lose four straight like we did, you can't say the other  
team was lucky,'' Detroit coach Scotty Bowman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can look at it as we underachieved,'' Red Wings captain  
Steve Yzerman said. ``Or you can look at it as we got beat by a 
great team. I choose to look at it as Colorado played fantastic. 
</P>
<P>
	``They made great adjustments from the first two games to the  
last four. Their top players played very well at both ends of the 
rink. Joe Sakic was excellent on penalty killing, on faceoffs, and 
he did all the little things well. 
</P>
<P>
	``They got production from all four lines, their defense is good  
and their goaltender was very solid. They did all the things 
through the last four games that are necessary, not just to beat 
good teams, but to win the Stanley Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While only 2-4 at home during the postseason this year, the Avs  
can take comfort in the fact they're 6-0 on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Stars' 51-19-12 regular-season record, Colorado  
compiled a 2-1-1 record against them. Dallas defeated St. Louis in 
six games to advance to the next round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:44:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ferraro Benefit Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A fund-raiser featuring President Clinton that  
was organized to pay off Geraldine Ferraro's campaign debt was 
canceled due to dismal ticket sales 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ferraro said sales were poor because her supporters had  
already contributed the maximum allowed under the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has nothing to do with the president -- he's a sweetie for  
offering to do this,'' Ms. Ferraro said Tuesday. ``I don't think 
it's him. I don't think it's me. I don't think it's Sen. Schumer,'' 
who was also scheduled to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit had been scheduled for Wednesday evening in New  
York. Organizers had hoped to have 400 people attend at $1,000 a 
head, but only about 100 people had bought tickets, according to 
Patricia Evert, the event producer who was putting the dinner 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ferraro still has about $1 million in unpaid bills from her  
unsuccessful bid to become a 1998 Democratic candidate for U.S. 
Senate. She lost in the primary to Charles Schumer, who went on to 
defeat Republican Alfonse D'Amato and capture the seat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:49:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic OKs 'Principles' of Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic accepted elements of a Kosovo peace plan Wednesday, but 
insisted in talks with a Russian envoy that the details must be 
negotiated directly with the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	That would appear to fall short of Western conditions for  
halting the eight-week bombing campaign -- unequivocal acceptance of 
the international plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the envoy flew out of the Yugoslav capital late  
Wednesday night, NATO warplanes launched their strongest attack in 
two weeks against the Belgrade area. Local media and witnesses said 
a hospital near a Belgrade military barracks was hit, killing at 
least three people. 
</P>
<P>
	The state-run news agency Tanjug said an operating room in the  
hospital was demolished and that rescuers were evacuating infants 
and pregnant women from the maternity ward. Witnesses said the 
hospital's neurological building was directly hit and an intensive 
care unit was leveled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambulances raced to the area to ferry victims to other hospitals  
from the two units, which were reduced to empty, smoking shells, 
witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedish ambassador's residence, located near the hospital,  
was also damaged when the blast from an explosion around 200 yards 
away blew out a few windows and a door, a Swedish Foreign Ministry 
spokesman said. There were no injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	State-controlled media said airstrikes elsewhere in Serbia  
earlier in the day killed six people. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin gave no indication of a  
breakthrough after nearly eight hours of talks with Milosevic, 
telling Russian reporters afterwards that it was ``most important 
to return Yugoslavia to the negotiating table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said any peace deal must be based on a plan put forward two  
weeks ago by the Group of Eight nations, which comprise the world's 
top industrialized countries and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the meeting, Chernomyrdin urged NATO and Belgrade to halt  
the bombing and the military operations in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	A brief statement from Milosevic's office said ``the solution  
could be found only politically and within the U.N. and with direct 
participation of Yugoslavia, starting from the G-8 principles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those demands include a total withdrawal of Serb forces from  
Kosovo and the deployment of an international security force. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic has so far rejected demands that the security force be  
armed. And the G-8 itself is divided over the plan's call for an 
``international security presence'' to police any agreement. The 
United States says that means an armed military force with NATO at 
its core. The Russians have not accepted that definition. It also 
does not define the size of a Serb withdrawal from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin was next to meet U.S. Deputy Secretary of State  
Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari in Moscow on 
Thursday to brief them on the Belgrade meeting. The three met 
Tuesday and earlier Wednesday in Helsinki. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the State Department said it was waiting to hear  
Chernomyrdin's report before reacting. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO demands for peace are similar to those of the G-8:  
withdrawal of Milosevic's 40,000-strong Serb forces, the return of 
nearly 800,000 ethnic Albanians who have been driven out by 
``ethnic cleansing'' or fled, and the deployment of a well-armed 
international peacekeeping force with NATO at its core. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, envoys from the G-8 group gathered in Bonn to try to  
draw up a U.N. resolution codifying their peace plan. After 12 
hours of talks, delegates said they were still divided on some 
details -- particularly the makeup of an international force. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important that Milosevic and the Belgrade authorities  
understand NATO's resolve,'' White House press secretary Joe 
Lockhart said in Washington. ``I think you are seeing almost any 
place you look now signs of problems for Milosevic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department said there was increasing opposition to  
Milosevic's handling of the Kosovo crisis, saying as many as 500 
Serb soldiers have deserted in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In reports of new dissent, an independent newspaper, Glas  
Javnosti, said protest rallies in the southern city of Krusevac 
occurred for the second straight day Tuesday by families of men 
drafted to serve in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement by the army garrison command in Krusevac condemned  
organizers of the protests as ``traitors'' and accused them of 
``undermining the defense of the country and collaboration with the 
enemy.'' Local sources said six were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters are barred from traveling outside Belgrade without  
government permission, and the reports could not be independently 
confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian opposition leader Zoran Djindjic said the protests took  
place, adding on Austrian radio that people do ``not want to die 
blindly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials have spoken of growing dissent in Yugoslavia over  
Milosevic's handling of the Kosovo crisis, but his government 
insists the country is fully united behind him in the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade says it has started withdrawing troops from Kosovo, but  
NATO officials say there is no evidence of a significant pullout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The enemy is now trying to find among us supporters of  
capitulation and traitors,'' the Krusevac command's statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO strikes on Belgrade late Wednesday also targeted the  
suburbs of Rakovica and Batajnica, where a key military airport is 
located. Also reportedly hit were industrial zones in Baric, about 
12 miles southeast of Belgrade and Sabac, 30 miles west, the 
reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong detonation was heard in the plush Belgrade district of  
Dedinje, the area where Milosevic lives and works, when NATO 
missiles hit an army barracks there, Serbian media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Strikes earlier in the day caused huge damage as well as deaths,  
Yugoslav media reported. Four people died in an attack on an office 
building in Gnjilane, a Kosovo town 25 miles southeast of the 
capital, Pristina, Tanjug, the state-controlled news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two prisoners were killed and two inmates and a guard were  
injured when NATO jets attacked a jail in Istok, northwestern 
Kosovo, the Serb Media Center reported in the provincial capital, 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav media also said alliance planes bombed an abandoned  
hotel in Pec, in the western part of the province, injuring four 
employees at an adjacent brewery. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other reported attacks, 25 missiles slammed into Raska in  
the fiercest attack yet on the southern Serbian city. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO campaign began March 24, 13 months after Milosevic's  
forces clamped down on Kosovo, killing at least 2,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 100 men in black leather jackets hurled stones and eggs at  
the headquarters of the main opposition Democratic Party, which has 
been castigated for opposing Milosevic's repression of ethnic 
Albanians in Kosovo. Protesters dispersed when police arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, in a hint of seeking peace, Yugoslav Foreign  
Ministry spokesman Nebojsa Vujovic said Belgrade is ready ``to cut 
a deal'' as long as the country's ``territorial integrity'' is 
preserved -- meaning no independence for Kosovo, a province of 
Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Macedonia, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan visited  
Stenkovec, the largest ethnic Albanian refugee camp, where he was 
cheered by refugees and expressed hopes for peace soon in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The second train of refugees in two days arrived at the  
Macedonian border. U.N. aid officials said nearly 2,500 people 
arrived over the previous 24 hours following a several day lull. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 11:31:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Group To Use Ill. 'Garage' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARRINGTON, Ill. (AP) -- A couple beset by complaints after they  
bought an extra house near their son's high school just so he could 
have a place to park are letting a support group for single mothers 
use the home. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Chilakamarri Yeshwant, an oncologist, and his wife,  
Akhileswari, an internist, bought a $157,000 bungalow near 
Barrington High School so their son, Srinu, could park his new 
truck in the driveway. 
</P>
<P>
	The family lives in a larger home in South Barrington. With the  
parking place at the bungalow, Srinu can sleep later because he 
doesn't have to fight for a spot in the school lot. 
</P>
<P>
	But neighbors said they resented how the house was nothing but a  
parking lot for the boy and five of his friends. Town officials 
began investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	Upset by the negative publicity, the Yeshwants agreed to lease  
the house for free to a not-for-profit agency called Women in Need 
Growing Stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors seemed to approve of the plan. And Susie Duboe-Bryant,  
president of the women's group, said Srinu -- but not his friends -- 
can still park in the driveway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
