<HEADLINE> Washington State Players Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Washington State starting running back  
Kevin Brown and two teammates were charged Wednesday with 
residential burglary and theft by the Whitman County prosecutor's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, Jason M. White and Ramin J. White, who are not related,  
will be arraigned on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The players were arrested early Sunday morning for investigation  
of burglary and theft at a student's apartment. They are free on 
their own recognizance. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were arrested after witnesses said they saw them enter  
an apartment through an unlocked back door and leave with a laptop 
computer and other electronics gear, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said $1,900 worth of electronics equipment was recovered,  
including 72 compact discs. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Price and athletic director Rick Dickson have  
declined to comment on the arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 20, of West Covina, Calif., was the Cougars' top  
offensive threat last season, rushing for 1,046 yards, a sophomore 
team record. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramin White, 19, will be a freshman and Jason White, 20, will be  
a sophomore this coming season. Ramin White is a Cougars running 
back and Jason White is a wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	The players each face six to 12 months in jail if convicted of  
the felony counts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
