<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:41:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Gun Control Concessions Offered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans offered fresh concessions  
on gun control Wednesday night, but the Clinton administration and 
Democrats swiftly said they didn't go far enough to plug gaps that 
allow some criminals to obtain weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	A draft amendment circulated by the GOP calls for background  
checks on all purchasers at gun shows, including transactions 
exempted in a proposal that Republicans muscled through the Senate 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the proposal would establish a requirement for a  
mandatory background check for anyone seeking to reclaim their own 
weapon at a pawnshop. 
</P>
<P>
	The concessions marked the latest in a series of retreats by the  
GOP in the wake of last month's shooting spree at a Colorado high 
school and a renewed push by Democrats for more restrictions on 
firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	But administration officials prepared a long list of additional  
issues the proposal didn't address, and one Democrat said 
Republicans were merely attempting to ``fill another leaky boat.... 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't get it,'' Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., said of  
Republicans. ``The public gets it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GOP aides, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said party  
leaders hoped that passage of the proposal would persuade enough 
wavering Republicans to help kill a stronger set of provisions 
advanced by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the maneuvering has occurred on legislation to crack down  
on juvenile crime, a measure that was brought to the floor to allow 
lawmakers to stage a debate over gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	A week of almost ceaseless political combat over the issue was  
briefly interrupted during the day when lawmakers approved creating 
a national Commission on Character Development to study the impact 
of cultural influences on good citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel -- to include one student and one parent among 36  
members -- would have two years to present Congress with 
recommendations for legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Public opinion polling has shown strong support for more gun  
restrictions in the wake of last month's shootings in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	While making the latest in a series of retreats, Republicans  
indicated they were drawing the line. GOP aides said the latest 
amendment had been drafted in a meeting with top Senate Republicans 
earlier Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats also have revived their proposal from a week ago to  
try and attract GOP support. 
</P>
<P>
	Their latest version removes some of the government record  
keeping and other red tape proposed in connection with gun show 
purchases. But it also would give the government three days to 
conduct a background check -- rather than 24 hours proposed by 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats also want to wait 90 days before expunging background  
check records in cases where the purchases are approved. The GOP 
wants immediate destruction of all records. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Republicans forced defeat of a Democratic call for  
mandatory background checks for all gun show purchasers, and 
approved their own alternative, approved by the National Rifle 
Association, calling for optional checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Within 24 hours, the GOP backpedaled under pressure, and  
approved a substitute that they said would make background checks 
mandatory at shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said that measure contained a loophole and would  
continue to permit unlicensed dealers to sell weapons without 
conducting a background check on the purchaser. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, they said it would permit individuals to sell their  
guns at pawnshops and reclaim them without undergoing a check. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., said the proposal would allow  
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to impose a new fee on 
gun purchasers. He also said the three-day period for a background 
check could halt otherwise qualified sales if the show closed 
before the check was completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The national commission was part of an amendment introduced by  
Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. The proposal underscored an effort by 
Republicans to turn attention toward cultural influences on young 
people, particularly in the wake of the shootings in Littleton, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission would be charged with studying ``the impact of  
current cultural influences ... on the process of developing and 
instilling the key aspects of character, which include 
trust-worthiness, honesty. integrity, an ability to keep promises, 
loyalty, respect, responsibility, fairness, a caring nature and 
good citizenship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel would include members of the clergy as well as  
representatives of law enforcement, the information industry and 
the entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate struggle, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, argued at  
length against a proposal by Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., to give 
school officials greater leeway in disciplining students with 
disabilities who bring guns to schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Harkin refused to agree to limit debate, at one point telling  
inquiring Republicans he needed to continue speaking ``Because I am 
so poor at getting across my point, it seems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
