<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Outlook Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- The Finance Ministry on Wednesday noted  
signs that Germany's long-sluggish economy could be on the rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter gross domestic product may show a slight rise from  
the previous quarter, the ministry said in a summary of its May 
monthly report. 
</P>
<P>
	The optimistic report also noted that price development remained  
stable, attributing an unusual 0.4 percent rise in consumer prices 
in April to a new environmental tax that drove up the cost of gas 
and oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, Europe's biggest economy, has been battling record-high  
unemployment -- 10.7 in April -- and slow economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Hans Eichel has called for government spending  
cuts and reiterated projections of 1.5 percent growth this year, 
revised downward from 2 percent at the end of April. 
</P>
<P>
	While a single month's developments were not enough to diagnose  
a sure improvement, the ministry said several factors pointed to 
increased economic momentum and the possibility for increased GDP 
in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The report noted: an improved business climate in western  
Germany's manufacturing sector in March; slight improvements in 
exports in the first quarter after setbacks in the previous two 
quarters; and continued growth in retail sales for the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the ministry noted that more steps are needed to improve  
the situation in the labor market beyond seasonal changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
