<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New-Look AT&AMP;T Hosts Shareholders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. hasn't stopped spending yet.  
</P>
<P>
	Having already committed $100 billion to acquisitions for its  
new cable-telephone strategy, the company is still shopping around 
for investments, the company said Wednesday at its annual 
shareholders meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and chief executive C. Michael Armstrong also stressed  
that AT&AMP;T needs a smooth transition at Tele-Communications Inc. and 
MediaOne Group, the two cable TV companies already being acquired. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest challenge for us is to execute against the  
potential of all these acquisitions,'' he said, referring to the 
company's ambitious plan to use cable TV wires for both phone and 
Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T president John Zeglis added that the company likely will  
make more investments in foreign companies, as it has in Canada and 
Japan, to expand its global network. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said it has begun testing a new wireless  
service in Dallas using a pizza box-sized receiver for local and 
long-distance calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The past year has seen AT&AMP;T acquire TCI, the nation's second  
biggest cable company, and strike a deal to buy No. 4 MediaOne 
after winning a bidding war last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Including all pending agreements, AT&AMP;T would surpass Time Warner  
as the nation's top cable operator, with 16 million subscribers and 
systems capable of reaching more than 25 million homes with cable 
access. 
</P>
<P>
	While AT&AMP;T plans to offer packages of TV, phone and Internet  
service over those cable lines, it is also working on deals to sell 
its phone service to Time Warner and Comcast cable customers. 
</P>
<P>
	If those agreements are finalized, AT&AMP;T phone service may one  
day be available in more than 60 million homes, or about 60 percent 
of the nation. 

</P>
</TEXT>
