<DOCNO> APW19990519.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel OKs GOP Spending Cuts Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans struggled Wednesday over whether  
to deliver billions in spending cuts promised in Congress' 1997 
budget deal with President Clinton as a House committee approved a 
GOP blueprint for doing just that. 
</P>
<P>
	Divided along party lines, the House Appropriations Committee  
adopted a Republican plan for cutting billions from legislation 
covering national parks, schools and other domestic programs for 
fiscal 2000, which starts Oct. 1. The vote was 31-23. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee approved the plan amid complaints by Democrats and  
some Republicans that the cuts were too deep and would produce 
legislation that even the GOP-controlled Congress would reject. 
That would lead to a repeat of last autumn's budget negotiations 
with the White House in which billions of dollars in extra spending 
was approved, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Spending will be pushed through the roof,'' said Rep. John  
Edward Porter, R-Ill. ``It will be the president in the driver's 
seat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Porter is chairman of the Appropriations subcommittee on labor,  
health and education, whose programs would be cut by $10.7 billion 
-- the deepest reduction of all. He was the only committee member to 
abstain from voting. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter said congressional leaders should meet with Clinton and  
seek a compromise on providing more money for the spending bills 
than the balanced-budget agreement allows. Other Republicans 
privately have expressed support for that idea. 
</P>
<P>
	But conservatives are uniting against abandoning the budget pact  
because any extra spending would have to come from the federal 
surplus, which this year comes completely from Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans this year have promised to leave Social Security  
funds for the pension program, and conservatives in particular have 
made that a rallying cry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is we're not going to spend Social Security  
surplus money'' for more domestic spending, said Rep. Nick Smith, 
R-Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives planned a news conference for Thursday to call for  
living within the budget agreement's spending limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee vote was on a plan for dividing $538 billion among  
the 13 annual spending bills the panel writes that keep government 
agencies functioning. Half the money would go to the Pentagon and 
the rest to the 12 other bills, which would get a combined $25 
billion less -- a 9 percent cut -- than they are receiving this year. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said that went too far.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're not sure if it's the sequel or the prequel, but it's the  
same old Republican cuts ... and it's just not going to be 
acceptable,'' said White House spokesman Barry Toiv. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, Sen. Ted  
Stevens, R-Alaska, is proposing similar plans and has predicted 
Congress will reject several spending bills because of excessively 
deep cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Wednesday when he would unveil his plan for dividing up  
the spending, he said, ``As soon as I get more money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Senate planned a Thursday debate on a $15 billion  
measure financing the conflict with Yugoslavia, aid to U.S. farmers 
and other items. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's likely passage would send the bill to Clinton for  
his expected signature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
