<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accused Mom Denies Starving Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tabitha Walrond's voice was just above a whisper  
as she recalled the preparations she made before her son Tyler's 
birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamaze classes, parenting magazines, no smoking or drinking --  
Ms. Walrond even went to night school to get her high school 
diploma. When a fever kept her from nursing just after Tyler was 
born, she said she used a breast pump to ensure her milk would keep 
flowing. 
</P>
<P>
	The image Ms. Walrond, 21, presented as she testified Tuesday at  
her manslaughter trial was starkly different from the one 
prosecutors offered. They say Ms. Walrond starved 2-month-old Tyler 
to death out of spite for her ex-boyfriend, who got another woman 
pregnant after he left her. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond's lawyer, Susan V. Tipograph, says her client had  
trouble nursing because of breast-reduction surgery and didn't 
realize her newborn was losing weight before he died in August 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened to Tyler Walrond was a tragedy and not a  
crime,'' Ms. Tipograph said outside court. 
</P>
<P>
	On cross examination, prosecutor Robert Holdman showed Ms.  
Walrond autopsy photographs of her son's emaciated body -- his tiny 
ribs sticking out, baggy skin hanging off his arms and legs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did he look thin to you?'' the prosecutor asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``He looked the same to me,'' Ms. Walrond replied. ``I didn't  
notice. I really didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Ms. Walrond's failure to act when Tyler dropped  
from his birth weight of nearly eight pounds to about five pounds 
amounted to reckless and negligent homicide. She's charged with 
second-degree manslaughter and could be sentenced to 5 to 15 years 
in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing arguments were scheduled for today.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond said she chose breastfeeding because her family and  
doctors all told her ``breast is best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said no doctor examined the newborn after he left the  
hospital because Medicaid was slow to issue him a card, and her 
health clinic would not examine the baby until the bureaucratic 
problem was resolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
