<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars-Avs Bring Strengths to Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- The Dallas Stars have met every challenge  
on their home ice through two rounds of the Stanley Cup playoffs. 
The Colorado Avalanche have made themselves at home on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Something will have to give Saturday night when the Western  
Conference finals begin in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche are perfect in six road games, the last three  
coming in front of the ruthless fans at Detroit's Joe Louis Arena. 
The Stars are 5-0 in the postseason on the sometimes slushy, uneven 
ice in Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just feel comfortable at home,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock  
said. ``We seem to have a confidence level right now that even when 
we're down in games we can still come back. Hopefully we can 
continue it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche spoiled the Dallas-Detroit showdown many Stars  
fans wanted by winning four straight against the two-time defending 
champion Red Wings. Colorado's roll began after two home losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars are coming off a six-game series against St. Louis.  
Dallas won two at home, lost two in St. Louis, then won one at each 
venue to advance to the conference finals for the second straight 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	It's tempting to say whoever wins this series will win the Cup,  
considering the last three champions have come from the West and 
the Stars and Avalanche have the best records of the four remaining 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas is the No. 1 seed in the West and Colorado second. In the  
East, Toronto is the fourth seed and Buffalo seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche were one of the few teams that won the  
regular-season series against the Stars, going 2-1-1. Colorado won 
the most recent meeting 2-1, but that was the regular season finale 
after both teams' playoff spots were set. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas' only victory was on Dec. 26, when Colorado was  
struggling. Since then, the Avalanche have become a deeper and 
stronger team with the addition of Theo Fleury, a return to health 
by Valeri Kamensky and the postseason blossoming of rookies Chris 
Drury and Milan Hejduk. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock said Colorado's success on the road stems from its  
depth. 
</P>
<P>
	By being able to send out line after line of scorers, the  
Avalanche can play conservatively and wait for scoring chance 
instead of the typical road strategy of going all out to score 
early and mute the home fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you know you've got enough top-end people who can score  
at any time, then you feel like you don't have to put on a show, 
that the other team is eventually going to crack,'' Hitchcock said. 
``If you're the home team, sometimes it can frustrate you. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought that happened to Detroit in Game 6. They were really  
prone to the big error and Colorado really took advantage of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas' strength is in a versatile mix of forwards who are  
committed to playing solid defense and eventually wearing down 
their foes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars do have some top players in Mike Modano, Brett Hull  
and Joe Nieuwendyk, but they can't match the Avalanche player for 
player. So Hitchcock doesn't even want them to try. 
</P>
<P>
	``To go with the attitude of shutting down this guy or that guy  
is unrealistic,'' he said, ``because they have too many.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Detroit-Colorado series ended, Hitchcock said either  
team would be favored over Dallas because both had been playing so 
well since making big trades at the deadline. On Wednesday, his 
players weren't buying it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that we're an underdog,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``A  
lot of people are very impressed with the way Colorado played 
Detroit and the way Patrick Roy is playing. But we've lost only two 
games in the playoffs, both in overtime. So you can't say that 
we're not playing pretty well, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
