<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings Denied Three-Peat Dynasty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The three-peat is gone. Instead, the Red Wings  
start over, taking consolation from the very team that ended their 
chance for another Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at Colorado,'' Red Wings captain Steve Yzerman said.  
``They had to retool a little bit, make some adjustments to their 
team, and they're back playing extremely well and contending again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect us to regroup and be a contender again next year. Our  
goal is to win again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Roy, the winningest goaltender in NHL playoff history,  
baffled the Red Wings during their second-round series. After the 
Red Wings won the first two games, Roy closed the door. As the 
series wore on, he seemed to fill every inch of the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	He was so dominant that when Detroit defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom  
scored at 17:24 of the second period in the sixth and deciding game 
Tuesday night, it ended a scoreless streak of 98 minutes, 7 seconds 
dating to the third period of Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a case of being outplayed,'' Detroit defenseman  
Larry Murphy said. ``Basically, a team had more control of the 
puck, scored and took advantage of their opportunities. It was all 
over then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is a suspicion the Red Wings are showing the first signs  
of age. Murphy and center Igor Larionov are 38 years old. Chris 
Chelios is 37. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, there are young legs. Martin Lapointe is only 25. Tomas  
Holmstron and Kirk Maltby -- whose overtime goal won Game 1 in 
Denver -- are both 26. Darren McCarty and Vyacheslav Kozlov are 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a good nucleus of players,'' coach Scotty Bowman said.  
``Teams are getting better, we know that. But, at the same time, 
the team needs a few adjustments, but not a lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of young players on the team. It's not an  
all-veteran team. It's a mixture. There's enough players in that 
room that have won, and I think the fire's still there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spark that ignites that fire is Bowman, and there is some  
question if he'll return. After 31 seasons, during which he won 
eight Stanley Cups -- with three different teams -- Bowman has hinted 
he might retire. If he does, a front office job awaits. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately after the 5-2 loss to Colorado, however, the  
65-year-old coach spoke as if he might stay behind the bench 
another season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll sit down with the people in Detroit and find out what  
they want,'' Bowman said. ``I've got a hidden goal that I'd like to 
coach in the year 2000. But that's not important right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't be an emotional decision. I'll sit down with the Red  
Wings. I came here for a year or two, and it's been six. If it can 
be longer, it will be longer. If it can't, it can't and I'll go out 
with my head high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There also is concern that Lidstrom, a Norris Trophy finalist  
for the second straight year, might return to Sweden. Lidstrom is 
29 and one of the finest defenseman in the league. His loss would 
leave a void on an otherwise aging defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Some players think the addition of Chelios and Ulf Samuelsson at  
the trading deadline might convince Lidstrom to stay. With someone 
like Chelios on his wing, Lidstrom no longer feels the pressure to 
be Detroit's dominant defender. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those acquisitions definitely helped our team,'' Yzerman said.  
``Not for just this season, but for the next few seasons as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lidstrom said he and his wife, Annika, will make a decision this  
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the earliest the Red Wings have been dialing for tee  
times in four years. Since 1996, they have played in the Western 
Conference finals four times, played in the Cup finals three times, 
winning the title in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was wonderful and all that to win in previous years,''  
Yzerman said. ``But you play for right now, and you're playing for 
this year. So it doesn't really do any good to sit back and feel 
good about previous years because that's over and done with now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
