<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:52:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Not Speaking Softly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nowhere among government documents is the  
Powell doctrine listed. It isn't a doctrine, insists retired Army 
Gen. Colin Powell, it's only ``common sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The national security adviser to President Reagan and chairman  
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff under President Bush calls his 
``doctrine'' an update to the advice of a third former Republican 
president -- Theodore Roosevelt's ``speak softly and carry a big 
stick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of Kosovo policy say the Powell doctrine's basic tenets  
-- first set clear political goals and then use overwhelming force 
to achieve victory -- are being ignored in the nearly two-month-old 
Balkans conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, a political moderate, suggests NATO has  
inverted Roosevelt's mantra. 
</P>
<P>
	``It spoke sharply and carried a stick which is one of the most  
counterproductive foreign policies of this century,'' Leach said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than ending civil violence in the Serbian province of  
Kosovo, Leach contends NATO's mixture of belligerent rhetoric and 
air-power-only might has spawned a ``hot war'' with Yugoslavia and 
two new cold wars, with Russia and China. 
</P>
<P>
	Powell may deny his doctrine exists on paper, but he has no  
trouble describing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you have ... clear political objectives, then let your  
military people come forward and give you a plan that will achieve 
those objectives in as quick and decisive a way as possible,'' he 
told a National Press Club audience on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Powell cited two examples during his watch as Joint Chiefs  
chairman: Bush's invasion of Panama in 1989 to capture Panamanian 
dictator Manuel Noriega and the 1991 Gulf War to drive Iraqi 
invaders from Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, Powell does not think the current conflict  
meets the terms of the Powell doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
	The political goals are not clear-cut and the political means of  
achieving them are ``far more difficult,'' depending on a consensus 
among 19 NATO democracies. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Powell said he wouldn't personally have taken the  
military ground forces option off the table, as NATO appears to 
have done. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kosovo is a textbook lesson in how not to use military  
force,'' said Richard Haas, a top National Security Council 
official in the Bush administration. ``You have at times 
unrealizable goals: the protection of the people of Kosovo, and the 
force you're willing to apply is, simply, inadequate to the task.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haas is now a Brookings Institution analyst.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Powell doctrine is the accepted critique among the  
military over what went wrong in Vietnam and what went right in the 
Persian Gulf,'' said John Hillen, an analyst for the Center for 
Strategic and International Studies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hillen said there is also ``a caricature of the true Powell  
doctrine, which is that the military only does the fun wars, the 
big wars and the wars where victory is assured, it's quick, and at 
a relatively small cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That view is held by some administration supporters, who suggest  
the Powell doctrine, if followed too strictly, would sharply limit 
the use of military force. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J., said the air war will succeed,  
if just given enough time. 
</P>
<P>
	Back from a three-day visit to the region and to NATO  
headquarters in Brussels, Lautenberg said Tuesday that he can 
understand why public opinion polls show rising support for moving 
toward a negotiated settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's taking longer than anyone expected,'' Lautenberg said.  
</P>
<P>
	But he said the air campaign is slowly succeeding. ``I came away  
with a better understanding of what the process is. I have more 
patience than when I left on this trip,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon said, ``We do our  
best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a military goal to meet. We're doing our best to meet  
that goal with as little collateral damage (damage to civilians) as 
possible. But, I stressed ... this is conflict and casualties are 
impossible to avoid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Powell himself conceded the possibility that the airpower-alone  
strategy ``may work'' in the end. He suggested there's no point in 
being too doctrinaire about doctrines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing in the Powell doctrine says no casualties. And you  
should have some idea of how you would like to see it end, but 
nothing in the Powell doctrine says you've got to have a precise 
exit strategy,'' said the retired four-star general, who is now 
leading a volunteer private-sector effort to help disadvantaged 
youth. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international  
affairs for The Associated Press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With John Pizzarelli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Pizzarelli grew up in New Jersey with his  
father, jazz guitarist Bucky Pizzarelli, who always played music 
around the house. The only time his father's guitar was in its case 
was when he took it along on a gig. 
</P>
<P>
	But the first instrument Pizzarelli learned to play was tenor  
banjo. His banjo-playing uncles were his teachers. He also played 
trumpet in his high school band. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was 20, his father suggested that he listen to  
recordings by the Nat ``King'' Cole Trio. Cole sang and played jazz 
piano. Pizzarelli loved ``Paper Moon,'' ``Straighten Up and Fly 
Right'' and ``Route 66.'' He started singing in Cole's laid-back 
manner. He recorded ``Dear Mr. Cole,'' his best-selling CD, in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli, 38, has five CDs in recent release, including the  
soundtrack for ``The Out-of-Towners,'' starring Steve Martin and 
Goldie Hawn. In the movie, the John Pizzarelli Trio plays ``That 
Old Black Magic'' at New York's Tavern on the Green restaurant. 
Pizzarelli's younger brother, Martin, who plays bass, and drummer 
Ray Kennedy, are the other members of the trio. 
</P>
<P>
	The guitarist-singer can also be heard on ``John Pizzarelli  
Meets the Beatles,'' his new CD released by RCA, and ``Contrasts,'' 
on Arbors Records, with his father. 
</P>
<P>
	1. What kind of places do you most often appear?  
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli: Mostly nightclubs and pops concerts. We've performed  
with the Boston Pops, Atlanta Symphony, San Diego Symphony, 
Indianapolis Symphony. We do college concerts and arts festival 
places like the Wheeler Opera House in Aspen, Colo. We cover the 
gamut. We've gone to Japan more than once and all around Europe. 
This summer we'll play at the Umbria Jazz Festival in Italy for 
several nights in different venues. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Did you always want to play jazz?  
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli: I sang in rock bands in high school. I thought I was  
going to be Billy Joel. I started singing Nat Cole's music in the 
early 1980s. His trio inspired me. Working with my dad, playing 
jazz, and hearing Nat, that had all the elements of what I wanted 
to do as a musician. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Why did you record a CD of Beatles songs?  
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli: We did one Beatles song, 'Honey Pie,' out of 12  
songs on 'Our Love Is Here To Stay,' our last previous album, and a 
lot of people mentioned it particularly. I thought, 'Maybe we'll 
record 11 or 12 and do them in my style. Maybe it'll bring Beatles 
fans as well as jazz fans to the same place.' The idea was not to 
scare anyone away. It worked out as well as I wanted it to, 
actually. I sing on all but one. We do 'Eleanor Rigby' as an 
instrumental. I've had at least one instrumental on each album. 
</P>
<P>
	4. You've recorded with a big band. Do you ever perform live  
with a big band? 
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli: We go to places where we bring the rhythm section  
and pick up a band. That works. One of the best was in Osaka, 
Japan. They didn't speak much English. I communicated to them by 
naming musicians I liked. I'd say to the tenor player, 'Zoot Sims.' 
He'd smile and nod his head. He knew what I was talking about. 
</P>
<P>
	5. Most jazz players don't become famous. How important is fame  
to you? 
</P>
<P>
	Pizzarelli: Jazz never goes out of style. It is treating me  
well. There's no reason to do anything else. I perform enough, 
around the world, to make a living. I like what we do. I really do. 
I think if I were playing rock 'n' roll, it wouldn't be genuine to 
me. I don't have the knowledge. I know what I'm doing now because 
of my dad. I feel like we're authentic and part of a line. I can 
trust myself playing the way I play. Fame would be great but I 
think we're doing pretty well. Eventually, I figure, everybody is 
going to get to hear us. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
