<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 17:51:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady May Form Sen. Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's close friends and  
advisers expect her to form an exploratory campaign committee next 
month, taking a dramatic step closer to running for the Senate in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Two longtime associates, both speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said this week the first lady has told them she intends 
to form the committee, which would allow her to raise and spend 
money while determining whether to seek the seat of retiring 
Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	But a senior adviser intimately familiar with Mrs. Clinton's  
decision-making process said Wednesday that Mrs. Clinton has not 
directed her political or legal teams to form the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Final word on the matter is not expected before she and  
President Clinton return from a brief Florida vacation May 30, the 
adviser said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton plans to use that time to discuss the race with the  
president and their daughter, Chelsea, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The adviser said while it was not likely, it still was possible  
Mrs. Clinton could decide this month not to seek the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	She is more likely to return from vacation and remain mum on her  
intentions, continuing to explore the race and moving ever closer 
to a full-fledged campaign, the three sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	If she takes this route, political and legal considerations  
would force Mrs. Clinton to form an exploratory committee almost 
immediately, the adviser said. 
</P>
<P>
	All three sources said Mrs. Clinton's staff and advisers now  
believe she is more likely than not to run. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's supporters long have suspected she would form an  
exploratory committee. The matter took on greater importance after 
she began to be criticized for traveling to New York at taxpayers' 
expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Forming a committee would allow Mrs. Clinton to raise money to  
help finance the trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Arranging for the first lady to travel is expensive, though the  
full costs never are disclosed. Mrs. Clinton goes with a Secret 
Service entourage and a handful of aides, staying at pricey hotels 
and flying aboard government planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the exploratory committee, taxpayers would cover most  
of her costs. Under federal policy, campaigns do not pay the full 
cost of flying government planes or providing Secret Service 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless Mrs. Clinton rules out the bid in June, she is not  
expected formally to enter the race for weeks or months. Friends 
and advisers, however, say it would be difficult to turn away from 
the race once she forms an exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	She determined weeks ago that a Senate seat would be a good  
platform for her advocacy of children and women's issues and a 
steppingstone for a potential long-term goal -- seeking the 
presidency. Associates also say Mrs. Clinton knows she could lose 
the race, and is increasingly willing to take that risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Her most likely GOP rival, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,  
would be a formidable candidate. Aides to GOP Gov. George Pataki 
say he plans to make a major political announcement next week, 
stirring rumors that he might seek the seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the potential hurdles to the race are the logistics of  
running for the Senate in New York while being first lady, one of 
the associates said. 
</P>
<P>
	A second associate, a longtime ally who would prefer that she  
not seek the seat, said Mrs. Clinton has told friends the 
opportunity may be too good to pass up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
