<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:29:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retirees' Taxes May Not Drop Much </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Most people assume that their cost of living --  
including their taxes -- will be lower during their retirement 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	That's certainly the case for most people, but taxes may not  
drop as much as you might think, says a tax expert from the College 
for Financial Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	``First, retirees may lose some of the major deductions they had  
before retirement. Second, and perhaps more important, they are 
taxed on income they are not used to receiving,'' says Michael 
Cates, a professional tax preparer and an academic assistant at the 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some financial planners estimate that up to 85 percent of  
their retired clients remain in the same tax bracket they were in 
before they retired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As people approach and enter retirement, they often lose some of  
the tax deductions that helped reduce the amount of taxable income 
they generated, according to Cates. For example, your home mortgage 
is typically paid off by retirement, eliminating the deduction for 
home mortgage interest, though the deduction for property taxes may 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Cates says he's seen suggestions in print that retirees may want  
to continue the interest deduction on a paid-off home by taking out 
a home-equity loan, but he thinks that's generally not a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, you're putting your home at risk if you can't pay  
back the loan, and second, why spend a dollar in interest costs 
just to save 28 cents (or whatever your tax bracket) in taxes. The 
only rationale he can see for such borrowing is if you can make 
more money by investing the loan elsewhere -- but that entails risk. 
</P>
<P>
	A more likely scenario for helping to offset the loss of the  
mortgage interest for the primary residence is the purchase of a 
vacation home, a motor home or even a boat. Interest on these 
second homes (most anything that has sleeping, cooking and bathroom 
facilities is viewed as a residence) is usually deductible. 
</P>
<P>
	Another major deduction that disappears for most retirees is the  
personal exemption for dependents, who (except for those boomerang 
children) have left home. 
</P>
<P>
	Deductions for unreimbursed employee business expenses that  
exceed 2 percent of adjusted gross income (AGI) also disappear at 
retirement. On the other hand, deductions for medical expenses may 
rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical expenses, including insurance premiums, that exceed 7 1/2  
percent of your AGI are deductible. Cates notes that premiums for 
long-term care insurance policies are now deductible up to a 
certain limit, depending on your age (In 1999, $2,120 in premiums 
can be deducted, for example, for those ages 61-70). 
</P>
<P>
	However, the major tax deduction pre-retirees often forget that  
they will lose when they retire is their contributions to 
tax-deferred retirement plans, Cates says. 
</P>
<P>
	These contributions might amount to as much as 10 percent to 15  
percent of their employment income, especially as they approach 
retirement. Thus, ``although their retirement income might be lower 
than before retirement, a greater percentage of the income will be 
exposed to taxes,'' Cates notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the loss of income-tax deductions, retirees sometimes  
overlook the fact that distributions from their retirement plans, 
whether pensions paid for by employers or withdrawals from accounts 
the retirees funded, are taxable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of these accounts were tax-advantaged going in, so they  
are fully taxable coming out,'' Cates says. 
</P>
<P>
	The real shock can come when you turn 70 1/2, especially if you and  
your spouse hit that age about the same time. At that point, you 
must start making minimum withdrawals from your retirement accounts 
(unless you are still working) and individual retirement accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	If those accounts have grown in size over the years due to wise  
investing, and if you've been getting by since retirement without 
having to dip too heavily into those accounts, you may find 
yourself required to make minimum withdrawals that will trigger a 
bigger tax bite. 
</P>
<P>
	These required distributions also boost the chances of another  
tax bite retirees often overlook -- the taxation of Social Security 
benefits. Married couples filing jointly can have half their Social 
Security benefits subject to tax if their ``provisional income'' 
exceeds $32,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Provisional income includes 50 percent of Social Security  
benefits, tax-exempt income and regular income. If their 
provisional income exceeds $44,000, then up to 85 percent of their 
Social Security benefits are subject to tax. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are strategies that can mitigate the tax bite in  
retirement, such as carefully choosing beneficiaries for IRAs, 
selecting the best distribution options or using charitable giving 
strategies,'' Cates says. ``Taxpayers should discuss options with 
their financial planner, preferably before they retire.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
