<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:24:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Torre Managing Yankees Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Now this was a sight all of baseball enjoyed: Joe  
Torre back in uniform, back on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly two months after undergoing surgery for prostate cancer,  
Torre returned Tuesday as manager of the New York Yankees and was 
greeted by a two-minute standing ovation from the rival fans at 
Fenway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Red Sox were not quite so hospitable, winning 6-3 to  
move a half-game past the Yankees for the AL East lead. Still, 
Torre was happy he was healthy enough to be in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt very good, no fatigue,'' Torre said after the 3 1/2-hour  
game. ``I wish the result was better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees lost for the sixth time in seven games. Yet there  
was a sense Torre's presence would bring calm to the World Series 
champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the leader of our team and has been for a long time,''  
shortstop Derek Jeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Torre, who looked like he'd lost a little weight: ``With me  
being back, some of the players hinted, we won't be distracted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bench coach Don Zimmer, who managed the Yankees since Torre  
underwent surgery in St. Louis on March 18, returned to his more 
familiar role, sitting at his friend's side in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer talked about leaving baseball because of a bad knee once  
Torre returned. But Zimmer said he's looking to ``stick around for 
the rest of the season as long as the knee isn't bothering me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, 58, said he made his decision Monday night, then took a  
flight with Yankees owner George Steinbrenner to Boston on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's healthy and he's back and he's well,'' Steinbrenner said.  
``It's a special day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, who guided the Yankees to two World Series titles in  
three years, said he called Zimmer in the morning to tell him the 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just said, `Are you ready to do the job you were hired to  
do?' '' Torre said. ``He said, `You bet I am.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	``A great big hug and a tip of the hat from me,'' Torre said.  
``It was just more than he should have had heaped on him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours before the game, Yankees general manager Brian  
Cashman walked up to Zimmer, shook his hand and whispered, ``Thank 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been ready to do this about a week,'' Torre said before  
the game. ``I think I'm all the way back. I don't anticipate 
missing any time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Urged by Zimmer to take the lineup card to home plate, instead  
of batting coach Chris Chambliss, Torre got a warm reception from 
the sellout crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans began standing as soon as Torre stepped from the  
dugout, and continued clapping. The scoreboard flashed, ``Welcome 
Back, Joe Torre,'' and he tipped his cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off a 3-6 homestand, the Yankees fell to 21-16 as Pedro  
Martinez outpitched David Cone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been chomping a little bit lately,'' Torre said. ``It's  
tough when we struggled here. I was feeling a little helpless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least Torre did not make the one mistake he feared -- he was  
concerned he might accidentally move his hands and signal some 
unintended play. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre had been with the Yankees for some of their home and road  
games, though he had not felt ready to return on a full-time basis 
until now. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never a doubt. I had to come back here to see,''  
Torre said. ``I want to busy my mind with something other than when 
the next test is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre will continue to undergo tests and said he expects further  
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very fortunate,'' Torre said. ``Future? I'd like to  
keep doing this next year and the year after that. I'm going to 
take it a little bit at a time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0179 </DOCNO>
