<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Old Red Wings or Just Old? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	One moment they looked like the old Red Wings, but the moment  
after that, they just looked old. Another dynasty-in-the-making 
ends with a thud. 
</P>
<P>
	Hockey is played too fast to see a team crumble over the span of  
a single game. But go back and look at freeze frames from 
Colorado's 5-2 series-clinching win Tuesday night in Detroit and 
it's tough to see how Hockeytown's future can be nearly as bright 
as its immediate past. 
</P>
<P>
	The last two years running, the Red Wings ended the season by  
drinking from the Stanley Cup. The two seasons before that, they 
could take some comfort in knowing they were beaten by the eventual 
champions -- the Avalanche in the Western Conference finals in 1996, 
and the New Jersey Devils in the Stanley Cup finals in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Avalanche vs. Red Wings is widely considered the toughest  
rivalry in sports, so there is no shame in losing. On the other 
hand, Detroit raised expectations by adding four big names to the 
roster just ahead of the trading deadline, then sweeping Anaheim to 
open the playoffs. And that may have been why the crash-and-burn 
nature of the second-round loss -- the Red Wings dropped four 
straight after winning the first two -- left everybody in the locker 
room wondering what's next. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to see the Cup going someplace else this year,''  
Detroit's Brendan Shanahan said. ``That's going to be the hardest 
part.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Red Wings fans might have to get used to it.  
</P>
<P>
	Their last night in contention for a third straight Cup got off  
to a terrible start, then turned, in the span of just 29 seconds, 
into something promising. Late in the second period, Detroit scored 
two quick goals to turn a 4-0 lead into 4-2 and slow Colorado's 
momentum from an avalanche to a crawl. And then, with 6 1/2 minutes 
left in the game, the night turned sour for good. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's Peter Forsberg picked up the puck near center ice and  
broke toward Chris Osgood in the Detroit net. The only Red Wing 
with any chance of catching him was center Igor Larionov, who was 
already a teen-age prospect in the old Soviet hockey machine when 
Forsberg was born. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second, the age difference -- 13 years -- was apparent.  
Larionov clutched, grabbed and poked Forsberg, but lost contact 
with him soon enough. A second later, Forsberg deked Osgood on the 
backhand side, pulled the puck back to his forehand and deposited 
both the puck and himself into the net. It was Forsberg's second 
goal of the night and there was a certain symmetry to his being the 
hero, because he was the goat of the first two games. 
</P>
<P>
	The whole series, in fact, was punctuated by mood swings.  
Detroit won two on Colorado's ice. Forsberg got himself tossed from 
Game 1 for a vicious check on Shanahan from behind, leaving his 
shorthanded teammates to get beat in overtime. The Red Wings won 
Game 2 in regulation when Bill Ranford, their backup netminder, 
posted a shutout and played the way everybody expected Colorado's 
Patrick Roy would. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as if on cue, the two switched roles. Roy began playing  
like the best playoff goalie ever. Ranford answered questions about 
why he was filling in for the injured Osgood by playing like a 
backup. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado won two in Detroit and a third at home. In the deciding  
game Tuesday night, Roy was unyielding early and then, after the 
two Detroit scores got the crowd at Joe Louis back to its throaty 
best, solid enough to quiet the joint down. In a nice touch, the 
crowd got back on its feet for the final minute to pay tribute to 
the team and the coach, Scotty Bowman, for a great run before 
heading for the exits. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether they'll return next fall to find a team nearly this  
competitive is anyone's guess. General manager Ken Holland made 
some bold moves to get the Red Wings back into a tough race at the 
end of March by trading for Ranford, Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson 
and Wendel Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	The team responded by winning nine of the final 12 and crushing  
Anaheim in Round 1, but the years caught up with them all of a 
sudden. Chelios and Clark had one goal between them, Ranford went 
2-2 in the net and Samuelsson ended the playoffs in civilian 
clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, who's won a record-tying eight Stanley Cups as a coach,  
is talking retirement. Nick Lidstrom, Detroit's best defenseman, is 
talking about returning to Sweden to raise his family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody learns from a champion,'' Colorado  
defenseman Aaron Miller said. ``I think these guys definitely give 
you a blueprint on how to win. They did it two years in a row. They 
can only beat you so many times before you look up and say, `What's 
going on here?' That's what we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cleopatra Goes to the Small Screen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Leonor Varela, the screen's newest Cleopatra, has  
a cold, but that's little surprise given the schedule she's been 
keeping on the set of television's latest blockbuster miniseries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave birth on Saturday. I was swimming in a pool on Friday.  
I had an affair in a boat with Caesar going across the Nile on 
Thursday,'' says Varela, star of the four-hour, $28 million 
``Cleopatra'' airing Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. EDT on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Now 24 (``I'm telling you my age only because I'm polite''), the  
Chilean-born Varela is stepping into some fairly iconic sandals to 
play the exiled Egyptian queen. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleopatra's life has inspired plays by Shakespeare and Shaw, as  
well as a famous -- some would say infamous -- Elizabeth 
Taylor-Richard Burton movie, a 1963 Academy Award nominee for best 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Varela's co-stars in this latest offering include Billy Zane,  
Timothy Dalton and Rupert Graves as the various emperors and 
warriors in her midst. There also are 1,000 extras, 600 horses and 
the one ton of copper used to make the jewelry and costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	If this ``Cleopatra'' were a feature film, it might cost as much  
as $150 million, says its British director, Franc Roddam 
(``Quadrophenia''), who filmed interior scenes at London's 
Shepperton Studios after six weeks on location in Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Roddam directed TV's top-rated ``Moby Dick'' for the  
producer of ``Cleopatra,'' Robert Halmi Sr. By comparison, Roddam 
says, the current project is ``like doing two feature films 
back-to-back. It's a great workout for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day, something big and magnificent happens,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are battles, assassinations, murders, strangulations,''  
he adds. ``There's no downtime on this picture, so what that does 
is add an incredibly rich texture to the piece.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of that texture falls to Varela and Zane, the latter  
playing Marc Antony, the military hero who succumbs to Cleopatra's 
charms. Together, they must establish the chemistry to be 
convincing as two of the classical world's most heroic lovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Varela appeared opposite Leonardo DiCaprio in ``The Man in the  
Iron Mask,'' a part that took her only a week to film compared with 
12 weeks on ``Cleopatra.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleopatra, she says, is ``one of the greatest parts any woman  
could be given,'' and she isn't daunted) by her celluloid 
antecedent, Elizabeth Taylor, or the 1963 movie that was said to 
have cost more than $40 million, making it the most expensive of 
its time. 
</P>
<P>
	For this version, the square-cut look of Taylor's hair is  
replaced by Varela's own thick natural locks, topped more often 
than not by a regal headdress. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have this image of Liz Taylor getting out of bed and being  
so overly made up,'' says Varela. By contrast, ``this is just so 
real. I have the sensation of a real human being that has her 
facets, her beliefs, her faith, her wounds, her difficulties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zane, in turn, talks of ``stepping out of holiday mode'' as he  
returns to the set for his first day's filming since Christmas 
break. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sorry, too much time off,'' he says, smiling to the crew  
following a bungled take. ``What movie are we making here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, still clad in flowing period garb, the 33-year-old  
Chicagoan best-known as the baddie from ``Titanic'' gives his own 
take on an affair of, well, titanic dimensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here is this woman, this last bastion,'' Zane says, ``this  
great, very wise, very strong female energy, keeping the candle lit 
in this windstorm of machismo and gangster tactics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	BIGGEST SMILE: ``Candid Camera'' has inaugurated an annual award  
for five people whose brilliant smiles most delighted the program's 
producers and viewers. Winners of the 1999 Smile Awards include 
James Scruggs of Seaside, Calif., whose infectious grin charmed 
viewers throughout a segment in which host Peter Funt insisted upon 
returning to him ``spare parts'' left over from work done on 
Scruggs' just-repaired vehicle. And 3-year-old Malcolm Jack of 
Phoenix, who delighted viewers by dancing in a supermarket aisle in 
time to music playing over the store's public address system. 
``Candid Camera'' airs Friday at 8:30 p.m. EDT on CBS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
