<HEADLINE> Former Blue Jays Manager Gets Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Tim Johnson, fired in spring training by the  
Toronto Blue Jays, was hired to manage in the Mexican league. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, fired in part for telling lies about serving in the  
Marines in Vietnam, took over the Mexico City Red Devils in the 
Triple-A-rated Mexican Baseball League before Wednesday's game 
against the Aguascalientes Railmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love baseball and as soon as they invited me to come to the  
Red Devils, I didn't hesitate to accept,'' Johnson told the 
newspaper Reforma. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Devils, with a 31-23 record, are in second place in the  
league's central zone, eight games behind the Mexico City Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	He arrived in Mexico City on Tuesday and was in the stands as  
the Red Devils beat Aguascalientes 14-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 49, led Toronto to an 88-74 record last year, but  
admitted in November that he had told people he served in Vietnam 
while he actually had been in the Marine reserves in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to conflicts with some players and coaches and the team  
fired him on March 17, during spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson had coached the Hermosillo team in the Mexican winter  
baseball league for six years, winning the championship in 1990 and 
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
