<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Luyendyk Waits To Qualify for 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indianapolis 500 qualifications can't come  
soon enough for the Treadway Racing team of Arie Luyendyk and Sam 
Schmidt. 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, a two-time Indy winner who is retiring after the May  
30 race, and Schmidt, his heir as lead driver with one of the top 
teams in the Indy Racing League, have their cars just where they 
want them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're there, we know what the car is capable of and I think we  
have a pretty good idea of what we need to do to get the car ready 
to qualify,'' Schmidt said. ``Now we're running with a full load, 
trying different fuel settings, stuff that most teams don't have 
time to get to, and I never had time to get to in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Stewart and Greg Ray also appear plenty ready. After  
posting two of the best speeds in his primary and backup cars 
earlier in the week, Ray took a third Team Menard car out on 
Wednesday and turned an even faster lap at 226.085 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart went even quicker later in the day with a 226.683. Other  
fast laps were by Luyendyk at 225.096, Kenny Brack at 224.411, 
Stephan Gregoire at 224.193, Robby Unser at 224.042 and rookie 
Robby McGehee at 224.025. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt took it easy, with a top lap at 223.120.  
</P>
<P>
	Qualifications begin on Saturday. While Luyendyk and Schmidt  
have been among the most consistent and fastest drivers since 
practice began last weekend, the remaining track time is helping 
other teams who didn't have the early speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the short amount of time we had, it was very  
productive,'' said Stewart, who missed the opening day because of a 
NASCAR race and will have to leave early Saturday to race in The 
Winston at Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just trying to get my confidence back and see how the car  
is,'' said rookie Mike Borkowski, who crashed Monday and was back 
on the track in a rebuilt car that still had some problems. ``They 
put me out there with a huge understeer. ... We only have one car, 
so we can't afford to take chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His top lap Wednesday was under 216.  
</P>
<P>
	Gregoire, meanwhile, improved his best speed in practice on  
Tuesday to more than 223 mph, a leap of more than 4 mph, and went 
even faster on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good for our guys. They've been working hard changing  
parts every day,'' Gregoire said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few others didn't have as good fortune.  
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Dave Steele crashed in the first turn and was treated at  
Methodist Hospital for a mild concussion and back strain and then 
released. Tyce Carlson and Mark Dismore also hit the wall in 
separate crashes but were not hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifications to determine the 33-car lineup are set for  
Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nice to qualify tomorrow, actually,'' Luyendyk  
said. ``Sam has been running really strong. ... At this moment, 
we're looking pretty good with time. If we don't have any 
mechanical problems, we're really OK on schedule. The team is well 
prepared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, the only driver to win at least one race in each of  
the first three seasons the Indy Racing League has been in 
operation, is preparing for his 15th start at Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	He already holds track records for speed in practice,  
qualifications and the race -- all set before the IRL adopted a new 
engine-chassis package that produced slower speeds -- and he's 
Indy's career money leader with more than $5.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt was the third-fastest rookie qualifier at Indianapolis  
with Blueprint Racing in 1997. He finished 34th in an expanded 
field of 35 starters after an engine problem on the pace lap. Last 
year, he started sixth, but wound up 26th after a multicar crash on 
the 48th lap. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even before this year, Arie was one of the guys that was  
approachable. Arie was very helpful,'' Schmidt said. ``You ask him 
a question, you get a straight answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in a lot of team situations, and this one is as good  
or better than any other one because it's like an open book. There 
are no secrets,'' he said. ``All the information we have is totally 
accessible (to Luyendyk's crew), as what they're doing with their 
car is open to us. So that really helps. You can accomplish a lot 
of things every day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
