<DOCNO> APW19990519.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Parliament OKs New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Sergei Stepashin was easily approved as Russia's  
new prime minister today after he warned lawmakers that Russia 
needed immediate and courageous policies to rescue its battered 
economy and avoid social unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Duma, the lower chamber of parliament, voted 297-55 to  
confirm Stepashin following the dismissal last week of his popular 
predecessor, Yevgeny Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	It took the usually hostile Duma just three hours to debate and  
approve the confirmation of a man who is a top loyalist of 
President Boris Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin, who headed the nation's police and internal security  
forces as interior minister, appeared relieved when the result 
flashed up on a big electronic screen in the Duma. He thanked 
legislators and said he hoped that months of bruising political 
confrontation were over. 
</P>
<P>
	``This probably means one thing: We're all united by pain for  
our motherland and our people and the wish to see our country 
finally become normal, civilized, rich, prosperous and decent,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The approval came after the Communist-dominated Duma failed last  
week to launch impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin. Lawmakers 
clearly did not want another confrontation with the president. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the major factions voiced objections to Stepashin's  
confirmation during brief hearings before the vote. Even some of 
the Communists said they would support the new prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expected a lot of difficult and angry questions today, but  
there were none,'' Stepashin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duma Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said after the vote that  
Stepashin would be under Yeltsin's thumb. ``If Stepashin disobeys, 
he and his team will be immediately dismissed,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin congratulated Stepashin on his confirmation and said he  
was pleased with the Duma vote, according to a presidential 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition lawmakers said they backed Stepashin because they  
feared Yeltsin would turn to a more radical candidate if his first 
choice were rejected. Many lawmakers, tired of months of political 
confrontation, said they hoped Stepashin would be in office for at 
least the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin's immediate task is to name a Cabinet, which will have  
to be approved by Yeltsin. The Communists warned they would oppose 
the naming of liberal reformers to the Cabinet, but the Duma cannot 
block any ministerial appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	In his address to lawmakers before the vote, Stepashin promised  
to tackle Russia's huge economic and social problems. He said 
Russia needs bold and effective policies to reverse years of 
economic decline, but he spelled out few details. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no room for half-measures and compromises any  
longer,'' he told the Duma. ``Time demands courageous and 
thoroughly verified steps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin, who has no experience in economic administration,  
said his predecessor had stabilized the economy, but policies that 
could solve Russia's problems had not been adopted. He also pledged 
his strong loyalty to Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	``The previous government of Primakov did not allow the country  
to plunge into the abyss, yet we have failed so far to drastically 
change the situation either in economics or in the social sphere,'' 
Stepashin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, already struggling with years of economic collapse, is  
still reeling after it was hit in August by the global crisis in 
developing markets. The Russian government was forced to devalue 
the ruble and defaulted on some loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin told lawmakers that he had no intention of resorting  
to unconstitutional policies or means. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not General Pinochet, my name is Stepashin,'' he said in  
a reference to the former Chilean ruler whose policies were 
attacked by human rights activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Yeltsin's health was again thrown into question  
Tuesday when diplomats said he was sick with bronchitis. The 
Kremlin denied it. Yeltsin was at work at the Kremlin today, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin has a history of health problems, including several  
heart attacks, that have prompted sustained worries about his 
fitness to govern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
