<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres, Leafs Brewing Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite being separated by just 107 miles,  
Buffalo and Toronto have little hockey history between them. That 
figures to change in the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres and Maple Leafs played five games this season after  
realignment sent the Leafs to the Eastern Conference. The Sabres 
won three times. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams could play as many as seven more games as they chase a  
berth in the Stanley Cup finals. That's a lot of traffic on the 
Peace Bridge, the span that links the two regions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eastern Conference best-of-7 final starts in Toronto on  
Sunday. The media already have named it the ``QEW Series'' after 
Queen Elizabeth Way, the highway between Toronto and the 
Buffalo-Niagara Falls area. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be pretty intense,'' Leafs president Ken Dryden said.  
``We want rivalries, and rivalries get spawned in playoff series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo and Toronto have enough in common to nurture a rivalry.  
Both have plenty of ice and snow. Both are stocked with hockey 
fans. And the two cities are only a 90-minute drive apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great for everybody outside the dressing room, for the  
fans, for Buffalo, for Toronto,'' said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff, 
whose playoff record is 18-7, including last year's trip to the 
conference final. ``You talk about building rivalries, all of a 
sudden we've got one that's an hour and a half away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blue-clad Leafs fans made their way to Buffalo's Marine Midland  
Arena in such large numbers that the Sabres sometimes wondered 
which city they were playing in. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had as many fans in our building as we had,'' said  
Buffalo center Brian Holzinger. ``And we had a lot of fans up 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leafs fans have wormed their way onto the Buffalo roster. Sabres  
captain Michael Peca and defenseman Jason Woolley grew up rooting 
for Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	After Buffalo disposed of Boston in the sixth game of the  
conference semifinal Tuesday night, Woolley, a Toronto native, said 
his biggest worry going into the Toronto series was how to handle 
all the ticket requests. 
</P>
<P>
	Peca, who grew up in a Toronto suburb, said he and Woolley joked  
about the Leafs fans pouring out of bars and honking their horns on 
Yonge Street after Toronto eliminated Pittsburgh on Monday night. 
``That used to be us,'' Peca said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams are fast and have solid goaltenders. Buffalo's  
Dominik Hasek ranks third in the playoffs with a 1.77 goals-against 
average and leads with a save percentage of .942. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto's Curtis Joseph sits one place behind Hasek in the  
rankings with equally impressive numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the two best goaltenders in the conference going at  
it right now,'' said Ruff, whose Sabres had a tough enough time 
with Boston's Byron Dafoe. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams have one more thing in common -- frustration. The  
Sabres haven't advanced to the Stanley Cup finals since 1975. The 
Flyers won the Cup that year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Leafs haven't made it to the championship round since they  
won the Cup in a series with Montreal in 1967. Toronto lost to 
Vancouver in the 1994 Western Conference final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
