<HEADLINE> Forbes' NH Campaign Manager Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Conservative activist Peter Robbio resigned  
as New Hampshire campaign manager for Steve Forbes after being 
arrested for pulling a gun on three men in Manchester. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbio was arrested April 16 at a Manchester bar, Manchester  
Police Lt. Mark Putney said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He resigned from Forbes' campaign staff the next day, saying he  
didn't have time to run another campaign, said Bill Dal Col, 
Forbes' national campaign manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running the New Hampshire presidential primary is more than a  
full-time job,'' Robbio said. ``For personal reasons, I just don't 
have that time. ... I told them it would be best for the campaign 
if I stepped down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Putney said Robbio bumped into another patron without  
apologizing; the two then got into an argument, and Robbio 
brandished a pistol. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached at home Wednesday night, Robbio said he would not  
comment on his personal life. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has asked Graham Shafer, former political director of the  
Tennessee Republican Party, to take Robbio's place. Schafer spends 
summers in New Hampshire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
