<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trie's Manager Testifies at Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The manager of Yah Lin ``Charlie''  
Trie's local office told investigators that the Democratic 
fund-raiser reimbursed six Arkansas residents for making 
contributions to President Clinton's legal defense fund, an FBI 
agent testified today. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys accused prosecutors of trying to ``infect this  
jury'' with testimony regarding separate charges against Trie made 
in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. instructed the jury to  
disregard FBI agent Roberta Parker's testimony that she had been 
told Trie funneled money to the defense fund and the Democratic 
National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie is on trial for obstruction of justice.  
</P>
<P>
	Parker investigated Trie for a Washington grand jury that later  
charged him with making and arranging illegal political 
contributions to Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker also testified that Maria ``Dia'' Mapili told authorities  
she spoke with Trie on numerous occasions regarding publicity about 
his fund-raising activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Mapili testified Tuesday that Trie told her as early as  
January 1997 to destroy related documents stored at his Little Rock 
home. She said the documents related to past business deals as well 
as invitations to the White House and to political events and 
contributions to the DNC. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Mapili, the prosecution's chief witness, appeared to  
bolster the defense with her testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	As prosecutors said she would, Mrs. Mapili testified that Trie  
ordered her get rid of documents sought in a Senate investigation 
into political fund-raising in the 1996 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``I read part of the subpoena to him. He told me to get rid of  
the documents,'' she testified. ``I throw out some documents. At 
some point I stopped. I was nervous and scared. I hid some 
documents in a credenza and under his bed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, under defense questioning, Mrs. Mapili said the  
conversation may have occurred months before or after she received 
a subpoena to provide documents to the Senate Governmental Affairs 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie, a central figure in the controversy over foreign-linked  
campaign donations to Democrats, could face up to five years in 
prison and a $250,000 fine if convicted of impeding the Senate 
probe. 
</P>
<P>
	He would face even stiffer penalties if convicted in Washington  
of charges that he made and arranged illegal contributions from 
foreigners to the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie is accused of making illegal contributions to buy access to  
Clinton and other top officials for himself and the likes of 
Chinese arms dealer Wang Jun. Wang is an adviser to the Chinese 
government whose company, Poly Technologies, has been implicated in 
the smuggling of arms into the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC has returned $640,000 that Trie raised. Clinton's legal  
defense fund has returned another $460,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
