<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Criticizes American Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dan Quayle, who cited a TV sitcom character in  
his 1992 critique of the American culture, has created himself a 
new family-values villain for his 2000 presidential campaign: ``the 
legal aristocracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former vice president coined that phrase to describe liberal  
lawyers, legal advocacy groups and federal judges in an address 
today to mark the seventh anniversary of his Murphy Brown speech. 
Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, are lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take courage to challenge this self-anointed group,''  
Quayle said in a speech prepared for delivery today to the 
Commonwealth Club of California. 
</P>
<P>
	In an address to the same group during the 1992 campaign, Quayle  
discussed the importance of family values in a culture of violence, 
drugs and sex. He used as an example TV sitcom character Murphy 
Brown, an unwed mother, and was ridiculed for attacking a fictional 
figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years later, Quayle picks up where he left off.  
</P>
<P>
	``Which is the greatest challenge facing America today? Jobs or  
values?'' Quayle asked. ``Values matter most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He ventured into the prickly debate over gun control, saying,  
``Quick-fix artists are now in a frenzy over guns'' after the 
Colorado school shootings. Quayle supports instant background 
checks for the purchase of guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``But let's be honest and recognize that the overriding issue  
isn't really gun control, it's self-control. A child who loves God, 
honors his parents, and respects his neighbors will not kill 
anyone,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The way to stop school shootings, Quayle said, is to change the  
culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today I want to focus on a sector of our society that has been  
largely exempt from the discussion and must be part of our effort 
to reverse the cultural decline: the legal system, and, 
specifically, the legal aristocracy,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The authority of parents is undermined by an international  
treaty on children's rights, policies of the American Bar 
Association and an administration that led children to believe they 
can sue their parents, Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based ABA declined to comment before reviewing the  
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The authority of school officials to keep classrooms safer is  
undermined by lawsuits that challenge their efforts at every step, 
Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally, let's remind ourselves that all students need a moral  
education, but the legal aristocracy has obstructed their ability 
to receive it,'' Quayle said, referring to restrictions on school 
prayer. ``The separation of church and state has come to mean all 
state, no church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He promised, if elected, to nominate federal judges who  
``appreciate the indispensable role of religion and morality in our 
society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, GOP rival Gary Bauer says the Bush-Quayle  
administration nominated some of the judges who are now part of 
what he calls the ``judicial elites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The next president of the United States must change this  
course,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the aftermath of the Columbine High School shootings,  
presidential candidates in both parties are talking about the 
decline of American values. Quayle believes the abuse he took in 
1992 gives him an upper hand on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In laying out his case against the legal system, he cited cases  
and the courts that acted on them, and singled out the Legal 
Services Corporation and the American Civil Liberties Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said he would appoint a watchdog at the Justice  
Department to find legal test cases ``to win back authority for 
parents and schools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In fulfilling its cultural agenda, the legal aristocracy has  
not worked alone. It was aided by a willing and compliant news 
media and an entertainment community that transmits counterculture 
values,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They live in gated communities and send their children to  
expensive private schools,'' he said. ``This is their world. But 
it's not the real world.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
