<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Down on Good Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures retreated Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade on favorable harvesting and planting 
weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures were pressured by mild, dry weather in  
Midwest growing regions, which should speed farmer fieldwork for 
what is expected to be bumper acreage. With the world still reeling 
from the effects of a global economic crisis, the prospect for 
another large harvest has sent prices reeling. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also fell after China purchased 40,000 metric tons of  
soybeans from South American competitors 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by reports farmers were seeing  
above-average yields during harvesting of the winter wheat crop, 
which accounts for much of total wheat production. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $2.59 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.19 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1/4 cent to 
$1.21 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 4 cents to $4.71 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .48 cent to 62.67 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .55 cent to 73.92 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 1.83 cents to 56.07 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .40 
cent to 54.45 cents a pound. 
</P>
