<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises to 7-Mo. High Vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose Wednesday to a seven-month high  
against the Japanese yen as the Federal Reserve's new bias toward 
raising interest rates made U.S. investments more appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also gained versus the euro in the aftermath of  
Tuesday's meeting by Fed officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bankers didn't raise the Fed's key lending rates,  
but revealed a heightened concern they may need to slow the economy 
to prevent an inflationary spurt. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro drew some support Wednesday from news of various  
diplomatic efforts to halt the fighting in Yugoslavia. U.S., 
Finnish and Russian negotiators flew in and out of several European 
capitals and G-8, the group representing the world's seven largest 
industrialized nations and Russia, was meeting in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 124.21 yen in late New York trading, up from  
Tuesday's late quote of 123.20 yen and the highest level since the 
exchange rate plunged below 130 yen in early October. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0657, falling from $1.0680 in  
Tuesday's late trading in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.5040  
Swiss Francs, up from 1.4989; and 1.4673 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4654. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound fell to $1.6173 from late Tuesday's $1.6207.  
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8352 German marks, up from 1.8312; 6.1538 French francs, up from 
6.1425; and 1,818.18 Italian lire, up from 1,811.59. 
</P>
</TEXT>
