<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:41:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bancorp To Buy Western Bancorp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- U.S. Bancorp plans to acquire Western  
Bancorp, which has 31 branches in southern California, for slightly 
less than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Western, based in Newport Beach, Calif., has branches in Los  
Angeles, Orange and San Diego counties, owns Santa Monica Bank and 
Southern California Bank, and has $2.5 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, Western Bancorp shareholders will  
receive in a tax-free exchange 1.2915 shares of U.S. Bancorp common 
stock for each share of Western Bancorp common stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition, which must be approved by regulators and  
Western Bancorp shareholders, is expected to close in the fourth 
quarter of 1999, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	David I. Rainer, who currently serves as president and chief  
executive officer of Santa Monica Bank, will serve as president of 
the southern California market for U.S. Bancorp. 
</P>
<P>
	Minneapolis-based U.S. Bancorp, with $76 billion in assets, is  
the 13th largest bank holding company in the nation and operates 
about 1,000 banking offices in 17 Midwestern and Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bancorp currently operates 88 branches in northern  
California as well as corporate trust and leasing offices in Los 
Angeles and San Francisco. The company's California presence also 
includes six offices of its U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray brokerage 
subsidiary and U.S. Bancorp Libra, an investment bank headquartered 
in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bancorp's previously announced acquisition of Bank of  
Commerce, with 10 branches in San Diego and Orange counties and 
$638 million in assets, is currently pending regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of U.S. Bancorp fell $1.81 1/4 to $32.56 1/4 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange, while shares of Western rose $1.31 1/4 to 
$40.31 1/4 in trading on the Nasdaq stock market. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
