<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Denies Cops Cheered Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- White police officers made no racial epithets  
and did not celebrate with ``high fives'' after fatally shooting a 
black woman, a lawyer for the men said Wednesday in response to a 
civil rights lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Riverside officers were ``hugging each other and  
commiserating with each other because they hadn't been killed,'' 
attorney Bill Hadden said. ``To say they high-fived is absolutely 
false.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Claims of racism made in the lawsuit are false and designed to  
win a damage award for the family of the slain woman, Tyisha 
Miller, Hadden said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil rights suit filed in federal court on Tuesday by a  
legal team headed by lawyer Johnnie Cochran named five officers and 
the city of Riverside -- 60 mile east of Los Angeles -- as defendants 
and alleged race was the motive for killing Ms. Miller, 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Miller was shot 12 times on Dec. 28 after she was found  
lying in a semiconscious state in her locked car with a gun on her 
lap. Police, who responded to a 911 call, say she suddenly reached 
for the weapon when an officer smashed the car's window. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of citizens have joined protest marches led by the  
Revs. Jesse Jackson and Al Sharpton. Jackson has called Ms. 
Miller's shooting the act of ``a firing squad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riverside County District Attorney Grover Trask announced this  
month that he will not prosecute the officers, although he 
criticized their handling of the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
