<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starved Baby's Mom Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A young mother who blamed breast-feeding  
problems for the death of her emaciated baby son was convicted 
Wednesday of criminally negligent homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabitha Walrond, 21, faces up to four years in prison at  
sentencing. She was acquitted of the more serious charge of 
manslaughter, which could have brought her a 15-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	She dabbed away tears as the verdicts were read.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ms. Walrond starved 2-month-old Tyler in 1997  
to spite his father, who left her shortly after she got pregnant -- 
or, at the very least, ignored signs that the baby was starving. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense said she was a doting mother who didn't realize that  
her surgically reduced breasts were failing to nourish her child. 
Defense attorney Susan V. Tipograph said Tyler may have suffered 
from an adrenal gland disorder -- not malnutrition. 
</P>
<P>
	But autopsy photographs showed her son was emaciated, having  
dropped from his birth weight of nearly 8 pounds to about 5 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond testified on Tuesday that she never noticed Tyler's  
drastic weight loss. She said she took natural-childbirth classes, 
went to night school to finish high school before Tyler was born 
and chose to breast-feed because doctors and family told her 
``breast is best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All those actions, Ms. Tipograph said, demonstrated motherly  
love. She said Ms. Walrond brought Tyler to a clinic for a checkup 
but was turned away because she did not have a Medicaid card for 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond sobbed on the witness stand as she described how she  
found Tyler looking lifeless and foaming at the mouth and rushed 
him to the hospital in a taxi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said `Faster, faster! ... Something's wrong with my baby!'''  
she testified. ``He left me, he died in the cab. I felt him 
leave.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
