<HEADLINE> Reporter's AIDS Test Is Negative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) -- A blood test has found that a former  
reporter who was fired for writing fictitious columns about her 
health does not have AIDS as she once claimed, the 
Messenger-Inquirer reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Stacy was fired by the Owensboro newspaper May 10 after she  
admitted that five columns she wrote detailing her battle against 
terminal brain cancer were fabrications. At the time of her 
dismissal, she said she lied in the columns to avoid revealing she 
had AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the columns was distributed in Kentucky by The Associated  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	But three days after losing her job and becoming the subject of  
an apology to readers by Messenger-Inquirer Publisher Ed Riney, 
Stacy said the story of her having AIDS was also a lie. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of the test were made available to the  
Messenger-Inquirer with Stacy's permission. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will bring closure to a lot of this,'' Stacy said  
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
