<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:31:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan Counting on New Xterra SUV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The stylish new Xterra economy sport utility  
vehicle that goes on sale Tuesday will fill a niche as the most 
affordable of the ``true'' SUVs built on a truck frame, company 
officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co. said the Xterra will be the driving force  
behind a projected 15 percent increase in its North American sales, 
as well as a jump in profits from the continent. The SUV starts at 
$17,349. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it will bring some fresh people into the Nissan  
showroom,'' said Jed Connelly, vice president of Nissan North 
America and general manager of its Nissan brand said in an 
interview Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The name Xterra (pronounced ehks-TEH'-ruh) is intended to link  
images of Generation X and rugged terrain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very stylish,'' said Nissan North America marketing  
manager Jack D. Wilkerson. ``We are able to get a hip or a cool 
factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cost, as well as design, is a big a part of its coolness, Nissan  
execs say. The base sticker price announced Wednesday places the 
2000-model Xterra well below the $25,000 or so of other truck-based 
SUVs. 
</P>
<P>
	The price should help lure buyers who otherwise would have  
bought cars or used SUVs, said Mark Perry, another marketing 
executive with Nissan North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Some compact SUVs do sell for less. But they use cars' unibody  
design, rather than the sturdier body-on-frame design used for 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Wesley Brown said the Xterra's ``rugged, muscular'' look  
and moderate price should make it a hot seller for Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like they're getting on track,'' said Brown, of  
Nextrend in Thousand Oaks, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealer and public interest has led Nissan to raise its  
first-year U.S. sales estimate from 48,000 to the 60,000 to 65,000 
range. Production at its Smyrna, Tenn. assembly plant is expected 
to reach a full-capacity 70,000 to 75,000. Canadian sales account 
for the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan has a large inventory of Xterras in stock already,  
Connelly said. He said the company moved up the introduction date 
from early June to catch Memorial Day weekend traffic and avoid 
possible disruption from a threatened Teamsters union strike 
against car haulers. 
</P>
<P>
	Value also marked the prices for the other 2000-model prices  
Nissan announced Wednesday. The Japan-built Maxima car will start 
at $21,049, $450 less than the 1999 model. Antilock brakes and 
other now-standard features make comparably equipped 2000 Maximas 
$2,000 less than '99s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Frontier Crew Cab four-door compact pickup will list for  
$17,290, and the two-door Frontier Desert Runner will start at 
$15,740. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide, Nissan is trying to fight its way out of deep  
financial problems made worse by Japan's continuing recession and 
North American sales that until recently lagged other Japanese 
automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan got a big boost in March when French automaker Renault SA  
agreed to invest $5.4 billion in exchange for a 36.8 percent 
controlling stake in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	In North America, sales and earnings both are moving up, chief  
spokeswoman Debra Sanchez Fair said. On Friday, she said it will 
report a ``small profit'' of about $40 million for the 12 months 
that ended March 31. Nissan North America lost $500 million a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. sales of Nissan-brand vehicles rose 23.4 percent in April  
and are up 5.6 percent since the start of 1999. The division 
expects to sell 630,000 in North America in its 1999 fiscal year, 
15 percent more than in 1998, Connelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	When sales of Nissan's Infiniti's luxury division are added in,  
Nissan sales should reach 700,000 vehicles, he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
