<HEADLINE> Xerox, Microsoft To Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Xerox Corp. is forming an alliance with software giant Microsoft  
Corp. that will enable Xerox to better link its products with 
computer networks running Microsoft software. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance was announced on Tuesday by Xerox Chief Executive  
Officer G. Richard Thoman and Microsoft President Steve Ballmer at 
Xerox's Research Center in Palo Alto, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The terms of the deal were not disclosed. Xerox will adopt  
Microsoft's Windows NT Embedded operating systems on its Document 
Centre machines which lead the company's digital product line. 
</P>
<P>
	Document Centre products accounted for about 10 percent of  
Xerox's total sales last year, generating $1.8 billion in revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox officials said the agreement would allow the company to  
develop cheaper machines that can meet the increasing need to fax, 
copy, print and scan documents into a computer network. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Microsoft licenses Xerox's WebForager software.  
</P>
<P>
	The alliance isn't the first between the two companies.  
Microsoft and Xerox teamed up in 1993 to develop software for ``the 
paperless office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also announced on Tuesday was a deal with Compaq Computer Corp.  
to use Xerox scanning technology with its Work Expediter software, 
which manages work-flow. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers will start to see the new Windows NT features on  
Document Centre machines this fall and Compaq machines in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
