<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loehmann's Files for Chapter 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Discount clothing retailer Loehmann's Inc.  
announced Tuesday that it has filed a petition to reorganize under 
Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chapter 11, Loehmann's will continue to operate under  
court protection from creditors while seeking to work out a 
reorganization plan. The petition was filed in federal Bankruptcy 
Court in Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert N. Friedman, chairman and chief executive officer of  
Loehmann's, said the decision to file for Chapter 11, ``while 
difficult, represents the most viable option for restructuring our 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past 18 months, we have implemented several strategic  
initiatives including a more diversified merchandise mix, an 
aggressive marketing campaign and improved operating 
efficiencies,'' Friedman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we believe these strategies were the appropriate course  
of action, they have yet to mature and generate the expected 
financial returns. The Chapter 11 filing will provide additional 
time to build on these efforts and to take the steps necessary to 
ensure a strong future for Loehmann's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced that Eliot Green has been named  
interim chief financial officer. Green is a financial consultant 
who has extensive corporate restructuring experience. In addition, 
Norman S. Matthews and Richard E. Kroon have resigned from their 
positions on the company's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Loehmann's sells women's and men's designer and brand-name  
clothing, accessories and shoes at discounts of 30 to 65 percent. 
The Bronx, N.Y.-based company operates 69 stores in 22 states and 
had fiscal 1999 sales of $432 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
