<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Residents Brace for Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CENTRAL CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Homeowners and high school students  
filled thousands of sandbags and hauled furniture from 
flood-threatened homes as an eastern Iowa river rose to record 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	About 30 families were evacuated Tuesday night and Wednesday in  
this town of 1,069 people north of Cedar Rapids, while others 
maintained a nervous watch as the Wapsipinicon River lapped at 
their doorsteps. 
</P>
<P>
	``Depending on how high the river gets, my kitchen may be under  
water,'' said Lori Kuchera, who waited anxiously for the river to 
crest. ``You live by a river, it's inevitable. You just have to 
roll with the punches -- or ride with the tide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty counties reported flood damage from a storm that swept  
the state Sunday, swelling rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	The river in Central City was measured at 19.7 feet at 3 p.m.  
Wednesday, well above its record high of 19.3 feet, said Bill 
Nichols, meteorologist in the Davenport office of the National 
Weather Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Wednesday, the river breached a sandbag dike 5 feet high  
and a half-mile long, sloshing into the heart of tiny Troy Mills 
where it chased some 12 families from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The breach washed away the work of hundreds of volunteers from  
Cedar Rapids, Independence and other communities, as well as high 
school students from Coggon North Linn High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boy, I'll tell you, you talk about heartbreak, those people  
just worked their tails off all day long,'' said Harold Annis, who 
had 3 feet of water in his home. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20,000 sandbags had been filled as of noon Wednesday and  
the town of Marion sent in another 18,000 to keep the river at bay. 
All day, scores of pickup trucks roamed the town loaded with 
sandbags and teen-agers looking for homes and riverbanks that 
needed shoring up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to keep doing this until they tell me to stop,''  
said Chris Oldfather, a ninth-grader who had put in 12 hours of 
sandbagging and was back at it at 8 a.m. Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
