<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lehman Group Reportedly Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's financial watchdog agency has begun  
inspecting three Japanese units of the Lehman Brothers group of the 
United States, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lehman Brothers spokesman said that the inspection began  
Wednesday; he refused to elaborate. The Financial Supervisory 
Agency would neither confirm nor deny the inspection. 
</P>
<P>
	The probe was first reported Thursday by the Nihon Keizai,  
Japan's top financial newspaper. The paper said the action was 
focused on derivatives transactions designed to defer client losses 
on securities holdings and loans. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lehman Brothers spokesman, who spoke on condition of  
anonymity, said that the company believed the agency action is part 
of a routine audit and that it is fully cooperating with 
inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's latest inspection involved the Tokyo branches of  
Lehman Brothers Japan Inc., Lehman Brothers Global Asset Management 
KK and Lehman Brothers Bankhaus AG, the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The inspection is only the second the agency has carried out of  
foreign financial institutions operating in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the watchdog agency began investigating the Japanese  
operations of the Credit Suisse First Boston group for alleged 
improprieties in derivatives dealings. The agency is in the final 
stages of that investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	If any illegalities are found, possible penalties include  
suspension of operations, the Nihon Keizai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
