<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royals Coach Hurt Ridding Bicycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Tom Burgmeier, bullpen coach for the  
Kansas City Royals, fractured his wrist and knee Wednesday when he 
was struck by a car while riding his bicycle to Kauffman Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Royals said Burgmeier, 55, was struck when a car made a  
right turn in front of him. Both he and the bike became airborne 
over the top of the vehicle. He was treated for a laceration to the 
right knee and he will undergo surgery Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The club said he was in stable condition with two fractures of  
the right wrist and a fracture of the left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	A 17-year major league veteran with five clubs, Burgmeier was  
79-55 with 102 saves and a 3.23 career ERA. He was a member of the 
1980 American League All-Star team. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Jirschele, the Royals minor league coordinator of  
instruction and infield, took Burgmeier's place as bullpen coach 
for Wednesday night's game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
