<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Telecom Posts Higher Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Greater use of mobile phones and the Internet  
helped boost fourth-quarter pretax profits for British 
Telecommunications PLC by 33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's largest phone company earned 836 million pounds, or  
$1.35 billion, before taxes in the three months ended March 31 
versus 630 million pounds a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Its sales rose 19 percent to 4.90 billion pounds, or $7.90  
billion, from 4.11 billion pounds a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	BT shares were up 4.6 percent in midday trading Wednesday in  
London. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, British Telecom posted a pre-tax profit of 4.30  
billion pounds, or $6.94 billion, up 34 percent from 3.21 billion 
pounds the previous year. The annual profit included a gain of 1.11 
billion pounds from the sale of the company's stake in MCI 
Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Full-year sales rose 14 percent to 18.22 billion pounds, or  
$29.39 billion, from 16.04 billion pounds a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	New ventures in Europe and Asia accounted for more than a third  
of the sales increase, while mobile and fixed-network calls in 
Britain made a strong contribution, BT said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rapidly expanding use of the Internet and a rise in the  
number of calls to mobile phones were the main factors in a sharp 
increase in domestic traffic in the second half of the fiscal year, 
Chairman Iain Vallance said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, losses mounted at BT's start-up operations in Europe.  
The loss at German joint-venture Viag Interkom swelled to 429 
million pounds from 336 million pounds, while BT's Dutch unit 
Telfort sank deeper into the red, to 130 million pounds from 46 
million pounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
