<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:31:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Faces Coalition Choices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Heading into coalition talks, Israel's next  
prime minister must contemplate whether to exclude the 
ultra-Orthodox Shas party to slow its phenomenal ascent -- or 
include it to speed the peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	Secular Israelis who gave Ehud Barak his crushing victory in  
this week's election fear the theocracy that Shas advocates, and 
prefer an alliance with Likud, the hard-line party Barak unseated. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least with the Likud we have a normative partnership on  
what the state of Israel is and how it looks,'' Avraham Burg, who 
led Barak's hard-hitting campaign against Likud Prime Minister 
Benjamin Netanyahu. ``With Shas, we do not have a normative 
agreement like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, Shas leaders have been quick to reassure secular  
Israelis that their descriptions of a state run according to 
religious law is a utopian ideal to pray for, rather than 
legislate. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was before they leapt from 10 to 17 seats in  
parliament, making Shas the third-largest party. The Likud has 19 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Shas, which was part of Netanyahu's coalition, has yet to  
outline any new legislative tacks, but followers are already 
speaking of a new look for Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is natural,'' said Yehuda Sharabi, a kiosk owner in the  
coastal town of Ashdod, a Shas stronghold. ``The state of the Jews 
must function according to Jewish law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such talk instills fear among secular Israelis, who resented  
incursions into their daily lives legislated while Shas was in the 
coalition, such as shutting down businesses that operate on the 
Sabbath and having Interior Ministry officials pose intrusive 
questions about immigrants' Jewish background. 
</P>
<P>
	Shas was able to cultivate support among Israelis -- especially  
Sephardic Jews who are of Middle Eastern background -- by offering 
free kindergarten education, long school hours and other social 
services through its control of deep-pocketed ministries such as 
Interior and Labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeping Shas out of government would dry up such sources, some  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it continues to be plugged into the coffers, the result  
would be that the Barak government would foster Shas and its youth 
at the expense of the good of the state,'' columnist Amnon Dankner 
wrote in Maariv. 
</P>
<P>
	Others said the need to advance the peace process frozen by  
Netanyahu during his years in power was more important. The Likud, 
which touted its deep suspicion of the peace process and the Arabs 
as a campaign virtue, would slow the peace, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, Shas supports the process, saying it fulfills a  
religious commandment to prevent bloodshed. Its legislative votes 
were crucial to sustaining the late Yitzhak Rabin's peace 
initiatives after 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak could build a narrow coalition without Shas or the Likud,  
but he says he needs wide backing to make hard decisions, including 
withdrawing from territory, pulling troops out of Lebanon and 
dismantling settlements. 
</P>
<P>
	For the time being, Barak is counting out Shas as long as Arieh  
Deri -- convicted last month on bribe-taking charges -- remains party 
leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sportswear Maker To Sell Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Apparel maker Brazos Sportswear Inc., which  
entered bankruptcy reorganization in January, plans to sell its 
business units through auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati-based company, which sells clothing with logos  
and licensed characters printed or embroidered on it, announced the 
sale Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the company's Chapter 11 filing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court  
for protection from creditors, management and the board of 
directors had been trying to find the best solution for creditors 
and employees of the company, said Chief Financial Officer Clayton 
Chambers. 
</P>
<P>
	``After careful consideration, it was determined that a prompt  
sale of the company's business units, either individually or as a 
whole, is in the best interests of Brazos' creditors, employees, 
customers and suppliers,'' said Chambers. He has been appointed 
interim chief executive officer and interim chief operating officer 
through the sale process. 
</P>
<P>
	Chambers said management believes that new ownership will allow  
the company's business units to capitalize on their individual 
strengths, while having access to greater financial resources. 
</P>
<P>
	The auction is scheduled for June 10; bids to purchase some or  
all of the assets must be submitted by June 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazos operates manufacturing, distribution and sales facilities  
in 12 states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
