<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 11:51:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Shuffles Lineup; Pax Adds Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Top-rated CBS is betting on lawyers to carry  
half of its six new fall series and is shuffling its schedule to 
move favorites like ``Cosby'' and ``Chicago Hope'' to new nights. 
</P>
<P>
	The network is canceling ``Promised Land'' and ``L.A. Doctors.''  
Its long-running comedy, ``The Nanny,'' is retiring this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of CBS's three new dramas will be legal shows with women as  
central characters. ``Family Law'' stars Kathleen Quinlan in a show 
about lawyers who form a new firm after one woman's husband leaves 
her and takes their practice with him. Former ``NYPD Blue'' actress 
Amy Brenneman stars in ``Judging Amy,'' about a single mother who 
becomes a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	A new CBS comedy, ``Work With Me,'' is about a husband-and-wife  
team of lawyers who work from their home. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is keeping its strong weekend schedule intact but is making  
significant prime-time changes on weekdays. ``Cosby'' will be moved 
from Monday nights to Wednesdays, and ``60 Minutes II'' shifted 
from Wednesday to Tuesday. CBS will air a movie on Wednesday 
instead of Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-running hospital drama, ``Chicago Hope'' is being moved  
to Thursdays and kept on the schedule after creator David E. Kelley 
promised to take a more active role in steering the show. 
``Diagnosis Murder'' will air an hour earlier, on Thursdays at 8 
p.m. ET. 
</P>
<P>
	Like some of its rivals, CBS is sensing blood on Thursday  
nights, which NBC has dominated for more than a decade. ABC and the 
WB have promised to attack NBC with youth-oriented series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think NBC will still win Thursday nights, but I think  
everyone's going to chip away a little at them,'' said CBS 
President Leslie Moonves. ``There's no reason to believe that 
they're not going to decline even further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is poised to wrest this season's Nielsen Media Research's  
ratings crown from NBC, the network's first win since 1993-94. Its 
rivals minimize the accomplishment, saying that CBS ranks fourth 
among the 18-to-49-year-old demographic most coveted by 
advertisers. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has tried to bring in a younger audience through football  
and Howard Stern, but won't be doing much more to shock its core 
viewers. One of its new comedies even brings back ``Golden Girls'' 
star Betty White as a character. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to play the hand you're dealt,'' Moonves said.  
</P>
<P>
	In a sign of new business realities, CBS acknowledged that it  
owns a stake in each of its six new programs. Struggling with 
declining revenue, television networks have been trying to make 
money by owning their programs, instead of buying them from 
independent production houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are CBS's other new programs:  
</P>
<P>
	--''Now &AMP; Again,'' an action drama about a middle-aged insurance  
salesman who is hit by a subway train. In return for a promise that 
he'll be a government agent, his body is scientifically rebuilt. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Ladies Man'' is about a furniture maker trying to keep peace  
in an extended family of women, including his mother, played by 
White. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Love or Money,'' an ensemble comedy about a New York  
apartment house that stars Swoosie Kurtz, David Ogden Stiers, Paget 
Brewster and Brian Doyle Murray. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Pax TV unveiled a schedule for its second year as a  
broadcast network. It will continue to air reruns of ``Touched By 
an Angel'' and ``Diagnosis Murder'' five nights a week, but is 
adding four new series. 
</P>
<P>
	The new series are ``Hope Island,'' about a minister who  
rebuilds a church on an island off Washington state; ``Twice in a 
Lifetime,'' about a guardian angel who guides people into their 
past to revisit a pivotal life decision; ``Chicken Soup For the 
Soul,'' a televised version of the inspirational books; and ``The 
Star Machine,'' an amateur hour-type entertainment show. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
