<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery May Be Launched Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA completed repairs today to  
space shuttle Discovery's hail-damaged fuel tank and remained on 
track for a launch next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said Tuesday that Discovery probably would not lift  
off on its station-supply mission until the Memorial Day weekend. 
But this morning, managers said they have a better shot now of 
launching the shuttle as early as May 27. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because the weather forecast has improved for the  
shuttle's planned trip back to the pad on Thursday -- the day it was 
originally supposed to blast off -- and because the repairs went so 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	The shuttle is loaded with 1 1/2 tons of equipment for the  
international space station, which was hoisted into orbit late last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery was returned to the hangar last weekend for repairs to  
its external fuel tank. Technicians discovered 648 holes in the 
foam insulation covering the tank, more than they expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the insulation holes were so small they did not need to  
be fixed, Wells said. Most were sanded or patched to prevent ice 
from forming when the tank is filled with super-cold fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers feared ice in the cavities could break off during  
liftoff and damage the shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuttle managers figure they will need a week to prepare  
Discovery for launch once it's back on the pad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
