<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres, Leafs: Great Lakes Showdown / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Many Toronto sports fans have a soft spot for  
Buffalo, a small-market city with Canadian-style winters, just 100 
miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Temporarily, though, the Peace Bridge that links Buffalo to  
Ontario may need another name. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time ever, the beloved hockey teams of Toronto and  
Buffalo are facing each other in a playoff series, with a berth in 
the Stanley Cup finals at stake. Players on both teams agree: Leafs 
vs. Sabres is a classic rivalry waiting for ignition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to start writing some history now,'' said Sabres  
forward Dixon Ward after his team advanced over Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eastern Conference championship series opens Sunday in  
Toronto; it will be the Sabres' first visit to the new Air Canada 
Centre. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the matchup was determined, the Canadian media dubbed  
it the ``QEW Series'' after Queen Elizabeth Way, the highway 
linking Toronto to the Buffalo-Niagara Falls region. 
</P>
<P>
	With the two arenas only two hours apart, large numbers of fans  
-- including some without tickets for the sold-out games -- are 
expected to drive to other city to support their team on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to lock our doors over here because of all the  
Leafs fans coming over,'' said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff. ``It should 
be mayhem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series has an extra dimension for Sabres players such as  
Jason Woolley and captain Michael Peca, raised as Leafs fans in 
Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Peca saw TV footage of Toronto fans celebrating in the streets  
Monday night after the Leafs eliminated Pittsburgh, and he recalled 
joining similar revelry as a fan six years ago when Toronto won a 
playoff series over Detroit with an overtime goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was me. ... I was that guy honking the horns and cheering  
the Leafs on,'' Peca said. ``It's going to be fun being one of the 
guys trying to upset those people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Leafs, it's the first time in the Stanley Cup's final  
four since 1994. Toronto hasn't won the cup since 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have never won the cup, although this is their second  
straight appearance in the Eastern Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo is often depicted sympathetically in the Canadian media  
as a Canadian-style sports city, faced with the same small-market 
challenges -- and often brutal winter weather -- that beset places 
like Edmonton and Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buffalo Bills of the National Football League are covered  
like a hometown team by the Toronto media, a phenomenon that has 
intensified since the Bills gave their quarterback job to longtime 
Canadian Football League superstar Doug Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres and Leafs met five times during the regular season,  
with Buffalo winning three but losing the last two. The Leafs, the 
NHL's highest-scoring team, outshot the Sabres 163-119 in those 
games, yet were outscored 17-10, thanks to the goaltending of 
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	The main reason the teams haven't met in the playoffs previously  
is that the Leafs, until this season, played in the Western 
Conference. The series with Buffalo is just the sort of showdown 
the Leafs' brass hoped for when they finally won their bid to move 
into the same conference with such natural rivals as Buffalo, 
Montreal, Boston and Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be pretty intense,'' said Leafs president Ken Dryden.  
``We want rivalries, and rivalries get spawned in playoff series.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gonzalez Hit Streak at 30 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Arizona's Luis Gonzalez extended his  
hitting streak to 30 games with a two-run, first-inning home run 
off San Francisco's Chris Brock on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-game streak matches the longest this decade, set in 1997  
by both Boston's Nomar Garciaparra and Cleveland's Sandy Alomar 
Jr., then again last year by Baltimore's Eric Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez's streak is the longest in the National League since  
Jerome Walton also hit in 30 straight in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez becomes the 37th player in major league history to have  
a hitting streak reach 30 games. Eleven of those failed to get a 
hit in their next game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gonzalez Hit Streak at 30 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Arizona's Luis Gonzalez extended his  
hitting streak to 30 games with a two-run, first-inning home run 
off San Francisco's Chris Brock on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-game streak matches the longest this decade, set in 1997  
by both Boston's Nomar Garciaparra and Cleveland's Sandy Alomar 
Jr., then again last year by Baltimore's Eric Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez's streak is the longest in the National League since  
Jerome Walton also hit in 30 straight in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez becomes the 37th player in major league history to have  
a hitting streak reach 30 games. Eleven of those failed to get a 
hit in their next game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
