<HEADLINE> Racing Writer Gallaher Dies at 75 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Mary Jane Gallaher, a turf writer who also  
worked in advertising and public relations promoting the equine 
industry, has died. She was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	She died Monday night of a head injury received May 11 in a fall  
down a flight of stairs at her home, according to a Fayette County 
coroner's office report. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher wrote about horses and their owners for the Lexington  
Leader in the 1950s. She also wrote for the Thoroughbred Record and 
The Blood-Horse magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mary Jane was just intimately involved in the thoroughbred  
business from the time she was a young woman, and was very 
involved, not just in a journalistic sense, but in a practical 
sense as well,'' said Arnold Kirkpatrick, former editor of the 
Thoroughbred Record. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father, Allan Gallaher, a horse trainer and owner, bought  
land near Lexington in the early 1920s. The 35-acre Gallaher Farm 
was sold by Gallaher and her sister, Polly Gallaher Gaitskill, to 
William du Pont III for $1,755,000 in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher landed a job at the Thoroughbred Record in the 1940s.  
She wrote a turf column called First Call for the Leader between 
1950 and 1957. She concentrated on racetrack color and topics of 
human interest. 
</P>
<P>
	She wrote about horses at a time when women weren't allowed in  
most racetrack press boxes. She reportedly was the first female 
reporter allowed in the Churchill Downs press box in Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher is survived by her husband, Fred R. Kissling; two  
stepdaughters, Jayne Kissling Tannenbaum of Atlanta and Sarah 
Kissling Hendrix of Lexington; and her sister, who lives in 
Lexington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
