<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bait Man Tries To Help the Herring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Every spring when the Atlantic  
herring begin to run, Paul Bettencourt can be found at an old dam 
at the mouth of Ten Mile River. 
</P>
<P>
	Stooped over in his flannel shirt and Greek fishing cap,  
Bettencourt scoops up the herring with a net and puts them in a 
pond on the other side so they can spawn. 
</P>
<P>
	Without him, the herring would swim in vain in the churning  
waters below the 10-foot dam, trapped a few feet from their 
spawning grounds after a treacherous migration from the ocean and 
up Narragansett Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers have joined him over the years, but locals know it's  
Bettencourt who brought the herring back to Ten Mile River. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of the last hunter-gatherers,'' said Andy Lipsky, a  
habitat restoration specialist with the environmental group Save 
the Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	For Bettencourt, 59, a retired bait fisherman, it's simply a way  
to repay nature. 
</P>
<P>
	Before a bad back forced him out of the bait business,  
Bettencourt caught just about anything that wriggled, swam and fit 
on a hook. 
</P>
<P>
	Shiners, eels, herring, crawfish, shrimp, shad: ``You name it, I  
fished it,'' said Bettencourt, whose face is etched with the lines 
of a lifetime in the wind and sun. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next to my family, the water is my one love.''  
</P>
<P>
	His interest in herring began as a child in the late 1940s and  
early '50s, when Bettencourt and his brother caught and sold the 
fish door-to-door in the Jewish neighborhoods of Providence's East 
Side. People pickled or smoked them for food; others ate the 
females' pungent orange roe. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettencourt went into the bait business full-time as a young  
man, and he often found himself near the dam on Ten Mile River. 
</P>
<P>
	It's shameful, he thought, that no herring could reach Omega  
Pond. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to move the dam, Bettencourt decided to move the fish.  
</P>
<P>
	It was the early 1970s and the dam had long since choked off the  
pond. So, Bettencourt and his brother removed the back seat from 
his beat-up '63 Ford, put in barrels and drove to a thriving 
herring run down the bay. 
</P>
<P>
	They filled the barrels, drove back to Ten Mile River and dumped  
them just beyond the dam. 
</P>
<P>
	``We drove like hell, back and forth all night,'' Bettencourt  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next spring, Bettencourt noticed a few herring had returned,  
so he scooped them over the dam. 
</P>
<P>
	He made a few more trips in his old Ford, continued to scoop the  
herring over the dam every spring and slowly brought life back to 
the pond, where the hatchlings fatten themselves all summer before 
heading to sea in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The dam on Ten Mile River is like many that were built on rivers  
up and down the Atlantic coast to create power or reservoirs for 
towns and cities. As the dams went up in a wave of industrial 
progress, the herring, salmon and other fish that travel upriver to 
spawn suffered. 
</P>
<P>
	Ponds and marshes became dumps. Industrial pollution and sewage  
made the rivers inhospitable. The herring stocks plunged in New 
England; commercial harvesting ceased in Narragansett Bay in 1930. 
</P>
<P>
	``They became a ghost of the past,'' Lipsky said.  
</P>
<P>
	Of 50 historic fish runs on Narragansett Bay, 35 are blocked,  
according to a report by the Save the Bay group. Water quality has 
improved dramatically over the past 25 years, but the fish can't 
get past obstructions. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the same on many waterways up and down the East Coast, said  
Michael Hayden, president of the American Sportfishing Association 
in Alexandria, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``The herring are at the base of the food chain for a lot of  
bigger fish such as striped bass,'' said Hayden. ``They are 
critical to the ecosystem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The association provides $400,000 in matching money annually  
through its Fish America Foundation to help fishing clubs and 
communities restore fish runs, but more money is needed, Hayden 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More people might be concerned if they knew George Washington  
was a herring man, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington earned much of his money by catching, salting and  
selling herring that surged up the Potomac River every spring near 
his Mount Vernon estate, Hayden said. To this day, the Potomac 
still supports one of the East's largest herring runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The herring runs here today are not what they were in George  
Washington's day, but they are a far cry from their lowest point'' 
in the early 1970s, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at Ten Mile River, Bettencourt hoists his small net to show  
several observers two eight-inch herring. He plops them into the 
water and watches as they swam into the reeds. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everyone does his part, we can bring the fish back, improve  
the environment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he scrambled down the granite stones to the water's edge  
and plunged his net into the roiling water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
