<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Calls Bush, Dole Untested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander said  
Wednesday he has the experience and personal character to seize the 
White House in 2000, dismissing Republican front-runners George W. 
Bush and Elizabeth Dole as ``completely untested candidates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, in an hour-long interview with The Associated Press,  
also fleshed out his gun control policy by supporting mandatory 
trigger locks for guns, background checks at gun shows and raising 
the age limit for purchasing and possessing handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	He called Vice President Al Gore, the leading Democratic  
contender, the ``head cheerleader'' for a disgraced president and 
accused him of trying to run local schools from Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	He blasted President Clinton's policies on Kosovo, saying the  
Monica Lewinsky investigation distracted him early in the crisis 
and stripped him of ``the moral authority'' to lead America and its 
allies. 
</P>
<P>
	And he said nothing in his personal background will be out  
bounds for the 2000 campaign. ``I'll answer questions about my 
character,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, 58, finished third in the 1996 Iowa caucuses and New  
Hampshire primary but is best remembered for his signature red 
plaid shirts. Dressed in a crisp suit and tie, Alexander said he 
retired his 1996 attire because voters knew more about his plaid 
than his platform. 
</P>
<P>
	``My shtick is I'm ready to be president and the rest (of the  
GOP field) are relatively untested,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shtick has yet to stick: Alexander is still a blip in  
Republican presidential surveys dominated by Bush, the Texas 
governor, and Mrs. Dole, the former American Red Cross president. 
</P>
<P>
	While Alexander has campaigned for president almost nonstop  
since 1995, Bush and Mrs. Dole are first-time candidates with 
well-known names. Bush is the son of former President George Bush; 
Mrs. Dole is the wife of 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are almost completely untested candidates in the  
national arena,'' Alexander said of Bush, Mrs. Dole and the rest of 
the GOP field. 
</P>
<P>
	As a former governor, college president, secretary of Education  
and businessman, Alexander said he is the most prepared. ``I've had 
more elective executive experience than all the rest of the 
Republican candidates put together,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Alexander knows the only way he can win the nomination is  
for Bush to falter under the weight of high expectations. And thus 
the interview signaled a shift in his strategy, with an increased 
emphasis on Bush's potential weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a big step from being a pretty good governor to being  
president of the United States,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Re-elected by a landslide in November, Bush has held elective  
office a little more than four years and has yet to campaign 
outside Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander also said of Bush:  
</P>
<P>
	--''There've been Texans before with lots of money who've blown  
through Iowa and blown out without votes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--''I'm skeptical of people who begin their national careers in  
the Oval Office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--''I was a one-term governor once. I thought I was pretty good.  
Was I ready to be president of the United States, to deal with 
Kosovo ... North Korea and the schools in this country and the 
aftermath of Littleton?,'' Alexander said, referring to the 
Colorado school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt it.''  
</P>
<P>
	In his most pointed reference to Bush's limited experience, he  
recalled that the governor recently called Kosovars ``Kosovarians'' 
and Greeks ``Grecians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That kind of mistake would sink Bush in a general election  
debate against Gore, Alexander warned. ``We need to know going into 
the general election that we have a candidate who's ready to be 
president,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said, ``As governor as the second  
largest state in the United States and the 11th largest economy in 
the world, he has an outstanding record of leadership and proven 
ability to unite diverse people and achieve results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Mrs. Dole was ready for the leap from Red Cross  
president to American president, Alexander said it would be 
``unusual'' for a politician to make the Oval Office her first 
elective office. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 11 most likely GOP candidates, five have never held  
elective office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's spokesman, Ari Fleischer, said his boss welcomed  
Alexander to the race, but had no comment on his remarks. Gore's 
office said his education record will speak for itself. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of stern rebuttals may suggest that Bush, Mrs. Dole and  
Gore do not view Alexander as a serious threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said character may be the most important issue of  
2000, even as Bush says he won't answers questions about his 
personal life 20 or 30 years ago. ``He'll have to decide what he 
does,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he supports some gun control, including raising the  
minimum age for gun purchases and possession to 21, Alexander 
accused Congress of taking part in a ``legislative orgy'' in the 
aftermath of the Colorado shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the only way to prevent school shootings is to make  
parenting easier with family-friendly policies such as reducing 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	In Austin, Bush said Wednesday he has no problem with requiring  
locks to be sold with guns, but thinks their use should be 
voluntary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
