<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesians Rally for Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Megawati Sukarnoputri grew up in  
Indonesia's presidential palace. Now she hopes that the first free 
election since her father suspended democracy 44 years ago will 
lead her back to the white-columned mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of thousands of her supporters choked Jakarta's streets  
Wednesday, dominating the official launch of the three-week 
campaign for the June 7 vote for a new Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the biggest outpouring of support so far for Megawati,  
the daughter of Indonesia's founding leader, Sukarno, and now a 
front-runner for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's parade through the capital was supposed to have  
promoted all 48 parties participating in what the government 
promises will be the first truly open ballot for the vast majority 
of the 130 million voters in the sprawling Southeast Asian island 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Each party had their own colorful convoys in the parade. But  
euphoric members of Megawati's Indonesian Democratic Party for 
Struggle took over the procession by sheer numbers, waving red 
flags and banners from the backs of trucks and motorcycles. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati's popularity has grown even though she rarely talks to  
reporters and remains vague about her party's policies. 
</P>
<P>
	While she did not take part in Wednesday's parade, she was  
clearly the object of mass adulation. Office workers lined 
Jakarta's main boulevard, cheering and clapping as party activists 
raised their fists and shouted ``Long live Mega!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts doubt her party can win power outright. Indonesia is  
the world's most populous Islamic nation and it's possible that 
conservative Muslims here might not accept a female president. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Megawati and her party top opinion polls ahead of  
the election for 462 seats in the new Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Newly elected legislators and government appointees are to form  
a special assembly later to select a head of state. 
</P>
<P>
	Her chances of getting the top job were strengthened when  
Megawati agreed to enter a coalition with two other pro-reform 
opposition parties this week. 
</P>
<P>
	They plan to put aside policy differences and use their combined  
strength in Parliament and the assembly to outvote the ruling 
Golkar Party for the first time in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar helped keep former authoritarian President Suharto in  
power for 32 years until he was forced to resign after riots and 
protests devastated the capital and left more than 1,200 dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's parade was a noisy and festive affair that was  
marred only by sporadic attacks on Golkar vehicles and officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In one incident, spectators jeered as a mob tore yellow Golkar  
signs from a truck. Later, an angry group punched and kicked a 
Golkar member. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar dominated the tightly controlled political landscape  
under Suharto, but it is now languishing in opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts predict it will face major losses at the ballot box as  
accusations of massive corruption and human rights abuses continue 
to swirl around Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar has nominated Suharto's hand-picked successor, President  
B.J. Habibie, as its presidential candidate. While he has 
instituted many reforms, he has been unable to shrug off close 
links to Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati's political rise is perhaps ironic. Her father ended  
Indonesia's last experiment with unfettered democracy in 1955. He 
later declared himself president for life, before being replaced by 
Suharto after an attempted communist coup in 1965. 
</P>
<P>
	Since entering politics in 1993, she has consistently called for  
greater democratic reform while tapping lingering nostalgia for her 
tough-talking, nationalistic father who died in disgrace in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Her popularity soared in 1996 after Suharto's regime tried to  
oust her as head of the party. 
</P>
<P>
	``Megawati has become the people's symbol of resistance in their  
fight against Suharto's regime and now Habibie's government,'' said 
Daniel Sparingga of the University of Airlangga in Surabaya. 
</P>
<P>
	``People like her, and not just because she is her father's  
daughter.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
