<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Death Row Inmate To Go to Tenn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A man who spent eight years on death row before  
DNA evidence cleared him has become the 12th condemned person in 
Illinois to be exonerated in the last 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ronald Jones didn't have much time to celebrate. He was  
in court Wednesday and said he won't fight extradition to 
Tennessee, where he escaped from a prison work detail. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 49, escaped while serving a five-year robbery sentence.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're just waiting for authorities from Tennessee to come and  
pick him up; he's basically their prisoner,'' said Bill Cunningham, 
a spokesman for the Cook County sheriff's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was convicted of the March 1985 rape and killing of Debra  
Jones. She was found fatally stabbed outside a Chicago hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he confessed, Jones said he did so after being beaten  
by police. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Supreme Court overturned the conviction in July  
1997 after DNA tests of semen showed that Jones was not the 
assailant. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cook County state's attorney's office on Monday announced it  
would not retry Jones on the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Pam Hobbins, a spokeswoman for the Tennessee Department of  
Corrections, said Jones was convicted of a 1979 robbery in 
Chattanooga and was serving five years in Cold Creek Correctional 
Facility when he slipped away from a community work crew in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
