<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Debate Over Lottery at Vets' Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLYOKE, Mass. (AP) -- Having risked their lives for their  
country, veterans living at the Holyoke Soldiers Home doubt it 
would be a big problem to risk a few dollars on scratch-off lottery 
tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Life is a gamble,'' said Geno Majewski, 71, a World War II  
combat veteran, chuckling at the debate in the state Legislature 
whether to allow the sale of lottery tickets in the state-run home. 
</P>
<P>
	Selling tickets at the home would be a convenience for its 284  
residents, Majewski said as he watched television in the spacious 
canteen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the fellows like to buy scratch tickets,'' he said May  
11. ``It gives them a little thrill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next to the big television set hung an even larger bingo board  
ready for the 50-cent-a-card games run nearly daily by local 
service and veterans organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the bill, including the Massachusetts Council on  
Compulsive Gambling, worry the aged veterans on fixed incomes are 
all too vulnerable to the lure of gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't sound like a good idea to me,'' said Gov. Paul  
Cellucci. ``I'll listen to the proposal, but I don't think you want 
to have lots of tickets sold in a home or residence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature got involved because it is against state law for  
state employees to sell lottery tickets, and the home's canteen 
staff are on the state payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Senate approved the bill, which would allow state  
employees at the home to sell the tickets, and sent it to the House 
where gambling foes have said they will try to block it. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't like cigarettes, either'' chorused a group of  
veterans smoking on a sunny outside patio. The only place inside 
the home where smoking is allowed is a glassed-in area in one 
corner of the canteen. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, one reason the home's management wants to sell lottery  
tickets is the sharp drop in revenue the canteen suffered after it 
stopped selling cigarettes, according to Paul Morin, the home's 
executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly they are still getting cigarettes,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said, in the same way the Soldiers' Home canteen  
doesn't sell ice cream to diabetics, scratch tickets wouldn't be 
sold to compulsive gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some residents are opposed to the measure.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who wants to play the lottery can go downtown and get  
a ticket or have a friend pick a number,'' said Edgar Hebert, as he 
waited for the bus outside the home. ``I don't think they should 
sell them in the canteen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Senate Minority Leader Brian Lees, a sponsor of the bill,  
said it would only be fair, because veterans at the state's other 
Soldiers Home in Chelsea are able to buy lottery tickets from a 
canteen operated by blind people who are not state employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Some state-run veterans homes in other states, including New  
York and New Jersey, also sell state lottery tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes the veterans feel like they are living on the  
outside,'' said Brian Gordon, community relations director for the 
Long Island Veterans Home run by New York state. ``They can wheel 
into our canteen just as if they were wheeling into a candy store 
in Brooklyn and buy a candy bar or a scratch ticket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have some people who play a little bit more regularly,''  
Gordon said, but those who receive Medicaid for their care get less 
than $50 a month in discretionary money. 
</P>
<P>
	``How much of an addict can you be on $50 a month?'' he asked.  
</P>
<P>
	State Treasurer Shannon O'Brien, who supervises the  
Massachusetts lottery, agreed. Recalling visiting her late 
great-uncle in the Holyoke Soldiers Home, O'Brien said it is a 
question of individual choice and convenience for the veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether they want to spend their discretionary money on a  
small ice cream cone or a pack of cigarettes, they deserve, as 
adults, to make these decisions for themselves,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
