	May 19  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on Israeli election:  
</P>
<P>
	There is just a year left to achieve peace in the Middle East.  
Negligence on the part of Prime Minister Nenanyahu to talk with the 
Palestinians is taking its toll. The Barak administration will need 
to start by trying to regain the trust of the Palestinians and the 
world. But Barak's own stand on peace with the Palestinians raises 
some concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	In campaigning references to the Jewish settlements in Israel's  
occupied territories, Barak said he would not build new 
settlements, but instead would put most of the established 
settlements under Israeli control. He also did not yield on the 
status of Jerusalem. He said both East and West Jerusalem are the 
eternally indivisible capital of Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	His stand on such issues is similar to that taken by Netanyahu.  
This will not make it easy to resolve differences with the 
Palestinians. We hope the new government will try to consider the 
Palestinian position and find common ground that both the Israelis 
and Palestinianss can find satisfactory. ... 

</P>
