<P>
	Il Giornale, Milan, Italy, on Israeli election:  
</P>
<P>
	Ehud Barak has triumphed, marking a shift in Israel's political  
orientation: Benjamin Netanyahu's crushing defeat and his 
subsequent resignation from the leadership of his Likud party have 
already caused a crisis in the right wing, which has dropped to its 
lowest level since 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the unquestionable winner is (Palestinian leader)  
Yasser Arafat, whose political and international prestige has been 
boosted by these elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Militarily and economically weak, at the head of a corrupt  
administration, Arafat turned all of Netanyau's bitter pills into 
diplomatic advantages. His collaboration with Israel's secret 
service prevented terrorist attacks. His endorsement of the Wye 
Plantation agreement gained him President Clinton's sympathy and 
$600 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat avoided all of Netanyau's traps and discreetly shifted  
the Arab votes towards Barak. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Netanyau's irresolution and his strive for  
personal affirmation overwhelmed some positive results of his 
premiership. 

</P>
<P>
	May 17  
</P>
<P>
	Tages-Anzeiger, Zurich, Switzerland, on Russian President  
Yeltsin: 
</P>
<P>
	Who is to blame? In Russian history, so rich in tragedy, this  
question is asked again and again. Because the individual was not 
ready to assume the responsibility, the questions could also be 
suppressed in the collectivity. Nobody was called to account. ... 
</P>
<P>
	In the debate over impeaching President Yeltsin, the Russian  
parliament was again asking the question `Who is to blame?' This 
time it was over the responsibility for the emotions and mistakes 
of the previous 10 years: the breakup of the Soviet Union, the war 
against Chechnya, the failed economic reforms. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Seen in the context of Russian history, this event is somewhat  
revolutionary. It was a signal that a future president will no 
longer simply be able to do what he wants. His actions must be 
transparent and controllable. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last 10 years there have been few bright spots in Russia.  
The failed attempt to impeach Yeltsin is, in spite of everything, a 
step forward. 

</P>
<P>
