<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Might Limit U.S. Lab Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson is ready to  
support limits on foreign scientific exchanges at U.S. weapons 
laboratories, but he warned Tuesday that a sweeping moratorium 
would hurt America's interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, touring an exhibit of anti-terrorist gadgets  
developed by scientists at the labs, said the kinds of restrictions 
being discussed by some in Congress would scuttle U.S. attempts to 
help Russia safeguard its nuclear material. 
</P>
<P>
	``If adopted it would literally mean the closure of our Russia  
lab-to-lab program,'' said Richardson. He was speaking of a House 
proposal to impose a broad, unrestricted moratorium on foreign 
visits to the three weapons labs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russia program has been a top Clinton administration  
priority because its aim is to help Russia keep its nuclear 
material and top scientists from going into the service of 
dangerous governments. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, more than 1,200 Russian and Chinese visitors were  
logged in at the New Mexico's Los Alamos and California's Lawrence 
Livermore weapons labs, Energy Department records show. The General 
Accounting Office, Congress' auditing agency, recently said visits 
to all the labs by scientists from ``sensitive'' countries soared 
from 500 to more than 1,800 in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange program has become a focus of attention in Congress  
as lawmakers attempt to grapple with reports of years of lax 
security at the weapons labs and of theft by China of nuclear 
warhead secrets. A voluminous congressional report on Chinese 
technology thefts is expected to be released within days. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said a Senate measure on the foreign visitor program,  
which cleared the Armed Services Committee this week, is one ``that 
we can live with'' and reflects ``bipartisan support to fix the 
problem cooperatively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That legislation would halt lab-to-lab foreign visitors unless  
the heads of the Central Intelligence Agency and the FBI and the 
energy secretary certify adequate counterintelligence safeguards. 
Administration officials said under those conditions essential 
programs would not be affected under the new security measures 
being put in place. 
</P>
<P>
	The House proposal, offered by Rep. Jim Ryun, R-Kan., bans  
visits from ``sensitive'' countries unless a waiver is given by 
concerned congressional committees. Ryun called it ``a mechanism to 
ensure our vital national security secrets are protected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such restrictions, Richardson said, would close down the Russia  
program and is an overreaction. ``It's draconian. It hurts our 
national security,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the anti-terrorist equipment Richardson viewed was  
developed at the weapons labs in conjunction with private industry 
and in some cases as part of the Russia lab-to-lab exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	One exhibit featured physical security measures aimed at  
preventing break-ins at nuclear facilities. Richardson was given a 
key to what was supposed to be a nuclear vault. He succeeded in 31 
seconds to break in, but was caught by the alarm and a hidden 
camera. 
</P>
<P>
	That project, as well as another from the Lawrence Livermore lab  
on detecting nuclear material in transit, were developed as part of 
the Russia exchange program, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Winifred Parker, a nuclear chemist at Lawrence Livermore, said  
she visited Russia twice and worked with Russians who have visited 
the U.S. lab in California to work on the nuclear material 
detection technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can't visit the Russians and they can't come to us, work  
is almost impossible,'' she said. ``We really need to be able to 
talk, to have scientists talking to other scientists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At yet another booth, Morton Lieberman of Sandia National  
Laboratories in New Mexico, showed off a high-tech artificial foot. 
He said the foot was the product of a cooperative effort between 
Tufts University and a weapons lab in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
