<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Counselor Sets Up Talk Show Therapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Thousands of people appear on national talk shows,  
sharing their problems and perversities with millions of television 
viewers. When their 15 minutes of fame is over and the audience 
goes home, what happens to those who have aired their dirty laundry 
in public? 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Huysman, a clinical social worker and addiction counselor,  
has built a business helping talk show guests whose psychological 
problems may be magnified by the sometimes negative experiences 
they encounter on national TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman developed his AfterCare Program in 1991 after appearing  
as a guest expert on ``The Geraldo Rivera Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just saw that talk television was an incredible way to reach  
mainstream America,'' Huysman said. ``It could be a powerful 
process if you get healing attached or it could be terribly 
exploitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman approached the show about setting up opportunities for  
guests to receive outside counseling, and Rivera agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If talk shows decide to take on the job or the editorial  
approach of broadcasting people in crisis then I think television 
has an absolute obligation to do something about the crisis they're 
talking about,'' Rivera has said in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman created a nationwide network of hospitals, outpatient  
programs, therapists, lawyers, consumer credit agencies and other 
resources that would offer their services for free if they received 
some sort of publicity on the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found that a 30 second spot on a national show was about the  
cost to treat a client,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman said he didn't like how talk show guests opened  
emotional wounds on television and then were sent home with little 
or no follow-up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that a lot of them do go hoping for help,'' he said.  
``But expectations become the seeds of resentment. Whatever 
problems they had are now exacerbated because now the whole 
community knows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of those treated by Huysman was Scott Sweat, who weighed 750  
pounds when he appeared on Rivera's syndicated show twice in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweat had sought help for his obesity from the Rivera show after  
being rejected by numerous clinics because he couldn't afford them. 
</P>
<P>
	After his TV appearances, he worked with Huysman's counseling  
and weight control programs, and is now down to 549 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I would have done without (Jamie). He's kept  
me alive,'' said Sweat, talking by phone from a friend's home in 
Resaca, Ga. ``He saw me through and told me things were going to be 
OK and they were.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before Rivera's show went off the air a year ago, Huysman helped  
about 200 guests and secured $4 million in donated health care for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past year, the AfterCare Program has worked with the  
``Leeza'' show on NBC, which pays about $5,000 a month for the 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman's team trains the show's producers to prescreen  
potential guests for warning signs that it would be detrimental for 
them to go on the show. In addition, Huysman's case managers follow 
the progress after the show of each guest and family members deemed 
potentially troubled. 
</P>
<P>
	He has helped about 50 ``Leeza'' guests and secured $500,000 in  
donated health care for them. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all shows use Huysman's services. ``The Jerry Springer  
Show'' doesn't, and neither does ``The Jenny Jones Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman testified against Ms. Jones' show in a recent lawsuit,  
saying that prescreening might have detected the potential 
emotional fallout between two male guests that allegedly led to 
one's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, the family of former guest Scott Amedure was  
awarded $25 million by a Michigan jury that found that the show and 
its producer, Warner Bros., negligent in Amedure's 1995 shooting 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	In an episode that was never broadcast, Amedure admitted that he  
was attracted to Jonathan Schmitz, who had agreed to appear to meet 
his secret admirer. Schmitz had said he expected to meet a female 
admirer. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz's conviction for second-degree murder was reversed on a  
technicality; his retrial is scheduled for this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Huysman testified that he met with Ms. Jones a year before the  
shooting to suggest that her show could use the counseling 
available through the AfterCare Program. He never heard back from 
the show's producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls from The Associated Press to ``The Jenny Jones Show'' were  
not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Farrell, a licensed psychologist in Engelwood, N.J.,  
who isn't associated with Huysman or Ms. Jones, said she supports 
therapy for some talk show guests, but is less convinced that a 
pre-show evaluation can help weed out potentially dangerous guests. 
</P>
<P>
	``A screening is no guarantee that you will pick something up,''  
she said. ``I think the problem is that many people don't realize 
that they have undiscovered buttons that if pushed can cause them 
to do things they never dreamed they would. No psychologist is 
going to be able to pick these up in an interview or in a 
screening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his work with AfterCare, Huysman has built  
another business, Partners in Health &AMP; Entertainment Management in 
Fort Lauderdale, which coordinates the services that come in to 
AfterCare. He also runs At the End of the Day Productions, Inc., 
which owns the license for AfterCare as well as a radio show, 
``Family Affairs,'' that Huysman has with his mother, a clinical 
psychologist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Family Affairs'' has mother and son talking about issues often  
seen on daytime talk shows. They just finished a TV pilot for a 
talk show by the same name. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sgt.: Volpe Boasted About Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of torturing a Haitian  
immigrant in a station house bathroom boasted about it that morning 
and then showed the stick he used, a sergeant testified Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, in an account never made public before,  
said that Officer Justin Volpe pulled him aside and told him what 
he did to Abner Louima. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima claims Volpe sodomized him with a broom handle in a case  
that shocked the city due to the brutal nature of the charges and 
has raised tensions between minorities and the police department. 
Five officers are accused in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Wernick testified that Volpe told him he had been punched  
earlier that morning in a street disturbance which led to Louima's 
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe then said he ``took a stick and put it five or six inches  
up (Louima's rectum), took it out and put it up to his mouth and 
teeth area, kind of like showing it to him. ... He told him that if 
he told anyone, he'd kill him and his whole family,'' Wernick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe asked Wernick if he wanted to see the stick, then took him  
into the bathroom and pulled out a 2- to 3-foot, gray-colored stick 
from a sink area, Wernick said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you believe him?'' asked prosecutor Alan Vinegrad.  
</P>
<P>
	``No, because I didn't think anybody would do that, and if they  
did, they wouldn't talk about it,'' said Wernick, a burly officer 
who wore his patrol uniform to court. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, officer Charles Schwarz and two other officers, Thomas  
Bruder and Thomas Wiese, are also charged with violating Louima's 
civil rights by beating him in a patrol car en route to the 
station. A fifth defendant is charged with covering up the 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier testimony, another man, Patrick Antoine, claimed  
Volpe punched him for no reason in the street around the nightclub. 
He testified that he too was taken into the bathroom by the officer 
-- but that Volpe apologized after he noticed Antoine was wearing a 
cross. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe asked if he believed in Jesus, Antoine said. ``I said,  
`Yes'. ... He told me he believed in Jesus, too. ... After that he 
told me that if someone hits him, he hits the person back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Louima and Antoine have filed multimillion-dollar lawsuits  
against the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank One Bets on Internet for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Banks expect someday the walls will come tumbling  
down as they move to become virtual institutions offering an array 
of services over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives at Bank One Corp., the nation's fifth-largest bank,  
took the bold step Tuesday of announcing that they're placing their 
bets on the Web as the surest future source of profits, giving up 
the industrywide practice of mergers and consolidation for growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to follow your customer,'' Bank One chief executive  
John McCoy said. ``I've always loved this business for the last 20 
years, but we aren't going to be like that anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a related announcement, First Union Corp., the sixth-largest  
bank, announced it is realigning its senior executive team and 
appointing an 18-year bank veteran to take charge of its electronic 
commerce businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	David Carroll, now president of First Union of Florida, will  
become executive vice president in charge of Internet and 
``alternative delivery channels'' -- businesses that the bank called 
a key corporate priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll has been credited with leading First Union's ``Future  
Bank'' strategy that offers banking by telephone, computer and 
automatic tellers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to fully leverage the various skills we have  
throughout First Union to build an Internet strategy and capability 
second to none in the financial services arena,'' said John 
Georgius, First Union president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking executives across the nation are tentatively exploring  
their options for virtual banking. The explosion of Internet use 
and the rise of such Wall Street darlings as the retailer 
Amazon.com and Charles Schwab Corp.'s online brokerage has many 
re-examining whether the concept of acquiring more branches, 
automated teller machines and banking satellites is the way to 
survive. 
</P>
<P>
	One Internet bank, Netbank Inc. of Alpharetta, Ga., has become a  
major player in just a year. With just 42 employees, the company 
had profits last year of $4.5 million on sales of $18.8 million. 
Because of its low overhead, it has signed up thousands of 
customers by offering higher interest rates on CDs and other 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago-based Bank One was created last year through the  
combination of First Chicago NBD Corp. and Banc One Corp. It has 
about 2,000 branches in 14 states, mostly in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	It recently launched http://www.bankone.com, a site offering customers  
the chance to open and review accounts, receive and pay bills 
online, apply for credit cards and loans, invest online, buy 
insurance and get news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The features make it one of the most comprehensive banking sites  
in the nation, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It offers them the opportunity to provide their services  
anywhere (in the world),'' Salomon Smith Barney analyst Henry 
Dickson said. ``Right now, that might not be the most profitable 
way of doing things, but it's something they have to offer because 
it's another way to reach customers who want convenience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bank One is betting it can vault into national consciousness by  
signing long-term agreements with Internet portal companies such as 
Yahoo! and Excite Inc. Portals are the entry points for users to 
venture onto the Internet. The agreements guarantee that Web 
surfers looking for Internet banking on those sites will be 
directed to Bank One. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank One also expects to sign up additional credit card  
customers online. It will generate additional revenue from customer 
fees for online banking. And it will collect fees from companies 
that will sell insurance and other products on its site. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Bank One merger was completed late last year, McCoy  
said it would be at least 18 months before he considered acquiring 
another bank. Even after that period is up, an acquisition may not 
be considered, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With what is happening on the Internet, I'm not sure that we  
will ever have to buy another bank,'' he said. ``There may come a 
time where we don't need to provide the brick and mortar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under First Union's ``Future Bank'' program, for example,  
customers use a telephone or computer to get information about 
account balances, advise whether checks have cleared, or transfer 
money between accounts. Customers also can apply for loans by phone 
or get help with investments. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union has about 2,400 branches in 12 states, mostly on the  
East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say it's too early to tell just how much banks can  
profit from the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A lot will depend on how efficiently they offer products and  
whether increased competition will cause fees to fall and thereby 
lower profits, they say. Most predicted, however, that banks will 
need to maintain some branches for those customers who want to do 
their business face-to-face. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
