<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:52:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pens' Future in Steel Town Unknown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins went home until next  
season Wednesday with the prospect of the NHL moving or breaking up 
the franchise looming over them. 
</P>
<P>
	That wouldn't make the players happy.  
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I hope the team stays in Pittsburgh,'' said Jaromir  
Jagr, the league's leading scorer last season. ``We have a lot of 
good players here. ... I had a lot of fun this season, and I think 
we can do better next season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz said Wednesday he is  
inclined to present the NHL's plan to break up the Penguins to the 
team's 200 creditors for a vote alongside competing plans, possibly 
June 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Rob Brown wants anything but.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was glad to get the opportunity to play here, and I hope  
that everything works out this summer,'' he said at the Penguins' 
practice facility in Canonsburg, Pa. ``It's hard to believe there 
is a chance the team might not be here, but I think it should all 
work out in the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps Mario Lemieux is the best alternative.  
</P>
<P>
	The retired Penguins superstar and a group led by Penguins  
landlord SMG and broadcaster Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh have drafted 
proposals for running the financially troubled team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's plan is already set for a vote, and the SMG-Fox plan  
will be reviewed and challenged May 28. Fox must surrender its 
stake in the New York Rangers to own part of the Penguins, NHL 
attorney Jeffrey Levitan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL wants to dissolve the team and sell the franchise,  
reportedly for $85 million to Seattle billionaire Paul Allen for a 
move to the Rose Garden in Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitan said the league also could allow other teams to  
cherry-pick Penguins players in a draft or buy the contracts and 
divide them up. 
</P>
<P>
	Creditors on Wednesday faulted the NHL for vagueness about  
details such as what they would be paid if the Penguins are sold or 
players moved out. One creditors' attorney chided the NHL strategy 
as ``an option on an option on an option.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You need a scorecard here,'' said the attorney, Joseph  
McDonough. 
</P>
<P>
	The league eased off its May 31 deadline and now wants ownership  
resolved by June 27. Its plan guarantees the NHL the entire $1.7 
million it is owed, while most creditors will be paid only a 
percentage of the Penguins' total debt of $125 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitan said the NHL cannot accurately predict what the players'  
contracts will fetch. Any draft and its terms still would have to 
be approved by the NHL Board of Governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, Lemieux and the SMG-Fox group will meet with Bill  
Newlin, a lawyer and negotiator appointed by Pittsburgh Mayor Tom 
Murphy, in an attempt to merge their plans. Newlin helped broker a 
deal that kept the baseball Pirates in Pittsburgh with general 
partner Kevin McClatchy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the NHL needs to be a partner with us in trying to  
save this franchise here and not put up roadblocks to make that 
happen,'' Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy said the team might get a new arena supported partially  
by taxes once the team is financially healthy. The Penguins are 
committed to the Civic Arena, the league's oldest venue, which is 
managed by SMG, through 2007. SMG and Fox need to embrace Lemieux's 
group to save the team, Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strength will be if we can combine them in a way that  
works for everybody,'' the mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mixed messages come forth daily in the case. The NHL has  
maintained public support of a Pittsburgh team run by Lemieux while 
moving ahead in court with the plan to padlock the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pittsburgh, the Penguins matter pits civic pride against the  
private stakes of the team's creditors, many of whom operate in the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Heather Lennox, attorney for creditor National City Bank, made a  
spirited plea for the team during objections to the NHL's plan. 
Markovitz interrupted to ask whether the bank would take a smaller 
percentage of what it is owed if the team would stay in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I really wouldn't characterize it that way,'' Lennox said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Then let's get back to the real issues,'' the judge said.  
</P>
<P>
	The NHL is preparing three schedules for 1999-2000: one with the  
Penguins, one with the Penguins somewhere else and one without the 
team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
