<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of May 23-29:  
</P>
<P>
	70 years ago: The Marx Brothers starred in their first film,  
``The Cocoanuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	55 years ago: ``Mr. Skeffington'' starred Bette Davis and Claude  
Rains. 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: John Wayne starred in ``The High and the Mighty,''  
often referred to as the ``granddaddy'' of airborne disaster films. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: Dustin Hoffman and Jon Voight starred in John  
Schlesinger's ``Midnight Cowboy.'' The film won Oscars for best 
picture and best director. 
</P>
<P>
	Creedence Clearwater Revival made its first appearance on the  
British singles chart with ``Proud Mary,'' which eventually reached 
the Top 10. 
</P>
<P>
	And John Lennon and Yoko Ono began a ``Bed-In for Peace'' in  
Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: Sigourney Weaver starred in ``Alien,'' a sci-fi  
horror movie. The film was followed by ``Aliens,'' ``Alien 3'' and 
``Alien Resurrection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And ``The Kids Are Alright,'' a film documentary of The Who,  
premiered in New York. The film included interviews with members of 
the British rock band, plus brief appearances by Steve Martin, Tom 
Smothers and Ringo Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Harrison Ford and Kate Capshaw starred in  
``Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: Katharine Hepburn and Red Skelton received  
lifetime achievement awards at the third annual American Comedy 
Awards. In the motion picture category, Bette Midler was selected 
funniest actress for ``Big Business'' and Tom Hanks as funniest 
actor for ``Big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago and the Beach Boys began their first tour together since  
1975 with a concert in Costa Mesa, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison Ford and Sean Connery starred in ``Indiana Jones and  
the Last Crusade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Cliff Richard, one of the most popular pop stars in Britain,  
released his 100th single, ``The Best of Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Oprah Winfrey won awards for best talk show and  
best talk-show host at the daytime Emmys. Dick Clark, a pioneer of 
daytime television, was presented with a lifetime achievement award 
for his work on ``American Bandstand'' and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	And The Eagles opened their reunion concert tour after 14 years  
of separation with a tribute to where it all began, ``Hotel 
California.'' The West Coast group's three-hour show in Irvine, 
Calif., kicked off with Don Henley, Glenn Frey, Joe Walsh, Timothy 
Schmit and Don Felder playing in front of electric blue lights. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Rock guitarist Robbie Robertson was presented a  
lifetime achievement award at the first Native American Music 
Awards. Jimi Hendrix was inducted into the Hall of Fame. The 
legendary guitarist, who died in 1970, had Cherokee ancestry. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm generous to people I know and to some people that I don't  
know, if I feel that their cause or their purpose has true meaning, 
and that they will benefit from the money.'' -- Talk-show host Oprah 
Winfrey. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``This is getting to be nice.'' -- Oprah Winfrey, as she accepted  
her fourth consecutive daytime Emmy for outstanding talk-show host. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``What pleases me the most is that the songs still work some 20  
years later. It's the same guy singing, but from a different 
place.'' -- Former ``Patridge Family'' singer David Cassidy, who 
re-recorded a soulful version of ``I Think I Love You,'' the first 
single from his new CD ``Old Trick New Dog.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
