<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Higher; Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar rose against other major currencies in  
European trading Wednesday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0654, down from $1.0682 Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Tuesday: 124.27 Japanese  
yen, up from 123.00; 1.5018 Swiss francs, up from 1.4993; and 
1.4676 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4586 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6199, down from $1.6205.  
</P>
<P>
	Midday in New York, the dollar bought 124.22 yen, while the euro  
was worth $1.0655 and the pound traded at $1.6181. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar was worth: 1.8358 German marks, up from 1.8310; 
6.1569 French francs, up from 6.1408; 2.0684 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0630; and 1,817.41 Italian lire, up from 1,812.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $272.40 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$274.20 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $274.65, down from $284.95.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $1.90 in Hong Kong to $273.15.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.30 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
