<DOCNO> APW19990519.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 01:31:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Face Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Never have the words ``road trip'' been more  
ominous to Pittsburgh Penguins fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Burdened by millions in debt and with no ownership in place, the  
Penguins could be history by June 24 -- not for the playoffs, not 
for the season, but forever. 
</P>
<P>
	There is only one man who can make the save, and it isn't  
goaltender Tom Barrasso or Hall of Famer Mario Lemieux. It is U.S. 
Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz, who will decide the team's fate 
within the next six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the judge, and the dozens of creditors who are owed  
anywhere from $26 million (Lemieux) to a few thousand dollars (a 
limousine company), can save the 32-year-old franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	If creditors approve Lemieux's reorganization plan, the Penguins  
will remain in Pittsburgh. If not, the court could choose an NHL 
plan that calls for an unidentified buyer -- presumably, billionaire 
Paul Allen -- to buy them for $85 million and relocate them, 
probably to Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	A third plan emerged Tuesday. SMG, the Penguins' landlord at the  
Civic Arena, and Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh presented a proposal 
that would make Lemieux a minority owner and consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a city-of-Pittsburgh perspective and a fan perspective,  
they should be rooting hard for our plan,'' SMG attorney Saul 
Burian said. ``Our plan, I believe, would produce a franchise that 
is in better financial shape than that which would result from a 
Lemieux plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox, SMG and their investors would own most of the team under  
their plan. If Lemieux rejects it, he would be lumped in with other 
creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said the team needs to be run by someone in Pittsburgh.  
SMG is based in Philadelphia, and Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh is part 
of a national broadcasting company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need an ownership team committed to one team in one market  
-- Pittsburgh,'' said Lemieux, the former Penguins superstar and 
sixth-leading scorer in league history. ``Our ownership group under 
my leadership will be committed exclusively to the Penguins and 
only the Penguins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins filed for bankruptcy in October, borrowed to get  
through the season, then prayed for the best. They nearly got it. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite an avalanche of distractions, including the bankruptcy,  
co-owner Roger Marino's attempts to shop the team elsewhere, Petr 
Nedved's holdout and Darius Kasparaitis' knee injury, the Penguins 
surprised top-seeded New Jersey in the first round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins then were in position to eliminate Toronto, only to  
lose the final three games. Two were in overtime, both at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The end -- and it might be permanent -- came with Monday's 4-3  
overtime loss on former teammate Garry Valk's overtime goal at 
1:57. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, I'm coming to Pittsburgh for training  
camp in September,'' forward Rob Brown said. ``In my heart, I'll be 
in Pittsburgh next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But will the Penguins?  
</P>
<P>
	Allegheny County commissioner Mike Dawida said Pittsburgh would  
survive without the Penguins, ``but they are a sign that we can't 
be called major league anymore if we were to lose such teams. They 
bring people together in a positive way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm cautiously optimistic that we will maintain the team,''  
Dawida said. 
</P>
<P>
	If this was the Penguins' last season in Pittsburgh, at least  
they left behind lots of memories. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL scoring champion Jaromir Jagr further emerged as the  
league's dominant player in the post-Lemieux and, now, post-Wayne 
Gretzky era. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for Jagr, the Penguins were mostly without their  
customary cast of stars (Lemieux, Ron Francis, Kevin Stevens, etc.) 
So they improvised, getting a career year from Martin Straka, a 
one-time castoff who made the All-Star game, and a big lift from 
rookie Jan Hrdina, who wasn't expected to make the team, but became 
the No. 1 center. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexei Kovalev finished with 53 points after being acquired in  
November for Nedved. Robert Lang and former career minor leaguer 
Kip Miller made major contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins had a 10-game winning streak earlier in the season,  
but slipped to the final spot in the conference playoffs by 
finishing 2-8-2. That sent them against top-seeded New Jersey, and 
the Penguins seemed destined for their third straight first-round 
elimination. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jagr delivered a gutsy effort in Game 6, returning from a  
four-game layoff with a groin injury to score the tying goal late 
in regulation and the winner in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins won Game 7 in New Jersey to reach the second round  
for the first time since 1996. They won Game 1 in Toronto and were 
up 2-1 in the series, only to lose Game 4 at home in overtime. They 
didn't win again, losing the final three games of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``This group, at any point during the season, could have latched  
onto a reason to not do well,'' coach Kevin Constantine said. 
``They refused to ever latch on to a real, legitimate excuse, 
because they wanted to win a Stanley Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins wrote a memorable chapter in their intriguing  
history this season. Too bad for them it was Chapter 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Guide Fired for Commentary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A volunteer guide at the Los Angeles County  
Museum of Art was fired for the way she explained to a group of 
10-year-old girls a sculpture depicting beer and sex in the back 
seat of a Dodge. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie Riseley said Wednesday she had described the piece  
precisely the same way for five years and never got any complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Riseley gave a tour in March to fifth-graders from Hurley  
Elementary School in Visalia, a farm community 150 miles north of 
Los Angeles. The Edward Kienholz artwork ``Back Seat Dodge '38,'' 
crafted from a real 1938 Dodge and featuring the life-size figures 
of a man and woman in a drunken sexual embrace, was part of the 
tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since this particular piece of art is an expression of an  
artist's first sexual experience, I assumed it was my job to make 
sense of it,'' Ms. Riseley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Riseley explained to the children that the woman in the  
sculpture is faceless and the man is made of chicken wire to 
signify the empty feeling of the moment. Beer bottles surround the 
couple. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she asked the children to look at their reflections in the  
car's mirrors to understand what she said was Kienholz's message: 
``That you only get one first sexual experience, so think before 
you act. Make it meaningful, make it special, make it beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The girls' chaperones and teacher were stunned. On their return  
to Visalia, they complained to Principal Doug Bartsch. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote museum officials to protest that the artwork and Ms.  
Riseley's commentary were inappropriate for his students. Bartsch 
said his school has a ``very enlightened sex education program, but 
the trip to the museum wasn't part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's docent committee agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``You have followed your self-appointed role as a teacher of  
subjects such as sex education which may be consistent with your 
agenda, but it is not consistent with your role as a docent,'' the 
committee said in an April 28 letter notifying Ms. Riseley of her 
firing. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum was closed Wednesday, and nobody returned a telephone  
message seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I became a docent after the 1992 riots. I said to myself,  
someone has to come forward and do something. People were moving 
away,'' said Ms. Riseley, a writer. ``I love Los Angeles and I love 
that museum.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:52:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gambling Panel Mulls Donation Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal commission studying gambling  
approaches its final meeting with a major issue still up in the 
air: whether to recommend a ban on campaign contributions from the 
gambling industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Gambling Impact Study Commission may urge all  
states with legal gambling to emulate New Jersey, which prohibits 
casino companies, employees and other ``agents'' from giving money 
to candidates for state office or to political committees. 
</P>
<P>
	Gambling interests have become prodigious givers on the state  
and federal levels. The National Institute on Money in State 
Politics says that in 10 states it has studied so far, gambling 
interests gave more than $1.5 million in the 1997-98 election 
cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission member Richard Leone, a former New Jersey state  
treasurer who proposed the ban, said the gambling industry should 
``bend over backwards to appear not to be buying their way into the 
business or into licenses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner William Bible, former chairman of the Nevada gaming  
control board, opposes the idea. He said it would unfairly single 
out one industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue will be resolved when the commission meets for the  
last time on June 2 and 3 in San Francisco. On June 18, the 
commission finishes two years of work by delivering a report on the 
impact of legalized gambling to Congress, the White House, state 
governors and Native American tribal leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Concluding a two-day meeting in Washington on Tuesday, the  
commission decided to recommend that governments require ``gambling 
impact statements'' -- akin to the environmental impact statements 
required of developers -- before approving new or additional 
casinos, slot machines or lotteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Robert Loescher, an Alaska businessman, objected to  
the idea as anti-business. ``This becomes a holdup. This becomes a 
delay,'' Loescher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner John Wilhelm, general president of the Hotel  
Employees and Restaurant Employees Union, agreed that the 
statements would slow the approval process. But he added: ``I don't 
think that's bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also discussed, but tabled, a rebuke of American  
Indian casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	Most tribes that run casinos refused to fill out a commission  
survey because they said the information requested was private. 
Members of the commission opted not to subpoena the information but 
promised to make clear their displeasure in the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm one of those who believe you don't always hide behind the  
law,'' said commissioner Paul Moore, a Mississippi radiologist and 
neighbor of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission considered a recommendation calling for creation  
of a new panel, ``with full subpoena power,'' to look specifically 
at Indian gambling. The idea was discarded after Loescher, an 
Indian, objected to singling out tribal casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	Among commission recommendations approved for the report:  
</P>
<P>
	--Automated teller machines should be banned from the area where  
betting takes place at casinos or race tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	--State lotteries should not move into casino-style instant games  
such as slot machines and video poker. 
</P>
<P>
	--States should not allow casino-style gambling to be introduced  
at horse tracks or other pari-mutuel facilities for the primary 
purpose of bailing out economically strapped facilities or 
competing with other forms of gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	--States should stop the proliferation of ``convenience  
gambling'' outlets, such as video gambling machines in neighborhood 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	--So-called ``cruises to nowhere'' should be prohibited unless  
states from which the boats originate specifically allow them by 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress should amend truth-in-advertising laws to cover  
American Indian gambling and state lotteries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
