<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nobelist To Lead Astrobiology Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) -- Nobelist Baruch S. Blumberg is joining  
the search for life in outer space. 
</P>
<P>
	Blumberg, who won the 1976 prize for physiology and medicine,  
was named Tuesday as the first director of NASA's Astrobiology 
Institute, based here at the Ames Research Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Best known for his work in developing the hepatitis B vaccine,  
Blumberg is a senior researcher at Fox Chase Cancer Center in 
Philadelphia and a professor of medicine and anthropology at the 
University of Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Blumberg should bring ``powerful and committed leadership'' to  
the search for life in outer space, said space agency head Daniel 
Goldin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are extremely fortunate to have a person of his  
scholarship, experience and accomplishment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Educated at Columbia University, where he received his medical  
degree, Blumberg later received a doctorate in biochemistry at 
Oxford. He previously taught biology at Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astrobiology Institute, formed last year, ties together  
researchers at NASA centers, universities and elsewhere. Its 
researchers study not only the possibility of alien life but how 
life began and evolved on Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	The institute will provide the ``intellectual underpinnings''  
for building new types of instruments and space probes for 
``finding if there is a thread of life beyond Earth,'' Goldin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
