<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ultrasound Found To Help Tendinitis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ultrasound treatment can give short-term relief to people with  
painful tendinitis in the shoulder, a study found. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, published in Thursday's New England Journal of  
Medicine, looked at the effectiveness of ultrasound in breaking 
down the calcium deposits in the rotator cuff that cause shoulder 
tendinitis. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoulder tendinitis affects hundreds of thousands of Americans  
and is most common among people between 30 and 60. Women and people 
with sedentary jobs appear to be at higher risk. In some cases, 
tendinitis can become chronic, causing pain even when the shoulder 
is at rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultrasound -- inaudible, high-frequency vibrations created by  
converting electricity into sound waves -- is widely used to treat 
the condition, but its effectiveness had not been widely tested 
until now. 
</P>
<P>
	Other treatments include anti-inflammatory drugs, surgery to  
remove the calcium, physical therapy, or use of a needle to extract 
the calcium. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gerold R. Ebenbichler and colleagues from the University  
Hospital of Vienna conducted a study in which 32 patients received 
ultrasound for 15 minutes at a time in 24 sessions over six weeks, 
while 29 other people received a sham treatment -- essentially, no 
treatment at all. 
</P>
<P>
	After six weeks, the calcium deposits had cleared up in 19  
percent of those who got ultrasound, and 28 percent had less pain 
and more mobility. Of those who got the sham treatment, calcium 
deposits cleared in none and 10 percent had less pain and greater 
range of motion. 
</P>
<P>
	At a follow-up visit nine months later, the calcium deposits had  
cleared in 42 percent of those who got ultrasound and 8 percent of 
those had the sham treatment. But the difference in pain relief and 
mobility between the two groups had all but disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	In an accompanying editorial, Drs. Cathy A. Speed and Brian L.  
Hazleman of Addenbrooke's Hospital in Cambridge, England, said the 
study failed to show whether ultrasound should be the preferred 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our recommendation is that it be used only in patients with  
severe symptoms, in conjunction with other treatments,'' they 
wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
