<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tries Again To Deport Demjanjuk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The U.S. Justice Department renewed its 22-year  
legal campaign to strip John Demjanjuk of U.S. citizenship and 
deport him Wednesday, alleging again that the retired autoworker 
was a Nazi death camp guard during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is the longest-running attempt by the U.S. government  
to revoke an alleged Nazi's citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit filed in federal court seeks to strip citizenship from  
the 79-year-old Demjanjuk, who was sentenced to die in Israel in 
1988 as the infamous death-camp guard ``Ivan the Terrible'' but was 
freed in 1993 when evidence indicated he was a victim of mistaken 
identity. 
</P>
<P>
	The government was criticized by a U.S. appellate court for  
``reckless'' withholding of evidence that might have cleared 
Demjanjuk in the earlier case. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Justice Department's Nazi-hunting Office of Special  
Investigations wins the latest case, it will then try to have 
Demjanjuk deported, said Myron Marlin, a department spokesman. But 
where Demjanjuk would be sent is unknown, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``John Demjanjuk does not deserve American citizenship and has  
no business living in this country,'' said Neal Sher, who headed 
the OSI from 1983 to 1994 and is now chief of staff of the 
International Commission on Holocaust Era Insurance Claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Tigar, Demjanjuk's attorney, said: ``Twenty-two years  
ago they sued Mr. Demjanjuk. It took 21 years, and all of his 
assets, to prove that the government was wrong. Now we'll try to 
show once again the Department of Justice doesn't have it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he is ordered deported, he would get to pick what country he  
would go to, but it would be up to that country to decide whether 
to take him. 
</P>
<P>
	However, any country that wants to bring a criminal case against  
Demjanjuk can ask at any time for his extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	The department wouldn't comment on whether Demjanjuk could face  
trial in another country. 
</P>
<P>
	The new lawsuit drops the charge that Demjanjuk was Ivan the  
Terrible. But it alleges that he was a guard at the Sobibor 
extermination camp in Nazi-occupied Poland and at the Majdanek and 
Flossenburg concentration camps. It also accuses him of serving in 
the Nazi SS-run Trawniki unit that participated in a campaign to 
annihilate the Jews of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli courts have already heard all or most of these  
allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Israeli Justice Ministry spokeswoman Orit Shemesh  
declined to comment on the case, saying the issue is for the U.S. 
courts to decide. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Israel would extradite Demjanjuk again, Elan  
Steinberg, executive director World Jewish Congress in New York, 
said: ``I doubt very much whether it would happen as a matter of 
practical reality because of the wrenching effect of the previous 
extradition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Demjanjuk was born in Ukraine, which was then part of the Soviet  
Union. He has denied serving as a guard in any concentration or 
death camp. He has said he was a Soviet Red Army soldier who spent 
most of the war in a German prison camp. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, Demjanjuk was accused of being Ivan the Terrible, a  
guard who operated a gas chamber at the Treblinka extermination 
camp. His U.S. citizenship was revoked in 1981 and five years later 
he was extradited to Israel for trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite overturning his conviction in the Ivan the Terrible  
case, the Israeli Supreme Court said it was convinced Demjanjuk had 
worked for the Nazis during the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	Demjanjuk returned to the United States in 1993, the same year a  
federal appeals court ruled the U.S. government had withheld 
evidence that might have cleared him. 
</P>
<P>
	A relative of Demjanjuk's noted the government's previous  
mishandling of the case and said the latest charges are old and 
lack credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're just reshuffling the deck and throwing cards at him  
again,'' said Ed Nishnic, Demjanjuk's son-in-law. ``Hopefully, it 
will not take another 22 years to clear his name once again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since returning to the United States, Demjanjuk has lived  
quietly in suburban Cleveland. His citizenship was restored in 
February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish groups across the country praised the lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everything we can do to bring an SS man to justice is fair,  
particularly when we look at the unfairness and unjust manner in 
which they conducted themselves in the death camps,'' said Rabbi 
Marvin Hier, founder of Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
