<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Aims for Philly Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A onetime fiery liberal activist bested a  
crowd of Democrats in his bid to become this city's second black 
mayor, and now faces a well-known Republican financial consultant 
in the final election. 
</P>
<P>
	John F. Street, the former City Council president who over the  
years went from liberal activist to financial conservative, should 
have an edge in this heavily Democratic city. For every two 
registered Republicans, there are seven Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	To have any chance of beating Street, Republican Sam Katz must  
capture roughly three out of every five Democratic voters along 
with the Republican vote. 
</P>
<P>
	That means going after the white rowhouse neighborhoods -- the  
folks who in the primary supported failed Democratic candidate 
Marty Weinberg. 
</P>
<P>
	But Katz, who made his fortune as a financial adviser to  
governments across the country, said he plans to appeal to all 
voters in all neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intend to make my candidacy attractive to all Philadelphians  
without regard to race, without regard to gender or ethnicity or 
(party) registration,'' he said while greeting the lunchtime crowd 
at the historic Reading Terminal Market. 
</P>
<P>
	His message -- lower wage taxes, strong schools and safe streets  
-- will be the same for all communities in the city, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Street asked his Democratic primary opponents to  
lunch Wednesday with the idea that they would unite behind his 
candidacy. Only one showed up, and not Weinberg, a longtime 
political powerbroker and Street's closest competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinberg's campaign stressed Street's younger and more hotheaded  
days, running ads with TV footage of Street shoving a reporter and 
throwing a cup of water on a police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	With 97 percent of precincts reporting, Street had 35.5 percent  
of the vote, or 100,597 votes, to Marty Weinberg's 31.2 percent, or 
88,564 votes. The rest were split among lesser-known Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Street, 55, said he plans to ask Weinberg ``to do his fair share  
to bring this party and this city together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katz, who served as a city school board member and made failed  
primary runs for mayor in 1991 and governor in 1994, helped develop 
retiring Mayor Edward G. Rendell's recovery plan in 1992, when the 
city was near bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell, a popular Democrat who is credited with bringing the  
nation's fifth-largest city back from the brink of financial ruin, 
is barred from seeking a third consecutive term. He endorsed 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz took in $2.2 million and spent only $941,000 for the  
primary, leaving him well-positioned for the campaign for the Nov. 
3 election. Street raised and spent much of his $3.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz, 49, is fond of pointing out that the nation's two largest  
cities, the longtime Democratic strongholds of New York and Los 
Angeles, elected Republican mayors in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia's voters haven't elected a Republican mayor in more  
than 50 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
