<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Airways Shareholders OK Bonuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- US Airways Group Inc. shareholders on  
Wednesday approved a management incentive pay plan giving top 
executives up to 500 percent of their base salary in bonuses. But 
chairman Stephen Wolf said he was withdrawing from the plan in 
response to a letter from a flight attendants union leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf told the company's annual shareholders meeting he and US  
Airways president Rakesh Gangwal agreed not to participate in the 
incentive plan after Lynn Lenosky, president of the US Airways 
chapter of the Association of Flight Attendants, wrote that the 
plan's approval ``can have a detrimental effect on employee morale 
and productivity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf told approximately 350 shareholders, ``We considered it an  
issue that could lead to divisiveness in the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Wolf also said he believes the plan was necessary to recruit  
and retain top managers. Under the plan, top executives can receive 
up to 500 percent of their base salary in bonuses if US Airways 
meets certain performance goals. 
</P>
<P>
	By not participating in the plan, Wolf and Gangwal will each  
forgo about $1.3 million in bonuses. Wolf's base salary is 
currently $580,000, while Gangwal's base salary is $566,538. 
</P>
<P>
	The overwhelming shareholder approval came despite complaints  
from union members, who argued that salaries of the company's 
41,000 employees stagnated for years while management's 
compensation skyrocketed. Shareholders holding about 63 million 
shares approved the plan, while those holding fewer than 3.8 
million opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the speakers at the meeting was a passenger service  
employee at Charlotte-Douglas International Airport who said his 
pay and pension have been frozen for six years. During that time, 
the only way he could support his wife and three children was to 
work a great deal of overtime, Danny Carter said, breaking down in 
tears. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf seemed genuinely moved by the comments.  
</P>
<P>
	``You have not been compensated at a fair level for a number of  
years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines' 9,000 flight attendants have not had a  
cost-of-living raise since 1996, and they are working under a 
contract that came up for renewal that year. The 10,000 ticket and 
gate agents have not had a cost-of-living raise since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, flight attendants have complained that US Airways  
paid Wolf $34.2 million and Gangwal $36 million during 1998, making 
each executive more highly paid than the CEOs of American, United 
and Delta combined. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf defended his compensation, saying that most of it comes in  
stock options. He received 37 percent less than comparable 
executives at United, Delta and American in actual cash salary and 
bonuses, Wolf said. The company offered him and Gangwal stock 
options as an enticement to retain them, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members say they are entitled to more compensation after a  
four-year-period when the airline earned profits of $2.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite saying it would move quickly to resolve labor issues  
after reaching a historic contract settlement with its 4,800 pilots 
in October 1997, US Airways has signed only one major contract 
since then, with its fleet service workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The slow pace is not unique. Seven of the 10 largest U.S.  
airlines are negotiating contracts, and some have been at it for 
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 05:52:19 </DATE_TIME>
