<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Correct New Stadium Defects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Structural defects found in five places in the  
new Cleveland Browns stadium were minor, and did not threaten the 
$283 million structure, Mayor Michael R. White said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspectors found the problems in five of 1,000 joints in the  
stadium where steel beams attach to concrete or steel columns. 
Contractors were paying to add bolts to improve support and fix the 
problems, he said. The cost was not known. 
</P>
<P>
	``These deficiencies are not considered unusual nor are they a  
safety hazard,'' White said during a news conference at the 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	City Council President Jay Westbrook said some bolts had sheared  
off. 
</P>
<P>
	Councilman Bill W. Patmon, who worked in construction for 15  
years, said sheared bolts could be a serious problem. He also said 
if the bolts were flawed because of improper heat treatment, the 
problem easily could be corrected. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Fratianni, project manager for construction company Huber  
Hunt &AMP; Nichols, said the problems were typical of large-scale 
projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of these presented imminent danger,'' he said. ``These  
are things that needed follow-up but not things that threaten 
lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Project managers said several inspectors check the stadium's  
construction regularly. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction on the 72,000-seat stadium is about 85 percent  
complete. The stadium is expected to open on time in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns play their first regular-season game at home Sept. 12  
against the rival Pittsburgh Steelers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
