<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sabres, Leafs: Great Lakes Showdown / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Many Toronto sports fans have a soft spot for  
Buffalo, a small-market city with Canadian-style winters, just 100 
miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Temporarily, though, the Peace Bridge that links Buffalo to  
Ontario may need another name. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time ever, the beloved hockey teams of Toronto and  
Buffalo are facing each other in a playoff series, with a berth in 
the Stanley Cup finals at stake. Players on both teams agree: Leafs 
vs. Sabres is a classic rivalry waiting for ignition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to start writing some history now,'' said Sabres  
forward Dixon Ward after his team advanced over Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eastern Conference championship series opens Sunday in  
Toronto; it will be the Sabres' first visit to the new Air Canada 
Centre. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the matchup was determined, the Canadian media dubbed  
it the ``QEW Series'' after Queen Elizabeth Way, the highway 
linking Toronto to the Buffalo-Niagara Falls region. 
</P>
<P>
	With the two arenas only two hours apart, large numbers of fans  
-- including some without tickets for the sold-out games -- are 
expected to drive to other city to support their team on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to lock our doors over here because of all the  
Leafs fans coming over,'' said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff. ``It should 
be mayhem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series has an extra dimension for Sabres players such as  
Jason Woolley and captain Michael Peca, raised as Leafs fans in 
Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Peca saw TV footage of Toronto fans celebrating in the streets  
Monday night after the Leafs eliminated Pittsburgh, and he recalled 
joining similar revelry as a fan six years ago when Toronto won a 
playoff series over Detroit with an overtime goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was me. ... I was that guy honking the horns and cheering  
the Leafs on,'' Peca said. ``It's going to be fun being one of the 
guys trying to upset those people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Leafs, it's the first time in the Stanley Cup's final  
four since 1994. Toronto hasn't won the cup since 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have never won the cup, although this is their second  
straight appearance in the Eastern Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo is often depicted sympathetically in the Canadian media  
as a Canadian-style sports city, faced with the same small-market 
challenges -- and often brutal winter weather -- that beset places 
like Edmonton and Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buffalo Bills of the National Football League are covered  
like a hometown team by the Toronto media, a phenomenon that has 
intensified since the Bills gave their quarterback job to longtime 
Canadian Football League superstar Doug Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres and Leafs met five times during the regular season,  
with Buffalo winning three but losing the last two. The Leafs, the 
NHL's highest-scoring team, outshot the Sabres 163-119 in those 
games, yet were outscored 17-10, thanks to the goaltending of 
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	The main reason the teams haven't met in the playoffs previously  
is that the Leafs, until this season, played in the Western 
Conference. The series with Buffalo is just the sort of showdown 
the Leafs' brass hoped for when they finally won their bid to move 
into the same conference with such natural rivals as Buffalo, 
Montreal, Boston and Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be pretty intense,'' said Leafs president Ken Dryden.  
``We want rivalries, and rivalries get spawned in playoff series.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:32:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise Despite Inflation Worry / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices recovered Wednesday after several  
days of being shaken by fears of higher inflation rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 1/16  
point, or $10.63 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.80 percent from 5.88 percent 
late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to up 1/32 point, and intermediate maturities were 
up 1/8 point to 7/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first strong showing for Treasury bonds since the  
market got hit by inflation jitters on Friday following a report of 
an unexpectedly high rise in consumer prices. Bonds also swooned 
briefly Tuesday afternoon after the Federal Reserve said it would 
lean toward raising interest rates in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	But the long bond ended the day higher Tuesday, and the gains  
continued Wednesday as buyers returned to the market hopeful that 
the overall benign outlook for inflation will remain in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount fell 0.04 percentage point to 4.48 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.76 percent, as the discount fell 0.06 percentage 
point to 4.58 percent. One-year yields were 4.86 percent as the 
discount fell by 0.03 percentage point from late Tuesday to 4.63 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.50 percent from 4.64 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 9/32 to 122 1/32. The average yield to 
maturity fell to 5.36 percent from 5.38 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 03:12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Student Drinking Policy in Mass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- The state Board of Higher Education has  
voted to require Massachusetts public universities to notify 
parents when their underage children are caught with alcohol on 
campus. 
</P>
<P>
	Board members unanimously approved the policy Tuesday, saying  
they hope to reduce repeat offenses and enhance public safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just makes good sense,'' said Chancellor Stanley Koplik.  
``Parents want to know when there's been behavior by their on or 
daughter that will jeopardize the academic career and certainly the 
public safety of the individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recent changes in federal law allow colleges to tell parents of  
violations by underage students. Before the change last year, many 
institutions feared they would violate privacy regulations if they 
told parents about their children's drug and alcohol use. 
</P>
<P>
	The change followed several high-profile drinking deaths like  
those at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Louisiana 
State in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first colleges to take advantage of the new policy,  
the University of Delaware, sent letters last fall to 1,414 parents 
whose under-21 children had violated campus regulations. Sine then, 
the campus has recorded a decline in repeat offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown University, Clemson University, Lafayette College and  
Indiana University are among the other schools that have adopted 
similar notification policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
