<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:31:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Peacekeeping Mission Changing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The military mission that the Clinton  
administration originally envisioned for NATO in implementing a 
Kosovo peace accord is taking on a new look. The ground force would 
be much larger, and some allies think it ought to be prepared to 
move even before Belgrade signs on to a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	If peacekeepers moved in early, they might face scattered  
resistance from remnant Serb forces, the Pentagon says. 
</P>
<P>
	The intent is still to use this multinational force to implement  
a peace, not launch a ground war. But as NATO's Operation Allied 
Force entered its ninth week Wednesday, alliance and U.S. officials 
said questions remain on how soon the peacekeeping force should be 
assembled and when it should enter Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The timing is important because of the degree of risk and cost  
entailed in various options, and because NATO wants to end the 
conflict and get the hundreds of thousands of displaced ethnic 
Albanians in Macedonia and Albania back into their villages in 
Kosovo under NATO protection before the onset of winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, there are going to be (NATO) ground troops of some  
type'' in Kosovo, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. The issue 
is whether they should be prepared to enter Kosovo without the 
consent of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, once Serb forces 
are too battered to offer much resistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. position remains that ``we need an agreement or a U.N.  
Security Council resolution'' first, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, however, Bacon said it was possible that an  
international peacekeeping force could enter Kosovo without 
Milosevic's consent. ``You don't have to have an agreement to do 
that,'' Bacon said on Monday, so long as the Serb forces simply 
stopped the violence in Kosovo and withdrew from the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally, NATO estimated it would need 28,000 peacekeepers, of  
which about 4,000 were to be American. Now it figures it might take 
50,000, of which the United States may contribute 7,000 to 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	British officials have argued in recent days that NATO should be  
preparing for an early entry into Kosovo, given the increasing 
damage NATO airstrikes are inflicting on the hunkered down Serb 
army in the Serb province. British Air Marshal Sir John Day told 
reporters in London on Wednesday that NATO has seriously degraded 
Serb air defenses, fuel resources, lines of communication and 
fielded forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO's air campaign has already significantly eroded the  
military capability of Milosevic's war machine, and it is being 
further reduced as each day goes by,'' Day said. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, due in Washington on  
Thursday for talks with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, said 
NATO should be ready to move quickly with ground forces to protect 
refugees once Serb forces are sufficiently devastated. ``The issue 
of judgment that needs to be made is at what point in the end game 
would it be appropriate, would it be safe, would it be right, for 
troops to enter,'' he said in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said Wednesday that the U.S. military could move its  
portion of a peacekeeping force into the area ``in days.'' He noted 
that 6,000 U.S. troops already are in Albania and NATO has about 
13,000 troops in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton stirred speculation about U.S. policy when he  
said Tuesday that no option should be ruled out on the use of 
ground troops, although he also said NATO should continue on its 
present course of airstrikes. Previously, Clinton had said he had 
no intention of introducing ground troops into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Chief of Staff Gen. Dennis Reimer was asked about Clinton's  
remark at a Senate hearing Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he said is that ground forces are still an option on the  
table, under the right set of conditions,'' Reimer said. Yet to be 
determined is what that ``right set of conditions'' will be. 
</P>
<P>
	At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, spokesman Jamie Shea  
said Wednesday the alliance is focusing on plans for a peacekeeping 
force in Kosovo, to be dubbed Operation Joint Guardian, not a 
ground war. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to send ground forces to fight in Kosovo, but  
as a peace force,'' Shea said. He said NATO was ``pushing this as a 
matter of priority'' because it does not want to leave a security 
vacuum in Kosovo if Serb forces suddenly give up and withdraw from 
the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us in the alliance share a sense of urgency that when  
Milosevic finally puts up his hand and says, 'I accept (NATO's) 
conditions,' we have to be ready with a peace implementation force 
to enter Kosovo rapidly,'' Shea said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Expects Fall Budget Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the Senate Appropriations  
Committee predicted another autumn budget clash between Congress 
and President Clinton on Tuesday as congressional leaders prepared 
plans for cutting domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're heading for a collision that will take us to  
September,'' Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, told reporters. ``It's a 
bad, bad scene.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens also predicted that because of spending cuts his  
committee will propose in bills covering environment, health and 
other programs, the Republican-controlled Congress will reject many 
of the measures unless more money is provided. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can we get the bills passed? No, we can't get the bills  
passed,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens' remarks placed him among a small number of Republicans  
who have publicly said that ultimately, Congress will have to 
exceed spending limits imposed by the 1997 budget-balancing deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans have said privately that Stevens' spending  
plans and a similar proposal by the House Appropriations Committee 
are purposely designed to convince GOP leaders and colleagues that 
more money is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	All year, Republicans have said they want to avoid a replay of  
last fall's spending battle with Clinton, when he forced them to 
provide billions of dollars more in spending than they wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens spoke after delivering a similar message to GOP senators  
in a closed-door lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, his committee intends to approve plans for dividing  
up $538 billion among 13 spending bills for the coming fiscal year, 
measures that finance all government agencies. That is billions 
below 1999 levels, forced by the two-year-old budget deal, which 
imposed increasing annual cuts in such programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a similar House blueprint, Stevens' proposal would provide  
billions of dollars less this year for bills financing health, 
education, housing, environmental and other domestic programs, 
while adding billions to defense spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants increases, not cuts, for many of those programs.  
</P>
<P>
	Publicly, GOP leaders insist Congress will abide by the spending  
limits. In part, that is because money to increase the spending 
would have to come either from Social Security's surpluses or by 
reducing funds available for a tax cut Republicans want, both of 
which would infuriate conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	In defense of their position, top Republicans have begun noting  
that Clinton and congressional Democratic leaders have produced 
their own budgets that abide by the spending limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't think of any point on which there seems to be ... more  
universal commitment,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, 
R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens said GOP leaders would have to find a solution to the  
spending problem or fall prey to numerous Democratic amendments 
designed to embarrass Republicans for cutting programs during a 
time of federal surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about who controls the Senate,'' Stevens said.  
</P>
<P>
	Separately, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., acknowledged  
that he was beginning to address the spending problem in his 
chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to vent this,'' he said in an interview, adding that  
his lieutenants would conduct ``a listening session with members so 
we know what their feelings are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990519.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 06:22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kmart Announces $1B Stock Buyback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Kmart Corp.'s years of retrenchment are over, and  
the nation's No. 3 retailer plans to add 30 to 50 stores a year as 
it rides the growth in the discount retail business, chief 
executive Floyd Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall also told shareholders at their annual meeting Tuesday that  
the company will buy back $1 billion in stock over the next several 
years, a response to what he said is the serious undervaluing of 
its shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like you, we are frustrated that our stock price is  
undervalued by many in the financial community,'' Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that its price-earnings ratio is about half the average  
of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the market isn't interested in buying, you can be sure that  
we are,'' he said. ``Kmart is taking this dramatic action today as 
evidence of our strong confidence in the growth and future 
performance of this company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, chairman since June 1995, presented shareholders with a  
glowing overview of the company's recent performance. He noted that 
the company: 
</P>
<P>
	--Has posted 12 consecutive quarters of earnings increases,  
thanks partly to strong private merchandise sales from Martha 
Stewart, Sesame Street and Jaclyn Smith lines. 
</P>
<P>
	--Has refurbished all of its stores within the last three and a  
half years, freeing up cash for renewed expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Will complete the conversion of traditional Kmart stores to Big  
Kmart stores, with a year-end total of more than 1,850 Big Kmarts 
in the chain. 
</P>
<P>
	In answer to one shareholder's question, he said Kmart was  
interested in finding a national retail chain to help it expand its 
grocery offerings. He said the company has been discussing the 
project with potential partners, which he did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	Troy-based Kmart is the nation's third-largest retailer, behind  
Wal-Mart and Sears Roebuck and Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had earnings last year of $518 million on sales of  
$33.7 billion. Kmart has 2,162 stores in all 50 states, Puerto 
Rico, Guam and the Virgin Islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
