<DOCNO> APW19990519.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:33:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Regulators Warn Olivetti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Italy's stock market regulator warned  
Olivetti SpA to stick to the facts in statements about its hostile 
bid for Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Consob's warning followed a complaint to the agency by Telecom  
Italia, which said statements attributed to an adviser to Olivetti 
could improperly influence the outcome of the takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $65 billion for Telecom Italia in a tender  
offer that ends Friday. If successful, it would be the largest 
hostile corporate takeover in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has said it needs to garner at least 35 percent of  
Telecom Italia's ordinary capital to even consider proceeding with 
the bid. At 67 percent or more, Olivetti is obliged to take up the 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian news agency Radiocor quoted an adviser to Olivetti  
CEO Roberto Colannino as saying it appeared the subscription rate 
already had passed the 35 percent mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia said that kind of statement violates the rules of  
correctness and transparency in that it influences subscription to 
the takeover bid. It could alter the price of financial instruments 
of both Olivetti and Telecom Italia with partial and undocumented 
information, Telecom Italia said. 
</P>
<P>
	Consob ordered Olivetti to ``immediately release any information  
it has, or its advisers have, on funds that have asked their 
brokers to tender their shares to Olivetti.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti also must ``abstain from spreading information about  
the bid that is not backed up by hard data, isn't verifiable and is 
only based on the calculations of analysts,'' the regulatory agency 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Milan stock market Wednesday, Telecom stocks rallied on  
investor sentiment that Olivetti has a good change of winning the 
bid for the former telephone monopoly. 

</P>
</TEXT>
