<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missed Free Throws Risk Pacers Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers couldn't hit their free  
throws and couldn't inbound the ball to Reggie Miller. In the final 
minute of Game 2 against Philadelphia, it almost cost them dearly. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite missing six free throws in the final 67 seconds, Indiana  
survived a late charge by Philadelphia for the second consecutive 
game and defeated the 76ers 85-82 Wednesday night to take a 2-0 
lead in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who led the NBA in free throw accuracy during the  
regular season, never touched the ball during that 67-second span. 
</P>
<P>
	``We like to get the ball to Reggie in those situations, but if  
it's not available, you get it to someone else,'' Indiana coach 
Larry Bird said. ``Guys have to step up and make their shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana led 81-73 with 55.2 seconds to go after a basket by Dale  
Davis. After Philadelphia scored, Mark Jackson was fouled and 
missed two attempts with 40.9 seconds to go. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson redeemed himself by hitting two free throws with 32.9  
seconds left, giving Indiana an 83-77 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Snow cut Indiana's deficit to three by hitting a 3-pointer,  
and Indiana failed to lock up the victory as Derrick McKey and 
Jalen Rose each missed one of two from the line in the final 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as in Game 1, the 76ers' full-court press in the final  
minute seemed to befuddle the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reggie's our best free throw shooter. They put two guys on  
him, double-teaming him. They weren't going to let him beat them,'' 
Davis said. ``And they were also being physical with him. We didn't 
want to try a risky pass just to get the ball to him and wind up 
turning it over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The missed free throws down the stretch were unusual for the  
Pacers, who won the Central Division championship while leading the 
league in free throw accuracy at 79.6 percent. Miller led the 
league at 91.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Free throws are always real big down the stretch. This is  
uncharacteristic for us. We usually do a better job, especially 
Mark,'' Smits said. ``I don't remember him ever missing two in a 
row.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers won with key contributions from several players.  
Smits scored 25 points, shooting 12-of-23 from the field. Miller 
scored 17, Dale Davis helped Indiana outrebound the 76ers 49-42 by 
pulling down 14 and Jackson had 14 assists while doing much of the 
defensive work against league scoring leader Allen Iverson, who 
scored 23 points but was 7-of-28 from the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very disturbing that we blew big leads two games in a  
row, but it was get to get two wins,'' Smits said. ``We seem to 
play well the first half and somehow the tone changes and we let 
things slip away.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
