<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Opens Sculpture Garden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's been 33 years in the making, but a  
sculpture garden first proposed when Lyndon Johnson was president 
was finally dedicated today, its 17 works of modern art promising a 
tree-shaded respite for museum-fatigued tourists on the National 
Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	The garden ``makes a powerful statement that art should be  
accessible to all people,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton said at the 
dedication of the garden, which opens to the public Sunday at the 
height of tourist season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1960s' Johnson administration plans to lay out the garden  
for the National Gallery of Art were abandoned long ago, after a 
circular pond that doubles as a wintertime skating rink was 
finished. 
</P>
<P>
	``The skating rink was put in first, but then someone thought it  
wasn't dignified to combine art with a skating rink, and we 
couldn't get money from Congress to do the garden,'' said J. Carter 
Brown, chairman of Washington's Fine Arts Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of delay, the garden was built by a $10 million  
grant from the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz Foundation, a 
Washington philanthropy that is also buying seven of the 10 new 
works to be exhibited. Other sculptures will come from the 
gallery's present collection or from private donations. Taxpayer 
money will go to operate and maintain the garden, as it does for 
the gallery. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation's current chairman, Calvin Cafritz, said his late  
parents would get ``great joy'' from seeing their 
great-grandchildren and other children ``romp through the garden'' 
and gawk at a huge, spindly spider sculpture that lurks between the 
trees in one corner. 
</P>
<P>
	New parks these days often are short on trees and shrubs, and  
even short on flowers because vandals tear them up and they are 
expensive to maintain, said Laurie D. Olin, who supervised the 
garden's landscaping. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``the National Gallery can do things right.''  
</P>
<P>
	The garden, which covers two city blocks just west of the  
gallery, has plenty of trees, shrubs and flowers, 45-foot cedars to 
pale pink geraniums in front of the gate. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no ``Keep Off the Grass'' signs, but five security  
guards will patrol the two-block area during museum hours. They 
also will have to keep visiting kids informed about which of the 17 
sculptures can or cannot be handled. No hanging from the legs of 
Louise Bourgeois' 24-foot bronze spider, for instance, and no 
climbing Sol LeWitt's ``Four-Sided Pyramid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibits will change from time to time but will be limited to  
20th-century and 21st-century work. The works at today's opening 
range from Roy Lichtenstein's ``House I,'' in the same comic-strip 
style as his paintings, to 30 three-foot bronze statues by Polish 
sculptor Magdalena Abakanowicz. Titled ``Puellae'' -- Latin for 
``Girls'' -- they refer to Polish children who froze to death in 
cattle cars during the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	The circular pool, newly enlarged, occupies the middle of the  
garden, with arching sprays of water. In the winter, the fountain 
will be turned off and new ice-making equipment will transform the 
pool into the skating rink. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-story, glass enclosed pavilion with indoor and outdoor  
seating will open in the fall as a cafe and full-service 
restaurant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
