<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Few OK Tax Money for Campaigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Not only are fewer Americans voting, but they  
also are declining to use their tax dollars to help pay for 
presidential campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: For the first time since federal financing of  
presidential elections began after the Watergate scandal, 
candidates will have to wait until the year after the election to 
get their full matching dollars, the Federal Election Commission 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Political observers say Americans are turned off by negative  
campaigning, so they stay home on Election Day and refuse to check 
the campaign financing box on their income tax returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time, people have been increasingly turned off from  
American politics,'' said Curtis Gans, director of the nonpartisan 
Committee for the Study of the American Electorate. ``They're not 
anxious to pay for the types of campaigns that we're running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only 13 percent of taxpayers in 1996, the latest year for which  
complete figures are available, agreed to earmark $3 of their taxes 
to the presidential election campaign fund. Preliminary figures for 
1997 and 1998 indicate the percentage is staying the same or even 
lower. In comparison, 29 percent checked the box in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, there will not be enough money to cover all the  
political expenses from next year's presidential election until the 
2000 income tax returns are filed in April 2001. Presidential 
candidates will get only about a third of the federal aid they are 
entitled to on Jan. 1, when the first matching funds are handed 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC expects eventually to have to pay out $99 million in  
federal matching funds to candidates running in 2000, up from $59 
million in 1996. Each candidate can receive a maximum of $16.75 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates become eligible for matching funds by raising at  
least $5,000 in 20 different states from individuals contributing 
no more than $250. In exchange, candidates agree to limit spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But first, the FEC must set aside money to pay the costs of the  
Democratic, Republican and Reform party nominating conventions, and 
the amounts required for general election candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Only then can the FEC begin making payments to the Democratic  
and Republican primary candidates. Under the law, the government 
fund matches dollar for dollar the first $250 of each individual 
contribution a qualified presidential primary candidate receives. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, a similar shortfall meant that presidential candidates  
received 60 percent of their money on Jan. 1 and the rest after 
April's tax-return filings. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who sought the GOP  
presidential nomination in 1996 and is running again in 2000, said 
candidates borrowed money to make up the difference and then paid 
it off once with they got their matching funds. He said he expected 
to do the same again next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a problem,'' Alexander said Wednesday. ``I assume it  
will be the same thing this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the percentage of Americans checking off the box on their  
tax returns has been in a steady decline, the maximum amount of 
federal dollars that candidates can qualify for continues to be 
adjusted upwards for inflation under a complex formula set up by 
the law that first created public financing for campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC annually recommends that the checkoff amount also be  
allowed to increase with inflation, but the requests have fallen on 
deaf ears in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the FEC on Thursday was to consider a staff  
recommendation that could make it easier for campaigns to raise 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC staff has proposed allowing contributions made by credit  
cards, including those made over the Internet, to be eligible for 
federal matching funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
