<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Counseled on Her Right To Die </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Hospital workers today were counseling a  
paralyzed woman -- who allegedly was shot by her mother -- to 
determine that she was certain of her decision to have life support 
removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgette Smith, 42, was still planning to have her ventilator  
removed shortly after 5 p.m., a move that could lead to murder 
charges against her mother, a hospital spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith on Tuesday won a court order granting her wish.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're ready to carry out the court order unless there would be  
a change in the patient's request,'' said Lisa Schultz, spokeswoman 
for Lucerne Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have said that if Ms. Smith dies, her 68-year-old  
mother, Shirley Egan, could be charged with murder. She already is 
charged with attempted murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ms. Smith has made a difficult choice, a choice which she has  
the right to make,'' Judge Richard Conrad ruled after visiting her 
in the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan, a frail woman who is blind in one eye, allegedly shot  
her daughter in March when she learned Ms. Smith planned to put her 
in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullet struck Ms. Smith in the neck, tearing through her  
spinal cord. It left her paralyzed from the neck down, unable to 
speak without effort, incapable of swallowing and with no control 
of her bladder. She is fed through a tube and runs a high risk of 
pneumonia, infections, ulcers and bedsores. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is wink my eyes and wiggle my nose, wiggle my  
tongue. I can't move any other part of my body,'' she said in a 
deposition. ``I can't live like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith's daughters, 22-year-old Candace Smith and 19-year-old  
Joeleen Hill, supported their mother's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan's lawyer, Bob Wesley, objected to the request to end  
life support because of the state's plan to pursue murder charges. 
However, he told the judge ``Ms. Egan does not want to see her 
daughter suffer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said Ms. Smith had one last request before she dies:  
She asked to be an organ donor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
