<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Charged in Gas Station Beating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The fatal beating of a black electrician  
allegedly at the hands of two Arab gas station clerks has revealed 
racial hostilities and prompted the formation of a task force to 
ease the tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadhel Mazeb, 46, and Adel Altam, 26, are charged with  
second-degree murder in the death of Kalvin Porter, 34, who lived 
two blocks from the Sunoco station where the defendants worked. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter's death on Friday has led to nightly protests,  
</P>
<P>
	``The African-American community has too long been the victim of  
mistreatment and disrespect by some who operate and work in stores 
and gas stations in our neighborhood,'' said the Rev. Wendell 
Anthony, president of the Detroit chapter of the NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Porter's death is a tragic example of festering problems  
of ill will and ill feelings between African-Americans and some 
Arab-Chaldean store operators,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People  
will monitor the case to ensure that justice prevails, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An interpreter read the charges Monday against Mazeb and Altam,  
both immigrants from Yemen. The defendants, who were not 
represented by an attorney, pleaded innocent and remain in custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter got into a fight with the men after one made an  
inappropriate remark to his 12-year-old stepdaughter, police said. 
They are accused of using a tire iron to beat Porter to death in 
front of his children. If convicted, they face life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole incident is very tragic to say the least. Our goal  
is to try to restore peace and tranquility as soon as possible,'' 
said Edward Deeb, an Arab-American community leader who helped 
organize the Crisis Intervention Task Force. 
</P>
<P>
	The task force hopes to hold a community forum soon where blacks  
and Arab-Americans can discuss Porter's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan is home to more than 200,000 Arab-Americans, who began  
to dominate the grocery store, liquor store and gas station 
business in Detroit when many white business owners left after the 
city's 1967 riots. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are basic economic differences between many blacks and  
Arab-American store owners, resident Rod Scott said. Blacks make up 
80 percent of Detroit's population. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't a situation like the Ku Klux Klan, where whites  
hate blacks just because of who they are,'' he said. ``A lot of the 
animosity stems from inequity. That's the undercurrent to a lot of 
these incidents. Look around -- how many black-owned grocery stores 
do you see?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jalil Saad, owner of a Detroit Mobil station, said business  
owners should train their employees to be culturally sensitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We teach our employees to interact with the customers and to  
get to know them on a personal level,'' Saad said. ``We greet them 
with a smile when they walk in and say `goodbye' when they leave.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
